amme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "cf413459ccf0ce3e9c6dca11283a4d8267f063891ca3e7416bedad3cbb11f58a"}}, "hash": "fd39e8a0e50a0eab53e27e5eafa408445ebe1e7aea31045c446bce7aa679d3e3", "text": "REBUILDING INTERNATIONAL FOOD POLICY ARCHITECTURE HUNGER BRIEFING PAPER SERIES: 2 Kirsty Hayes Biplove Choudhary UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo Serving Asia and the Pacific Acknowledgements This paper was written by Kirsty Hayes and Biplove Choudhary of the UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo (RCC), Sri Lanka. While taking full responsibility for all the views and analyses in the paper, the authors gratefully acknowledge the suggestions made by Parthapratim Pal of the Indian Institute of Management, Kolkata, on a previous version of the paper, and mem- bers of the UNDP RCC Knowledge Resource Committee, with particular thanks to Menaka Gunawardena and Manisha Mishra, for their substantive comments and editing suggestions. The beautiful photographs in this paper were taken by Jason Taylor. The authors would also like to gratefully acknowledge the participation of Lord Mark Mal- loch Brown, UK Foreign Office Minister, Supachai Panichpakdi, Secretary General of UNCTAD, Sandra Polaski, Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, Washington DC, Tim Lang, City University, London, Saman Kalegama, Institute of Policy Studies, Sri Lanka, Biswajit Dhar, WTO Centre IIFT, India and Safdar Sohail, Foreign Trade Institute of Pakistan for their partici- pation in a UNDP RCC Round Table on the theme of this paper, which contributed many fresh perspectives into the authors\u2019 thinking. Foreword In May 2008, the United Nations Development Programme Regional Centre in Colombo (UNDP RCC) and the Food and Agriculture Organisation (FAO) launched a Seven Point Agenda under their Campaign to end Hunger in the Asia Pacific region. One key agenda point is the rebuilding of international food policy architecture in order to achieve a fairer outcome for the world\u2019s poor and hungry. The world produces more than enough food to feed all its people. As far back as in 1980, the Brandt Commission noted that \u201cmankind has never before had such ample technical and financial resources for coping with hunger and poverty\u201d. The existence of so many hungry nearly three decades later, therefore, suggests a massive market failure and lack of a necessary collective will to address the immense task at hand. The UNDP RCC and FAO recognize that any new or improved global food architecture must take into account the differing interests and needs of all world regions. However, this pa- per is focused on the effects of international food policy on the Asia Pacific region, in rec- ognition of the fact that 61% of the world\u2019s hungry live in this region. This paper prepared by the UNDP RCC, forms one of a series of Hunger Briefing Papers, aimed at policy makers and other opinion formers, who may not have an academic re- search background in areas related to hunger. As such, it aims to synthesise and analyse thinking on the issue of international food policy architecture in an easily intelligible form, in order to facilitate the formulation of appropriate policy responses. The paper concludes that current international food policy architecture does not deliver for the world\u2019s poor, particularly small farmers in the Asia Pacific region. This is in large part due to distortions in patterns of trade in food products, due to the historical legacy, and re- sidual existence, of developed country subsidy, combined with the neglect of developing country agriculture by both developing countries themselves and international donors. Moreover, international food policy has been approached as primarily a trade issue, rather than considering the broader elements of food production, including climate change. The paper also concludes that food cannot be treated in the same manner as other traded com- modities because of the human right to food, and the human impact of adjustment shocks. Additionally, imperfections in agricultural markets make price transmission mechanisms ineffective, especially for small farmers. The paper calls for the rebuilding of international food policy architecture to provide a fairer deal for Asia\u2019s poor and hungry. Omar Noman Chief, Policies and Programmes UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo C O N T E N T S Introduction 1 What is the link between international food policy architecture and hunger? 2 Why have developing countries captured so little share of the international food exports market? 6 International agricultural trade policy architecture - An Overview 8 How do agricultural markets react to pricing signals?", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "bbcf3b53-48ae-4851-95fb-02baa5a2cbe8": {"__data__": {"id_": "bbcf3b53-48ae-4851-95fb-02baa5a2cbe8", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a92556f54ef17cffd07cacd1998c6e7817af67153ac4dc074ad5020112f2bea2"}, "2": {"node_id": "02ea6d62-d7f1-44e8-b89f-bce2b582274b", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fd39e8a0e50a0eab53e27e5eafa408445ebe1e7aea31045c446bce7aa679d3e3"}}, "hash": "cf413459ccf0ce3e9c6dca11283a4d8267f063891ca3e7416bedad3cbb11f58a", "text": "6 International agricultural trade policy architecture - An Overview 8 How do agricultural markets react to pricing signals? 10 The Doha Round: Prospects for further liberalization and current market distortions 14 The role of Regional Trade Agreements (RTAs) and Preferential Trading Agreements (PTAs) 18 Non-trade elements of international food policy architecture 19 Potential linkages of the 2008 Global Recessionary trends on hunger 21 Diverse solutions for a fairer food policy architecture 22 Conclusions 27 References 30 Annexes 32 Introduction This paper aims to provide an overview of the current state of international", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "bebeb33c-d4e5-4861-a23d-b2fd2a0cb003": {"__data__": {"id_": "bebeb33c-d4e5-4861-a23d-b2fd2a0cb003", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a7e7c71c087d91d9d7592821f7d2f292aff45703be7e3cee34ec8d6d3602a642"}}, "hash": "a7e7c71c087d91d9d7592821f7d2f292aff45703be7e3cee34ec8d6d3602a642", "text": "food policy architecture which is defined for the purposes of this paper as those international rules governing trade in food products and the inputs for food production; policies adopted by international organizations or countries which impact the production, distribution and in a related sense consumption of food products; and the rules (or lack thereof) governing agricultural commodities markets. The paper, in particular, focuses on the impact of this architecture on hunger1 in the Asia Pacific region. It approaches the topic of food policy architecture first by exploring why patterns of agricultural production do not seem to match with likely comparative advantage of major producers. The paper then investigates how efficiently the market for food products work, particularly in the transmission of price signals and examines the structural issues which underpin global agricultural trade and its linkages with food insecurity and hunger. The paper then concludes with recommendations on how to address the biggest failings of the current international food architecture: market distortions and failures; underinvestment in agriculture in developing countries; and the failure to recognize the cross cutting nature of food production. It concludes that the existence of so many living in hunger is a human rights failure, which it is the international community\u2019s responsibility to resolve. 1 Unless otherwise stated, hunger is measured in terms of prevalence in the population of undernourished as defined by the Global Hunger Index designed by IFPRI (2007) and based on three equally weighted indicators: the proportion of undernourished as a percentage of the population; the prevalence of underweight in children under the age of five and the under-five mortality rate. (these are also official MDG indicators) 1 The liberalization of trade has been pursued by developing and developed countries alike as a route to faster rates of growth for over half a decade. Economic growth has indeed accelerated for many WTO members. Fuelled by exports of manufactured goods, and (in- creasingly) services, the Asia Pacific region has grown at a phenomenal rate. In 2008, it was the world\u2019s fastest growing regional economy, sustaining an average growth rate of 7.4% in East Asia and 5.9% in South Asia. Today, fewer people in the Region are living in absolute poverty: only DPRK has failed to reduce the number of people living on less than US$1 per day since the Millennium Development Goals were announced. Yet, trade liberalization has done little to ease the plight of some 500 million people in the Re- gion who continue to live in hunger2. Most of these people are the rural poor, small scale agricultural producers. The benefits accruing from growing markets for exported manufactured goods have been remarkably concentrated in coastal manu- facturing centres3. Although poor farmers should have benefited from increased con- sumption by richer urban workers, this trickle down effect has been limited. Many analysts have noted the linkages between increased trade liberalization in agriculture and poverty reduction (thereby leading to increased food security and reduced hunger) in rural areas. Following this line of reasoning, the incorpo- ration of trade in agricultural products into the world trading system in 1995 (see below) was hoped by many to provide rural workers in poorer countries with the chance to raise their incomes through capturing export mar- kets, and lift themselves out of poverty and hunger. What is the link between international food policy architecture and hunger? 2 2 FAO 2001-3. Cited by UNDP RCC 2008. 3 Gallup andSachs 1998. 4 FAO 2006. 5 Indonesia, on account of the AoA, substantially dismantled the domestic support, government procurement prices and other price stabilization measures thereby contributing to the distress of its farmers. See Ecumenical Advocacy Alliance 2007. 6 This section draws upon Choudhary, Pal and Mangnani 2005 7 As per estimates of FAO, less than 10 percent of women farmers in India, Nepal and Thailand own land. See FAO n.d. In reality, however, these hoped-for gains have not materialized, partly as a result of low national investment in agriculture and rural livelihoods, but also because of high levels of remaining domestic subsidies and other trade distorting measures. World pric- es in staples such as rice, wheat and corn have been low from around 1995 to 2002. On the import side, these factors together with the lowering of trade barriers and lack of WTO compatible protective mechanisms, seem to have contributed instead to the in- creased vulnerability of countries to disrup- tive import surges in agricultural products.4 Farmers in many developing countries have found it difficult to compete with cheap im- ports, and have seen their incomes fall as a result. In many cases, falling agricultural incomes have followed sharp", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3c9a9286-8fa6-462a-96e4-bcec6e1c0a9e": {"__data__": {"id_": "3c9a9286-8fa6-462a-96e4-bcec6e1c0a9e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4332e19939de893ecb572f4fe5624ab5c9092cb4b6a3be39c58e7eaf3de4cd77"}}, "hash": "4332e19939de893ecb572f4fe5624ab5c9092cb4b6a3be39c58e7eaf3de4cd77", "text": "on the heels of the dismantlement of tariff protections. In In- donesia, for instance, following a combina- tion of factors, including adoption of trade liberalization measures and dismantling of domestic protection and subsidies in the rice sector post 1995, the livelihoods and food security of the small farmers was badly affected.5 Women tend to be particularly hard hit by failing agricultural sector and poor food security, for several reasons.6 Most women who are involved in agricul- ture, tend to be landless workers7. Studies show that even when women own farm land, these lands are generally in small frag- mented plots and are of poor quality. This denies them access to institutional credit and public support programmes. Farming in these lands is done primarily for self- consumption and a very small portion of their output is either sold in the market or exported. As a result, even if trade liberal- ization does indeed unlock export oppor- tunities, it is unlikely that these farmers will have the ability to take advantage of such opportunities. 3 On the other hand, trade liberalization and associated domestic reforms can multiply the problems of small farmers, especially women farmers. With the WTO setting limits on subsidy levels in developing countries and associated liberalization measures, the farm- ing communities in developing countries are facing the spectre of increasing prices of in- puts such as fertilizer, water and electricity. This is expected to push up the production costs for farmers. To make the situation more complex, removal of import restrictions is likely to open the gates to imports of a num- ber of commodities, making them vulnerable to global volatility. Small farmers, especially women farmers, tend to be excluded from the emerging globalized food economy. Histori- cal constraints work against women adopt- ing new technologies and their participation in marketing channels higher upstream. Pre- liminary trends show that smaller farmers in developing countries are selling off farms, leading to land concentration and commer- cialization of agriculture.8 Emergence of con- tract farming has in a limited sense opened up employment opportunities for women and children, primarily on account of their lower wage requirements but has been at the cost of exposing them to harsh working conditions.9 With the recent rise in global food and fuel prices, net food consumers among both ur- ban and rural poor have struggled to buy enough food to meet their basic needs. As per provisional FAO estimates, the number of undernourished people in 2007 increased by 75 million globally, out of which 41 million are in Asia Pacific. Much of this increase in hunger has been attributed to high food prices. The FAO report also notes that through the end 2007, the progress of reducing the proportion of hungry people in the developing world has been re- versed by 17%, to about the same level as a decade ago10. In theory, these price rises should be good news for food producers, heavily represented among the most poor and hungry in Asia, especially if the price rise of agriculture inputs does not increase proportionately. However, even if the production costs do not offset the benefits of food price rise, the increased profits from exports tend to exclude in most cases small scale farmers who are unlikely to produce significant mar- ketable surpluses and are not linked well with the markets. For the small farmers to benefit from increased prices a number of comple- mentary policies need to be put in place, namely, transmission of price signals to small farmers, overhauling agriculture extension and research services and enhancing access and utilization by small farmers, improving connectivity to markets and providing reli- able irrigation systems. Cash Crops, Price Volatility and Food Security in India Higher returns from some export oriented cash crops like tobacco and sunflower have lured even smaller farms to undertake cash crop cultiva- tion at the expense of traditional crops, including foodgrains. This is a risky move because these farmers are now totally dependent upon the revenue from the cash crops even for their domestic consumption. International prices for cash crops are volatile and they fluctuate wildly from year to year. Every now and then, low prices of these commodities lead to heavy losses for farmers. For farmers who do not maintain a cushion of self-pro- duced foodgrains to support them, such losses can create huge food se- curity problems. Also, these farmers get into severe debt traps because of this problem. In South India, there have been numerous cases of farmers\u2019 suicides because of this reason. Estimates indicate that since 1997, more than 25,000 farmers have committed suicide in India and", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b363b2ca-a727-42c2-8ade-7d71449c3938": {"__data__": {"id_": "b363b2ca-a727-42c2-8ade-7d71449c3938", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4c944ac85eb8c5c120b8c00ea06b0ee1a2471e2da1bcd86a5702f6c079bd12a9"}, "3": {"node_id": "3d4e0145-8569-46c0-869e-8ac3249c52b2", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c93fc87e3523d53c78c9bf261aa44baa3ff25827035002b7cde1bf077c00956a"}}, "hash": "e0e10fc707523700f97f113412001b14da68c644a84217ae58bff7406ddb4849", "text": "a majority of these suicides are a result of crop failures and high indebtedness. (For a comprehensive discussion on this topic See, the \u2018Report of the Com- mission on Farmers' Welfare, Government of Andhra Pradesh\u2019 available at http://www.macroscan.com/pol/apr05/pol070405Andhra_Pradesh.htm) 8 FAO, 2006 9 Ghosh, 2007 10 FAO 2008. 4 Moreover, many countries, including de- veloping countries, have encouraged the creation of industrial agriculture systems which are believed to provide greater value addition domestically. However, since bulk of the value addition occurs in agriculture firms, small farmers do not stand to benefit from the post farm gate price realizations which are significantly higher.11 Until such time as these flanking policies are institut- ed domestically and distortions in global agriculture markets corrected, any price rise will not translate into income increases for the small farmers. An FAO study12 based on data from devel- oping countries highlights the fact that the majority of poor households are net buy- ers of staple foods, implying that for most households consumption needs are great- er than the value of their produce for the same staples. The study brings out further that even in rural areas, \u2018where agricul- ture and staple food production are im- portant occupations for the majority of the poor, a vast share of the poor are net food buyers and stand to lose (or at least not gain) from an increase in the price of tradable staple food\u201913. In this light, food price stabilization emerges as a critical fac- tor for poverty reduction and ensuring food security ,leading to reduced hunger. Recent research suggests that while the impact of rising commodity prices varies across coun- tries and commodities, depending among other things on the extent to which global prices pass through to domestic consum- ers, more often than not \u2018poverty increases are considerably more frequent and larger than poverty reductions [when food prices increase]\u2019.14 The World Bank estimates that average impact of a 10% increase for sev- en key food items would raise the poverty headcount ratio by 0.4 percentage points.15 Another piece of research examining future impacts on account of food price increases estimates that a 20% increase in food prices in 2025 relative to the baseline would swell the ranks of the undernourished population by 440 million people.16 As this FAO report notes, challenges for urban poor may be particularly severe as they tend to consume more tradables and are unlikely to produce much for their own food needs or even for sale.17 Arguably, the challenges of increased liberalization in agriculture trade may out- weigh the opportunities therein for some developing countries, since in addition to the domestic constraints, the current inter- national food policy architecture does not seem adequately geared to ensuring food security and reduction of hunger for the poor. This paper aims to explore why internation- al food policy has to date delivered so little for the world\u2019s hungry. In so doing, it aims to unpack some of the issues which policy makers need to consider in developing new approaches to the international food policy architecture while responding to the emerging challenges and addressing the structural causes and limitations affecting agricultural trade. 11 Kwa 2001. 12 FAO 2008 13 Ibid 14 Ivanic and Martin. Cited by World Bank 2008. 15 ibid. 16 Senauer and Sur. Cited by FAO 2008. 17 ibid. 5 International trade in agricultural products- continues to form a significant component of trade in the Asia Pacific region even though its overall importance is in decline as a per- centage of GDP18. It has expanded more rap- idly in recent decades than global agricul- tural GDP, though at lower rates than trade in goods and services. Over the years, global agriculture trade has seen a profound shift in structure, direction and composition which is often paradoxical in nature19. Agricultural trade accounted for around 70% of Asia Pa- cific\u2019s exports, and around 40% of its imports in 1961, but in 2003, accounted for less than 10% of each20. The Asia Pacific region as a whole has recently moved to a net import position: the share of agricultural exports and imports as a proportion of total exports and imports have both fallen, but the latter more slowly. Asia Pacific accounts for only around 3% of world trade in agricultural products21. A large and increasing proportion of Asia Pa- cific exports and imports are concentrated within the Region (48% and 41% of exports and imports respectively in 2003) 22.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3d4e0145-8569-46c0-869e-8ac3249c52b2": {"__data__": {"id_": "3d4e0145-8569-46c0-869e-8ac3249c52b2", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "