ian countries have the potential to be competitive producers and export- ers of staple grains, the past four decades have been characterized by the increasing dominance of agricultural exports from developed countries. The EU, for example, accounted for a little over 20% of global trade in the early 1960s to over 40% today.24 Conversely, developing countries have seen their share of world agricultural exports de- cline over the same period from nearly 40% to around 30% today25. It is worth noting that the model of growth through liberalization assumes functioning markets in order to achieve the benefits of comparative advantage-based production. As Bhagwati26 and others have noted, the existence of market failure at any level may result in sub-optimal systems of produc- tion. In other words, though a perfectly functioning free market economy may be the most efficient means of production, a relatively freer economy may or may not be more efficient or welfare-enhancing than its relatively less free predecessor. More- over, gains from liberalization in agriculture trade along the lines of comparative advan- tages cannot be assumed to be automatic and critically dependent on the presence of several complementary policies and in- stitutions at the national and international levels. 24 ibid. 25 ibid. 26 1971. 7 Agricultural trade has only relatively recently been subject to the disciplines of the mul- tilateral trade system following the setting up of the World Trade Organisation (WTO) in 1995 and adoption of the Agreement on Agriculture (AoA). During the period, when the General Agreeement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) of 1947 governed international trade in goods, before the birth of the WTO, the bulk of the general rules of trade in goods did not apply to agriculture, contrary to the original draft of the GATT text. The special treatment of agriculture under the GATT re- sulted chiefly from US concerns about stabi- lizing agricultural incomes and their desire to preserve national means of food production. This meant that, for most of the second half of the twentieth century, many GATT signa- tories were able to maintain, introduce or increase restrictions on agricultural imports, while subsidizing domestic production and export of agricultural products. The GATT, however, liberalized trade in non- agricultural products, fuelling a dramatic increase in the exports of goods and ser- vices. During this period, many developing countries, including in the Asia Pacific region, adopted a deliberate policy of rapid indus- trialization, reducing investment in, or even taxing, domestic agricultural production. Meanwhile, industrial workers were sustained by importing cheap food, often heavily sub- sidized, from developed countries, notably the US (and, later, the EU). In addition, the US, in particular, provided large quantities of wheat to developing economies in the form of food aid under its Food for Peace (PL-480) programme.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "82a369b5-7612-4c58-9955-ef2492e31ac1": {"__data__": {"id_": "82a369b5-7612-4c58-9955-ef2492e31ac1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5a0be1f254f875db448e1a89369fdbb9845803bf8fc5f840