veloping countries. How- ever, it came at the cost of unsustainable fis- cal and current account deficits, and further impoverishment of the rural and landless poor. Some governments attempted to re- dress these problems through measures to support domestic agriculture or control im- ports. The result was increased volatility in global food prices. In addition, import substitution resulted in some unanticipated outcomes, the dis- tortionary effects of which are difficult to quantify. These include changes in the crops consumed, particularly the increase in wheat consumption, among developing countries, and displacement of local grains and root crops at the expense of a small number of staples. This, in turn, allowed the US and EU to consolidate their increasing dominance of international trade in staple food crops, al- lowing them to benefit from economies of scale and reduced risk for producers. The 1994 Uruguay Round Agreement on Ag- riculture, followed by the setting up of the WTO in 1995, established the first binding global framework for the trade of agricultural products. It aimed to rationalize the current system of protection, and gradually reduce trade-distorting protection of the agricul- tural sector. The AoA\u2019s main provisions are summarized in Annex 1. Although the Uruguay commitments placed lower obligations on developing than devel- 27 See annex 1 for definition of amber, blue and green box measures 28 FAO 2001. 29 FAO 2003. International agricultural trade policy architecture \u2013 An Overview 8 oped countries, and exempted LDCs from most provisions, in practice, they tended to benefit richer producers, especially in the area of subsidies. This was because devel- oped countries tended to have higher lev- els of existing subsidies, a significant part of which was accommodated within the framework of the AoA under the so called \u2018green box\u2019 and \u2018blue box\u2019 measures. In ad- dition, developing countries often lacked the resources to take advantage of green box and blue box provisions27, which were permitted under AoA rules. Moreover, many developing countries did not declare export subsidies, limiting their future abil- ity to make use of this provision while giv- ing up resort to quantitative restrictions on imports and reducing bound tariffs on agri- cultural products. Meanwhile, even though developing countries tended to have high- er bound tariffs following the introduction of the AoA, applied rates on average were often much lower than bound rates. A FAO study covering 14 countries showed that while the bound rate was 90%, the simple average of the applied rates for 12 coun- tries was 22%.28 While there existed Special Safeguard (SSG) provisions to protect sen- sitive sectors, or other sectors which faced supply shocks, in practice, these were often difficult to apply. It has been suggested that elements of the AoA worked towards re- ducing the policy space and flexibility avail- able to developing country governments to stimulate agricultural development by providing protection and/or support to the sector. 29 In addition, many of the developing coun- tries undertaking \u2018structural adjustment policies\u2019 were faced with pressures to liber- alize autonomously by the International Fi- nancial Institutions (IFIs), including through reduction of import tariffs and quantitative restrictions and a significant scaling down of agriculture expenditure, including sub- sidies30. As a result, over the last couple of decades, while subsidies in the OECD coun- tries have increased in nominal terms by 5-10%, agriculture expenditure in develop- ing countries has fallen31. Agricultural development tends to benefit from intensive investment in early phases of sector development, to help farmers to take risks associated with experimenta- tion and more intensive production, as well as giving access to credit. Successful agricultural growth then tends to result in greater consolidation and the achieve- ment of economies of scale, and a focus on value added agricultural production. At this point subsidies may no longer be necessary because producers have already gained comparative advantage through such efficiency gains. However, the current imbalances in the global agricultural trade policy architecture have effectively served to constrain the nurturing of the agricul- ture sector along lines of comparative ad- vantages in developing countries and while the developed countries have succeeded in maintaining significantly their protectionist stance, the developing countries continue to be nudged towards accepting signifi- cant reduction of import tariffs and dilution of protective safeguards in the Doha trade talks. 30 ibid. 31 ibid. 9 A well functioning market for agricultural products would efficiently transmit price signals without distortions and is essential for equilibrating the forces of supply and demand. In the literature on the relationship between transmission of prices, whether spatial or vertical, at least six groups of fac- tors have been seen", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ea639ed5-b0a0-4648-8213-0abaadf43ad3": {"__data__": {"id_": "ea639ed5-b0a0-4648-8213-0abaadf43ad3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e1e9c759e0b30da8a0019ab53e87755934509b86210dc26ea593be3ecd6f19c1"}, "3": {"node_id": "69b076da-fe1b-4254-874e-842d8714f050", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9ba89accc4c09bb2bea5ec12e7b55c9398f53257e6f4348ae04769efd15501e9"}}, "hash": "808d48d73de4f6fb654509510b3ad0565d166ed01d911fa21c1356ff3c0ba3a9", "text": "as significant: transport and transaction costs, market power, increas- ing returns to scale in production, product homogeneity and differentiation, exchange rates and border and domestic policies.32 In this light, since the degree of transmission of price signals is seen as a broad indicator of whether or not the markets are functioning efficiently, an examination of how agricultur- al markets react to pricing decision assumes relevance. Although almost all countries in the Region rely on rice as a staple food, the impact of a rice price increase or decrease on poverty and hunger outcomes differs signifi- cantly, depending on whether a country is a net importer and exporter of rice (see be- low). 32 FAO 2004. How do agricultural markets react to pricing signals? 10 There will also be a differing impact of such an increase within a country, according to re- gion and sector. During the late 1990s and early 2000s, cheap rice imports benefited the net consumers of rice \u2013 notably the ur- ban poor. However, domestic producers of rice were unable to compete with cheap im- ports, reducing their income and thus their ability to feed themselves and their families. For example, between 1998 and 2002, an in- ability to compete with cheap food imports threatened the livelihoods of around 17 mil- lion small farmers in Indonesia and the Phil- ippines33. The main beneficiaries of the recent food price spike will be those farmers who ben- efit from the efficient transmission of pricing signals, and who have the means to increase production. The main losers will be net food consumers such as the urban poor, marginal farmers and the landless poor. In line with other traded products, the im- pact of a price movement in either direc- tion should be self-correcting, assuming a functioning market. In the case of the recent price increase, for example, the rising prices should signal to farmers to increase produc- tion, while there will be some reduction in food consumption (though demand for food has low income flexibility). Meanwhile, pro- ducers should benefit from rising incomes, which both allow them to consume increas- ing non-food products, and to invest more in the productivity of their land (through labour or other inputs). Conversely, if food prices fall, urban workers and other consumers should benefit from low food prices, allowing them to spend or invest more of their income on non-food items. Figures 1-3: Dependence on rice imports for Asia Pacific countries, from UNDP RCC 2008, original source FAO statistical database 33 Dhar 2005. 12 34 FAO 2005b. 35 Dhar, 2007. 36 Economic Report of the President, Environmental Working Group 2006. Cited by Oxfam. Farmers should be incentivised to reduce production, which will reduce supply and hence raise food prices to an equilibrium level. If low prices persist, they will be in- centivised to leave the food production sector for more productive sectors. However, food differs from other commodi- ties in several respects. First, the results of \u2018reduced consumption\u2019 for the poor can in- rease hunger or even starvation, meaning that the human cost of market adjustments can be immense. Moreover, in countries which have suffered from historical under- investment in agriculture, farmers may be incapable of increasing production to bene- fit from rising prices. High oil prices may ex- acerbate production limitations, by making fertilizers, a key input, less affordable. Even if they have the technology and inputs to produce more over the long term, they still have the time delay of growing and har- vesting the crops. Finally, a preponderance of subsistence farming can also mean that a significant share of output does not come to the market; hence, in such a scenario, production changes may not be correlated well with price changes. A 2005 FAO study34 found that for 150 episodes internationally, where data on both price and production changes are presented in the studies, in only 66% of cases was the response in the direction expected. Nor can farmers in countries with declining agricultural sectors easily shift into differ- ent occupations, for reasons of geography (most rural farmers are located far from ur- ban centres) and skills.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "69b076da-fe1b-4254-874e-842d8714f050": {"__data__": {"id_": "69b076da-fe1b-4254-874e-842d8714f050", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e1e9c759e0b30da8a0019ab53e87755934509b86210dc26ea593be3ecd6f19c1"}, "2": {"node_id": "ea639ed5-b0a0-4648-8213-0abaadf43ad3", "node_type": null, "metadat