ext": "framework, and likely to be characterized by high rates of unemployment, poverty and hunger in the meantime. The ability of the world market to regulate prices also depends on the efficient trans- mission of pricing signals. However, for de- veloping countries with poor infrastructure, or markets where the influence of powerful and rent-seeking middlemen is significant, farmers may not always receive an accurate indication of world price increases or de- creases. For this reason, the US in particu- lar, has faced criticism for the concentration of their remaining domestic subsidies on large producers (with the largest 10% of producers receiving 75% of subsidies ac- cording to some estimates36). Food prices are also increasingly affected by volatility from commodities traders, which can result in false pricing mechanisms being relayed to producers. While the urban poor go hungry as the result of high world prices, domestic agri- cultural products consumed locally may still bring a poor price for their hungry producers. However, what is clear is that, though food prices may swell the number of hungry people in the Asia Pacific region, the vast majority of those going hungry have been hungry for decades, even when food prices were low. This was largely due to poor productivity and high post harvest losses, low incomes and distribution issues, which meant that food did not always reach those who needed it most. 13 The AoA included in its provisions a commit- ment to further progressive liberalization of the agricultural system. A new round of ne- gotiations, \u2018the Doha Development Round\u2019 was launched in 2001. This Round is mandat- ed to accord particular priority to the needs of developing countries. Agriculture remains one of the main obsta- cles to concluding the Doha Round, mostly due to disagreements over how much sup- port to agriculture should be maintained by the US and EU and the nature and extent of effective protection available to developing countries to protect food security, livelihood security and rural development. The recent stalemate at the mini Ministerial held in Ge- neva in July 2008 over the agricultural mo- dalities in this regard are symptomatic of the lack of convergence between the developed countries led by US, EU and large blocks of developing countries led by India and China seeking to strike a balance between the im- peratives of liberalization and protection. In part, disagreement on the way forward on subsidies is a result of a lack of consensus about the amount of progress made so far in reducing subsidies. The two most commonly cited indicators of support to producers are the WTO\u2019s Aggregate Measure of Support (AMS) and the OECD\u2019s Producer Support Es- timate (PSE). By the former measure, in 2003, EU farmers received a subsidy of $115 million in 2003; US farmers $54 million. Using AMS, the figures are only $51 million and 17 mil- lion respectively37. 37 FAO 2005a. The Doha Round: Prospects for further liberalization and current market distortions 14 Developed countries have criticized the use of the PSE in calculating levels of sub- sidy because it includes border protections such as tariffs. However, even when border measures are discounted, there is a signifi- cant difference between PSE and AMS cal- culations. The AMS has also been criticized because it excludes support to the actual domestic price (as opposed to the administered or guaranteed price) received by farmers from its calculation. Moreover, because of its re- liance on historical world reference prices as a base, countries can actually raise the level of domestic support when actual cur- rent world prices fall. Additionally, whereas PSE is calculated on the basis of all subsidies made to farmers, AMS looks at only \u2018amber box\u2019 provisions. Amber box measures have steadily de- clined since the introduction of the AoA. However, there has been a roughly com- mensurate increase in green and blue box measures. Two studies in 200438 found that while blue and green box policies were sig- nificantly less trade distorting than direct subsidies, they did provide some distortion. Anton calculated that such support was ap- proximately equal to 20% of the distortion caused by market price supports, while the OECD suggested that actual distortion could be even higher because such pay- ments served to reduce the risks of produc- tion, particularly for riskier commodities. In 2004, WTO members approved a Frame- work Agreement. This expresses members\u2019 intention to harmonize levels of subsidy, substantially reduce tariffs amongst mem- bers, while maintaining increased flexibility for sensitive sectors in developing coun- tries. However, clear differences still exist between members. Broadly defined, the US and EU have made substantial offers to reduce further", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "bc822bc0-bba5-4a4f-8c7c-80be7f657708": {"__data__": {"id_": "bc822bc0-bba5-4a4f-8c7c-80be7f657708", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "153cca494ae9f5cd2d19f10f20a0f951ab056ecc7cb733e28b758ebb98c89b6a"}}, "hash": "153cca494ae9f5cd2d19f10f20a0f951ab056ecc7cb733e28b758ebb98c89b6a", "text": "their domestic subsidies. But the EU has rejected blanket cuts and has further tried to link concessions in agri- culture to progress in Non Agricultural Mar- ket Access (NAMA) and services in particu- lar. Moreover, their offers have fallen short of what has been called for both by the Cairns group of major producers, and most developing countries, who have pushed for much more extensive reductions in domes- tic support. The 2004 Framework Agreement also in- corporates an important decision to in- clude measures to protect an appropriate number of products as \u2018Special Products\u2019 (SPs) in developing countries which are be- lieved to be particularly important from a food security, livelihood security and rural development point of view. The decision constituted a much sought after middle ground between the objective of ensuring enhanced market access and operationalis- ing the principle of special and differential treatment. SP provisions are intended to protect the interests of small and vulnera- ble farmers. Under the provisions, SPs were to be afforded lower and more flexible re- duction commitments than other products. Additionally, a provision for developing countries to have recourse to invoke a Spe- cial Safeguard Mechanism (SSM) which will allow them to protect their markets from import surges and pricing shocks was also outlined. The inclusion of these elements in the Framework Agreement followed lobbying by the G33 and are supported by the G20 and other poor and net food importing. At first, vigorously opposed by major produc- ers such as the EU, US and Cairns Group, the principles of SP and SSM have now been recognized by all major players as key to any hopes of concluding the Round. Significant challenges still remain, not least of which is achieving agreement on which products should be covered by SP provisions, and how SP and SSM will operate. 38 Anton 2004, OECD 2004. 15 The designation of Special Products recog- nizes implicitly that total reliance on import- ed staples is a high-risk strategy for a devel- oping country, particularly in the context of staple food price volatility, and encourages the maintenance of some degree of national food production, at least where some pro- duction capacity already exists. Members of the G33 and other developing countries have argued that they should be given the right to designate the SPs for at least 20% of their agricultural tariff lines, guided by a set of indicators. These indicators include, inter alia, staple food or products which form a major part of the food basket in developing countries; products whose domestic con- sumption is largely met through domestic production; and products produced by a large number of resource poor and subsis- tence farmers39. However, reaching an agree- ment on scope, coverages and mechanisms for SP and SSM provisions has been challeng- ing. This is in part because the criteria and thresholds for determining which products are critical for livelihoods, food security and rural development will vary by each country. OECD producers have argued for a minimal- ist set of Special Products, to consist mostly of key staples. A 2005 ICTSD multi-country study suggested that the following products were particularly significant in terms of the three elements highlighted in the 2004 Framework Agree- ment (food security, livelihood security, ru- ral livelihoods): wheat, rice, maize, sugar, chicken and beef, milk and dairy products, tomatoes, onions and potatoes. As the au- thors note, these are the same sectors which currently suffer from the greatest degree of trade distortion (e.g. due to subsidies). This is particularly significant because granting of additional protection in these areas would recognize the fact that subsidy reduction alone would not level the playing field for developing country producers because of dynamic gains from previous subsidization. The intention behind the SSM is slightly dif- ferent from SP provisions, in that it aims to protect the rural producer (particularly the small farmer), whereas the SP provisions aim to protect both small producer and vulner- able consumer. In principle, therefore, SSM product coverage could be much broader than that of SP, and could even include non- food items (such as cotton), as long as these were significant for rural livelihoods. Once more, the G-33 have argued for, and the OECD producers against, a broad scope. A key concern for SSM is to ensure that it will be more effective than the current Special Safeguard Provision (SSG). This is only avail- able to 22 developing countries, and has been little-used because of difficulty in calcu- lating the volume of import surges. For this reason, a price-triggered mechanism may be preferable40 as price surges are easier to track than import", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7f93398e-2018-4662-a74f-eacb487ea1dc": {"__data__": {"id_": "7f93398e-2018-4662-a74f-eacb487ea1dc", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "653daaa789f37d594bcc944117a5621d00d78e5e5f73e3d0238e55127c5b86d7"}}, "hash": "653daaa789f37d594bcc944117a5621d00d78e5e5f73e3d0238e55127c5b86d7", "text": "surges. Moreover, by focusing on import prices, the SSM would avoid be- ing triggered when the import surge was a response to a dramatic shortfall in domestic production (e.g. caused by drought or flood- ing), in which case imports would form a vital part of any country level response. In order that SP and SSM provisions are best able to help the hungry of Asia Pacific, and small farmers which are so critical to achiev- ing food security in the region, we suggest that the following factors should be borne in mind: 1. SP and SSM provisions should be designed to counter act both current subsidies by developed country producers, and historical distortions from previous subsidies \u2013 this will im- pact on product selection, scale of tar- iffs (or non-tariff measures) applied and duration of measures; 39 Roy 2006 40 ICTSD 2005 16 2. Given the urgent need to address is- sues of hunger, scope of the measures should be clear, transparent, and pro- vide a straightforward and simple agen- da for negotiation. In the case of SSMs, there is a further need to ensure that the provisions are simple to activate. 3. The needs of developing countries (and particularly small holders) should be prioritized; 4. If possible, the measures should incen tivise investment in staple crops in pref- erence to export and cash crops, at least for the duration of this round (given sta ple price volatility and the low level of development in agriculture overall). Taken together, these factors might argue for the adoption of maximalist SP protection for staple crops,together with other products, subject to heavy market distortions, combined with the freedom for developing countries to implement SSMs in the face of downward price shocks for any product (subject perhaps to a maxi- mum number of products at any one time, to prevent abuse). The former should facili- tate the development of food security, at a national and regional levels, while the lat- ter should enable small farmers to mitigate against risk of shocks across the breadth of their activities. 17 Regional trade agreements are becoming an important part of the global trading landscape and are set to proliferate further, given the continued stalemate at the mul- tilateral level. As with most other regions of the world, there are a plethora of RTAs and PTAs within the Asia Pacific region, the most significant of which are based around the ASEAN, APEC and SAARC groupings. To date, none of these institutions have been very successful at incorporating agriculture into their remits, partly because of widely different domestic policies and levels of protection (a factor likely to reduce if the Doha Round concludes with reduced levels of protection for agriculture globally). Gen- erally speaking, given the existing thrust of RTAs on non-agricultural trade, it is difficult to predict their impact on food security. There is a dearth of literature in this regard and any welfare impact would be condition- al, largely on the specifics of the agreement and whether or not it leads to more trade creation and not trade diversion.41 Also, the ability of low income households to benefit from an increase in market access would continue to be constrained by supply side issues.42 Modelling by Bandara and Yu43 sug- gests that a pan-Asian RTA on agriculture is likely to deliver more welfare benefits to its members than smaller RTAs (e.g. for South and South East Asia). However, even under this scenario, net food importers such as the Philippines, Bangladesh and Sri Lanka are likely to suffer some welfare losses. A South Asian FTA (Free Trade Agreement) would deliver significant benefits for India (though not as great as if it were included in an ASEAN plus RTA) and Pakistan, while an ASEAN RTA would be welfare enhancing for most members, but at very modest rates. 41 FAO 2003. 42 ibid. 43 2007. The role of Regional Trade Agreements (RTAs) and Preferential Trading Agreements (PTAs) 18 The traditional approach to international discussions on food production and distri- bution is to focus on trade. The non-trade elements of international food policy archi- tecture are subject to fewer formal control mechanisms than those relating to trade. There is a danger, therefore, that a holistic view of international food policy architec- ture is not achieved by policy makers who address the issue through specific \u2018lenses\u2019 without consideration of the broader im- plications of their decision making. This section intends to discuss some of the non- trade aspects of international food policy architecture, and how these relate to hun- ger. The recent boom in activity in commodities futures trading has increased", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fd7cbf12-8d88-4251-a232-9a0e0b6874df": {"__data__": {"id_": "fd7cbf12-8d88-4251-a232-9a0e0b6874df", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c9915e8e05777d7faab1d0fec428a68be07fac1a806eccef1f4c00fd8302db7a"}, "3": {"node_id": "8b6c948c-a354-44b5-89d0-7a5801c5b84e", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9eb6f97182496fad8f9e40d23d902567aee6dd9a580ad01bd79704e3aba14c39"}}, "hash": "472a5642b6e2d4a45e55fec2b332ef818657f5c954df8a74fc528123e005af6d", "text": "both world food prices and their potential volatility. According to some estimates44, volumes of capital flows in the food commodities markets have risen from $13 billion in 2003 to $260 billion in 2008 (although these fig- ures remain relatively small compared with other non-food commodities such as oil). Speculators have shown increasing inter- est in food markets following the collapse of the financial derivatives and real estate markets. India recently took the unusual step of suspending trade in futures of four staple products (including rice). Placing international controls on agricultural com- modities futures may prove neither prac- ticable nor ultimately desirable. However, policy makers need to be aware that, for example, a major crash in this market could significantly damage any attempts at a fairer international food policy. At the least, there may be the need for national or inter- national legislation to prevent market ma- nipulation and excessive speculation. One of the most controversial issues at the FAO 6 June, 2008 Rome meeting on the food price crisis was the production of biofuels, which participants argued caused anything from 3% to 30% of the recent increase in food prices. The impact of biofuels on hun- ger levels in Asia Pacific has so far been neg- ligible: rice, the main regional staple, has not been diverted into biofuel production, nor has land in the main regional produc- ers of rice been diverted to production of biofuel crops. However, some market fore- casters claim that the region being a net importer of energy and being vulnerable to oil price vulnerability, is set to witness an increased use of bio-fuels in order to meet a part of its increasing domestic demand.45 Given increasing attention to biofuel pro- duction across countries and region and the government support to harnessing bio- fuels in several countries already in place, international policy makers will doubtless take an interest in future trends in biofuel production, in order to assess whether rules governing their production would be ap- propriate. International agreements on combating Climate Change are not usually considered alongside similar debates on agricultural trade policy. However, even small rises in world temperatures could have significant and devastating effects on agricultural pro- duction in the Asia Pacific region, through increased flooding and desertification46. 44 Master Capital Management LLC. Cited by www.npr.org. 45 http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2007-09/irri-anu092007.php 46 See Stern Review 2006. Non-trade elements of international food policy architecture 19 Moreover, attempts to increase produc- tion within the Region may place additional strain on existing water resources. Therefore, there is some logic in considering the issues of climate change and hunger to be closely linked. As Stern47 has noted, there are com- plex interlinkages between the issues of climate change and development. Richer countries are more able to afford adaptation mechanisms which may protect lives and livelihoods in the event of extreme climatic events. This may include measures to pre- serve and protect food production systems. However, the process of development itself may result in increased carbon emissions (which may increase the likelihood and se- verity of such events). Many small holders, who will suffer disproportionately from the effects of climate change, have already start- ed experimenting with new methods of cul- tivation and means of reducing risk48. How- ever, a significant challenge remains the lack of small holder voice at international meet- ings to discuss climate change. As in the case of trade talks, these tend to be dominated by arguments between developed and devel- oping major polluters, with both focusing on their aggregate economic growth (with, in the case of climate change talks, a heavy em- phasis on the non-agricultural sector). 47 2006. 48 See ActionAid 2007. 20 In mid-2008, it became clear that the world was heading for a major economic down- turn, on a scale unprecedented in recent years. As noted in this paper, international food policy is affected not just by trade policy but also by other developments on the international stage. We might, therefore, expect that the downturn would have a sig- nificant impact on hunger in the Asia Pacific region. Although, it is too soon to quantify these impacts, their vectors are likely to include: - Increased agricultural trade protec- tionism by major developed countries: already the food price spike had encour- aged French President Sarkozy to scupper a draft US-EU compromise on un- picking subsidies.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8b6c948c-a354-44b5-89d0-7a5801c5b84e": {"__data__": {"id_": "8b6c948c-a354-44b5-89d0-7a5801c5b84e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c9915e8e05777d7faab1d0fec428a68be07fac1a806eccef1f4c00fd8302db7a"}, "2": {"node_id": "fd7cbf12-8d88-4251-a232-9a0e0b6874df", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "472a5642b6e2d4a45e55fec2b332ef818657f5c954df8a74fc528123e005af6d"}}, "hash": "9eb6f97182496fad8f9e40d23d902567aee6dd9a580ad01bd79704e3aba14c39", "text": "- Reduced consumption of income-elastic food and non-food agricultural products: declining consumption patterns, notably in the developed world, could lead to a reduction in demand for certain income- elastic agricultural products (these might include e.g. cut flowers, processed agri- cultural products and meat products). This would likely", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "180054cb-8e1c-4305-8693-242bab5cd5a4": {"__data__": {"id_": "180054cb-8e1c-4305-8693-242bab5cd5a4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "dacde0fe6896c842a578160cc378004541eb3955a7255cf1567669e85408fc93"}}, "hash": "dacde0fe6896c842a578160cc378004541eb3955a7255cf1567669e85408fc93", "text": "lead to a decrease in certain agricultural exports which could impact the Asia Pacific economic growth, and particularly foreign exchange earn- ings. However, the overall impact on Asia Pacific food security might be posi- tive over the medium to long term, if this process led to a shift back towards staple food production at the expense of agricul- tural exports, as well as encouraging lower meat consumption, a food pattern which is easier to sustain. Because of their low income-elasticity, most staple foods would not see major declines in demand (at least at a macro level). - With a declining trend in prices of oil and a potential reduction in overall energy de- mand, there may be a reduction in the pric- es of bio-fuels as well, which in turn would affect the profitability and consequent de- mand for bio-fuel related products such as corn and sugarcane. Fertilizer costs are also likely to fall in line with fuel prices. - However, at the level of the poorest con- sumers, those in countries affected by the economic downturn may be less likely (be- cause of e.g. rising unemployment) to pur- chase enough staple food for themselves and their families, directly increasing the number of hungry people in the Asia Pa- cific region. - As noted in the paper, the recent boom in commodities futures is a result of declining confidence in the housing and financial markets. A further economic downswing, and recession in major economies, is likely to drive investors further into new mar- kets considered to be resilient, including food commodities. This is likely to result in increased price volatility, which will not only impact poor consumers (in the form of price spikes) but also inhibit producers from receiving accurate pricing signals on which to base their supply decisions. - A recessionary environment in major do- nor economies will inevitably result in less money being available for aid donation, as well as reduced interest by voters in inter- national affairs. This is likely to inhibit prog- ress on achieving the Millennium Develop- ment Goals, notably MDG1 on eliminating poverty and hunger. Potential linkages of the 2008 Global Recessionary trends on hunger 21 In some ways, the food price crisis has shifted the reference points for the major players in Doha Round negotiations on agriculture,that have been preoccupied for many years with the problems of low food prices. However, this shift has not facilitated a meeting of minds on the best way to proceed to ensure that international food policy brings benefits to all. Proponents of increased liberalisation point to rapid rate of economic growth in develop- ing countries following the introduction of the AoA, notably in the Asia Pacific region. They also highlight to the fact that the least developed countries tend to have the high- est barriers to trade. An FAO49 analysis of the incidence of hunger (as defined by the num- ber of underweight) in countries with varying degrees of agricultural trade openness (as defined by ratio of agricultural trade to agri- cultural GDP) shows that more open societ- ies are likely to have a smaller number of un- dernourished people. However, this relation may not be causal, and the results are highly dispersed, suggesting that liberalization may not bring benefits for all, and/ or that exter- nal factors such as market effectiveness may be critical. Most credible economic models50 predict that further reductions in US and EU do- mestic and export subsidies, and greater stringency in interpreting green and blue box measures, are likely to shift production towards the world\u2019s most efficient produc- ers, mostly Cairns group countries that are primarily developed or richer developing countries51. In Asia Pacific, these include Ma- laysia and Indonesia, the latter a moderately hungry nation52. However, Panagariya has emphasized that the overall effect of such reductions may well be a rise in prices53, which will impact nega- tively on food importers, such as Bangladesh, Malaysia, Philippines and Sri Lanka. He also notes that such as liberalization might also hurt those who currently benefit from buy- ing subsidized food imports at low cost, while selling their exports at artificially high prices within the EU through the Everything But Arms Initiative. This effect may not be pro- nounced in Asia Pacific, where most hungry nations do not export significant quantities of food; and where bulk of the agriculture produce is sold locally. Moreover, given the fact that the subsidies would be phased out gradually over a period of time and increased prices may lead to increased production, this could lead to an increase in agricultural pro- duction in the long term.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7f381edb-66c3-40e9-ac93-bea66f8bbefd": {"__data__": {"id_": "7f381edb-66c3-40e9-ac93-bea66f8bbefd", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1093b68cf18a521ec7fd4385c3617964e56e729705a5aef4c718b218feb6349d"}}, "hash": "1093b68cf18a521ec7fd4385c3617964e56e729705a5aef4c718b218feb6349d", "text": "An important question for policy makers therefore is which is their highest priority: low prices for consumers; living wages for producers; or efficient allocation of produc- tion. Reliance on low-cost imports may be a sustainable model for food importing de- veloping countries. However, it does rely on countries being able to pay for large scale food imports with exports in other sectors. It also places these countries at the mercy of volatility in world food prices, as recently ex- perienced. Most models suggest that the greatest po- tential for opening new export markets to 49 FAO 2005a. 50 It should be noted that models which have been used to generate the likely outcome of trade liberalization programmes are not sufficiently sophisticated to capture all variables and inter-relationships. Recent improvements in the methodology of such programmes have tended to revise downwards estimates of the potential benefits of trade. Additionally, models tend to look at aggregates rather than the effect on individual countries, nor on the effect on equality and hunger rather than pure growth. 51 Pangariya 2005. 52 i.e. 10-19.9 on the Global Hunger Index. 53 ibid. Diverse solutions for a fairer food policy architecture 22 developing countries is in lowering tariffs in developing countries themselves, opening the doors to greater inter-regional trade. This said, it is worth repeating that full trade liberalization is only likely to deliver the \u2018op- timal solution\u2019 in terms of global welfare if markets are functioning effectively54. As dis- cussed above, the global market in food does not currently function effectively. The risk is that further liberalization may result in losses for some developing countries, whether in terms of lost revenue to domestic farmers unable to compete with cheap imports, or increased price volatility. There are a range of measures, both national and international, which could be adopted to mitigate against these risks. These include, SP and SSM measures; increased reserve stocks of staple grains; controls on commod- ities futures markets; and promotion of im- port competing food products. These mea- sures could potentially be supplemented by further measures to offset historical market distortions (e.g. through implementation of Marrakesh Agreement promises to give developing countries the investment and technology they need to support their agri- cultural sectors). At the other end of the spectrum, advocates of food sovereignty have pushed for a freeze in further liberalization, or even a roll back of AoA provisions. They have instead empha- sized the importance of national production, and support of small farmers. They also cite the example of China, which arguably has a comparative disadvantage in grain produc- tion, but has yet invested heavily in produc- ing staple crops, achieving exceptional rates of growth but also a low hunger rate (less than 10 on the GHI compared with well over 20 in India, for example). On the other hand, Cambodia under the Khmer Rouge pursued an aggressive policy of self-sufficiency which resulted in the starvation of over a million people. Moreover, it is debatable whether complete isolation of national agricultural production is even possible. Ultimately, the focus for developing countries should still be on food security rather than food sovereign- ty. However, a credible food security plan is likely to include provisions for some domes- tic production of food. 54 Bhagwati 1971. 23 On 15th July, regional and international experts in the field of international food policy55 met at a Roundtable in Colombo to discuss how international food policy architecture could be realigned better to meet the needs of Asia Pacific\u2019s poor and hungry. Participants agreed that there was an urgent need to address hunger in the Asia Pacific context: there was a danger that hunger was seen as an African issue. Africa faced severe problems regarding poverty and hunger, but the majority of the world\u2019s hungry lived in Asia, and their circumstances differed from the hungry of Africa. It was crucial that their interests were not overlooked. There was broad agreement that it would be crucial for Asian governments to reverse past policies which had \u2018overshot\u2019 in terms of moving investment out of agriculture and into industry or social services. The re- sult has been that, for many in the Region, agriculture has faced chronic underinvest- ment, leading to low productivity and competitiveness. Given the heavy con- centration of small farmers amongst Asia\u2019s poor and hungry, governments needed to invest in infrastructure and micro-credit schemes, as well as ensure that market pricing signals are more accurately trans- mitted to small farmers. Agriculture had to be mainstreamed into development and economic strategies. The feeling was that developed countries had done this more successfully for their own agricultural", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "419ff481-19f2-4fbb-bd65-2cfa4dd6b8aa": {"__data__": {"id_": "419ff481-19f2-4fbb-bd65-2cfa4dd6b8aa", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "50cbd9ea74e99e96d9cd8da826d3342a54b369fe6c691e9bd136a48785d5c0bb"}, "3": {"node_id": "93f898b7-e6fe-4dce-bd6c-5a5d23f3c336", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "24d69fa8b1e4366240c8dddb3d7935e2e19247bf6d7b190bd134c62e05859036"}}, "hash": "66cd6212a5d4f30fde335ed3e01172d5d23e2f32fae0886c7ce714720e8726cf", "text": "sec- tors than had developing countries. However, while many of the key actions which could help combat hunger in the Region were the responsibility of national governments, participants emphasized the importance of creating an appropriate international policy space which would enable governments to rejuvenate their agricultural sectors. Historically, agricultural trade and other international food policies have tended to be set in reaction to short term triggers. For example, many of the Agreement on Agriculture provisions were set in a climate of low food prices, provoked by a fear that WTO members\u2019 markets would be flooded by cheap imports. Conversely, current discussion on future food policy has been dominated by discussions of how to miti- gate the spikes in staple food prices seen since late 2007. Yet, as this paper has dem- onstrated that the causes of hunger are not solely, or even primarily, determined by pricing issues. Policies need to be devel- oped which address the underlying causes of hunger, not just high prices. Central to this is stimulating the agricultural sectors of developing countries. As discussed above, for many years \u2018inter- national food policy architecture\u2019 has basi- cally been equated with agricultural trade policy. But recent developments have dem- onstrated that international food produc- tion mechanisms are vulnerable to threats which lie outside the sphere of trade. Chief among these is climate change, and, relat- ed to this, the sustainable use of water. Cli- mate change threatens to destabilize cur- rent locations for crop production, and to push overall patterns of production in Asia northwards. Already productive areas of India, Pakistan and China are placing huge demands on ground water supplies, and 55 Participants were: Lord Mark Malloch Brown, British Foreign Office Minister; Dr Saman Kelegama, Executive Director, Institute of Policy Studies, Sri Lanka; Dr Sandra Polaski, Carnegie Endowment; Dr Tim Lang, City University; Dr Biswajit Dhar, Professor and Head, WTO Centre, IIFT, India; Dr Safdar Sohail, Foreign Trade Institute of Pakistan, Islamabad; and Dr Supachai Panichpakdi, Secretary General UNCTAD and former DG WTO. Roundtable on international food architecture 24 any attempts to intensify production will need to be based on a more efficient use of water resources (which must also take into account cross border water security issues). New national approaches to agriculture will need to factor in increased risks aris- ing from climate related incidents, but even more crucial will be international efforts to mitigate the effects of climate change (and to encourage adaptation responses for vulnerable states). It is important that in- ternational policy makers understand that climate changes is as much a development issue as it is an environmental one. There is also scope for the international community to recognize the impact of factors such as di- ets rich in meats, dairy and refined sugars in the developed world on developing country producers, as well as demand for cash crops (including, but not limited to biofuels) and the impact this had on countries\u2019 abilities to produce food crops. The cross cutting nature of hunger needs to be better realized and reflected among the relevant international institutions. Some in- dividual institutions have already adopted a leadership role in this respect. For example, the WTO and UNCTAD have promoted for the Doha Round measures (such as SSMs and SPs) which protect rural livelihoods and enable the poor to feed themselves. How- ever, what is missing is a coherent interna- tional governance mechanism \u2013 a \u2018Consen- sus on Agriculture\u2019 or \u2018Security Council for Development\u2019. Until better co-ordination is achieved, there is still a danger that individ- ual actions taken by the international com- munity may conflict with measures taken in other fora. In particular, the international community should recognize explicitly the pivotal role played by small farmers in de- veloping country agricultural production, and ensure that their needs are adequately reflected in policy formulation. In the light of the heavy impact on many of Asia\u2019s poor of the recent food price crisis, par- ticularly for the urban poor and for net food importing countries, calls for greater protec- tionism were understandable. However, the indiscriminate adoption of measures such as export restrictions risked exacerbating price increases, especially for the poorest and least food-secure nations.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "93f898b7-e6fe-4dce-bd6c-5a5d23f3c336": {"__data__": {"id_": "93f898b7-e6fe-4dce-bd6c-5a5d23f3c336", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "50cbd9ea74e99e96d9cd8da826d3342a54b369fe6c691e9bd136a48785d5c0bb"}, "2": {"node_id": "419ff481-19f2-4fbb-bd65-2cfa4dd6b8aa", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "66cd6212a5d4f30fde335ed3e01172d5d23e2f32fae0886c7ce714720e8726cf"}}, "hash": "24d69fa8b1e4366240c8dddb3d7935e2e19247bf6d7b190bd134c62e05859036", "text": "Among the Roundtable participants, there was agree- ment that, while the promotion of a vibrant agricultural sector should form the key plank in most developing countries\u2019 response to hunger issues, this should not be equated with a policy which advocates complete self-sufficiency in food. This risked exposing consumers to even higher prices, and that overall levels of production would fall short of national need. It was equally important that developing countries did not", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9ab51ee4-6611-4173-b29f-0b56c62e7f17": {"__data__": {"id_": "9ab51ee4-6611-4173-b29f-0b56c62e7f17", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6e7f36aa111e23c79bb547235683d6de3245ad55e336f4888e8c9382723ac107"}}, "hash": "6e7f36aa111e23c79bb547235683d6de3245ad55e336f4888e8c9382723ac107", "text": "abandon Doha56, which offered a real opportunity to realign trade policy to be more responsive to developing country needs. But the Development Round has to be just that. The willingness of WTO members to al- low poorer countries apply Special Products and Special Safeguard Mechanisms in order to protect nascent agricultural development is critical. But significant challenges remain to ensuring these provisions are implement- ed in a way that helps the most needy. It will be important for the international commu- nity to orientate their discussion on these issues within the context of their vision for the realization of the Millennium Develop- ment Goals, rather than viewing simply as areas for concessions within a simple trade negotiation. The other key issue for discussion at Doha is the reduction of subsidies for developed countries. Again, it is important here that developed countries act in a manner which will allow agricultural production to devel- 56 Two weeks after the Roundtable, on 29th July 2008, Doha Trade talks in Geneva collapsed. 25 op along comparative advantage lines. As participants acknowledged, some de- veloped countries have a comparative advantage, and benefits from reductions in subsidies will not necessarily accrue pri- marily to the least developed countries. However, production along the lines of comparative advantage offers the best hope for stable levels of production and pricing. It was noted, however, that pat- terns of comparative advantage are likely to shift northwards over time due to cli- mate change. Some participants flagged the potential for more regional co-operation on food and agriculture, given that most staples consumed by Asians are produced with- in the Region. Such co-operation could take the form of a technical fund, a more effective seed bank which could provide a safety net in times of crisis, or regional trade agreements (however, on the lat- ter, thorough analysis would be needed on the likely costs and benefits of such an agreement). Participants agreed that there remained a critical role for donors in terms of in- vestment in agriculture in developing countries. International investment in agriculture has declined dramatically over the late twentieth and early twenty-first century, now accounting for only 6% of bilateral donor aid. Given the special role of agriculture in allowing the poor to meet their nutritional requirements, as well as to provide rural livelihoods, participants felt that this was a priority for donor aid strategies. An aggressive focus on agri- culture by the international community can help strengthen and support national rural strategies. Linked to this, there was an urgent need to increase investment in international bodies, such as IRRI, which could help increase productivity in Asian agriculture. Overall, participants were optimistic that a fairer deal for Asia\u2019s hungry could be achieved through a reconfiguration of the international food policy architecture, broadly defined to include aid and envi- ronmental issues as well as trade. But it would require active engagement, bet- ter co-ordination, and a willingness for all parties to adopt a visionary approach which focused on the long term need of \u2013 in particular \u2013 small farmers. 26 It is clear that the current state of food ar- chitecture is inadequate for protecting the economic and social rights of the world\u2019s hungry. The architects of the WTO and the Agreement on Agriculture wanted to cre- ate an international system which promot- ed equality and prosperity through trade liberalization and subsequent economic growth, based upon production along com- parative advantage lines. This vision has unfortunately not delivered \u2013 especially for the hundreds of millions of people living in poverty and hunger in Asia and other parts of the developing world. There are three main reasons for this, each of which has significant policy implica- tions for international and national policy makers. First, the theory of welfare gains along com- parative advantage lines assumes perfectly functioning markets. As discussed above, this is a flawed assumption. The persis- tence of trade-distorting subsidies and tar- iffs, combined with failures in market price transmission and the unique nature of food production in terms of supply side con- straints, income inelasticity of demand and the human cost of market distortions, com- bine to create massive market failures. The dominance of world agriculture by coun- tries which we would not expect to have a comparative advantage in agricultural pro- duction is a result of a combination of: 1. Remaining market distortions which benefit developed countries: It is in- disputable that most direct agricultural subsidies have been phased out by major OECD producers. However, considerable confusion exists over issues such as the trade distortion potential of green and blue box subsidies and of price baselines", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b12353e8-c268-4dd7-92c6-7631c255c371": {"__data__": {"id_": "b12353e8-c268-4dd7-92c6-7631c255c371", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7e8c2a80b16959c94bb9f00e0e8f1c655c6cf9704b3c082e1c79064105534a7e"}}, "hash": "7e8c2a80b16959c94bb9f00e0e8f1c655c6cf9704b3c082e1c79064105534a7e", "text": "used to calculate acceptable levels of support. Moreover, the concentration of (even much reduced) subsidies in a small number of large and powerfulcompanies also prevents developing countries from competing successfully. It is, therefore, crucial that the developed world acts to dismantle remaining distortions. 2. The legacy of historical market distor- tions, which have made developed countries more competitive: Decades of subsidized agriculture in developed economies have increased productivity of developed country agriculture, both through better technology, but also through economies of scale. This lat- ter was also achieved through market distortions caused in the past by large scale food aid and sale of staples at very low prices. Even if all existing subsidies were removed, it is unlikely that develop- ing country producers would be able to capture significant market share without measures to rebalance the playing field. 3. The legacy of sub-optimal national agricultural policies in developing countries which has hindered the de- velopment of competitive agricultural sectors: It is telling to note that while, in their drive to develop, developing economies considered agriculture to be too low down the value chain to be of interest, developed countries continued to nurture and protect their agricultural production. The significant underinvest- ment in agriculture by both domestic governments and aid donors is one of the major causes of trade distortion and hunger in the Asia Pacific region. Conclusions 27 4. High rates of tariff protection in de- veloping countries which may have hampered the development of intra- regional trade: Given the high levels of distortion existing at a global level, and the special characteristics of the rice trade (see Annex 2) which means that most rice is consumed in Asia, and that the market is very thin, regional trade holds much po- tential both for generating a profitable ex- port sector, and enhancing regional food security. However, high tariffs (as well as a lack of policy maker attention compared to regional trade in non-agricultural goods and services) have inhibited the growth of this sector. What does this mean for policy makers? Bhagwati recognized that when markets fail, increasing liberalization does not nec- essarily lead to welfare gains. But given the likelihood that demand for staple foods will continue to increase (due to, inter-alia, popu- lation growth and changing diets) it would seem sensible to encourage production of agricultural staples in those countries with a comparative advantage in such production. As discussed above, many developed coun- tries have forged a comparative advantage in crop production despite high land and la- bour costs. Nor does it seem likely that fur- ther trade liberalization in itself will provide the least developed nations with significant new market access (though gains to some richer developing countries are likely). How- ever, the experience of OECD producers, and of China who have both invested to produce a vibrant agricultural sector and reduced hunger among their poor, argues for a sub- stantially increased investment in agriculture for those countries with the potential to be- come effective producers. Only then can true patterns of comparative advantage become apparent. This should be facilitated by the removal of distortions which unfairly benefit richer producers. In the light of, in particular, the recent food price crisis, voices advocating a strict food sovereignty approach have argued that countries should retreat from the global trading system and produce their own food rather than importing from others. While this strategy may work for large countries, covering a diverse range of climatic zones, and those with reasonably good natural en- dowments for agricultural production, it is not a strategy which will end hunger for the majority. Moreover, even in more success- ful cases, countries will be heavily exposed to the risk of crop failure or natural disaster. Arguably, the current spike in rice prices has been exacerbated by the very thin market in rice, combined with \u2018beggar thy neighbour\u2019 policies such as export restrictions adopted by some. In the final analysis, the most im- portant factor is that food should reach the hungry, rather than where that food comes from. However, developed nations should recognize that the current trade system is unfairly slanted in favour of their interests. It is specially important that the voice of the developing country small holder is not lost in international trade negotiations on agri- culture. A fairer deal would allow small hold- ers the potential to increase their income through potentially larger markets (whether domestically or possibly through exports, particularly regional). Moreover ,the use of SSM and SP measures would allow such pro- ducers to mitigate against the risks of poten- tially devastating import surges and subse- quent price", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "df0ff417-fc12-45ba-a5d2-dd8cfc942b12": {"__data__": {"id_": "df0ff417-fc12-45ba-a5d2-dd8cfc942b12", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b85c8151efa2654f46f3f2db9a52366b821f3bab27ec9da2eb0ff18e462ea4d3"}, "3": {"node_id": "ef0c9c8c-a674-4851-b752-0403c9927a28", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "df7dcd2181947cc09aafc74ae26b0e5977f20c53992dea198930cacda2ddcf45"}}, "hash": "bfc6a635cb052efb2ec3c9a403d995c348138b615bc46abbdefb8ace03d44610", "text": "crashes. Secondly, it needs to be recognized that hun- ger in the Asia Pacific region (and elsewhere in the developing world) is in large part a result of \u2018overshooting\u2019 of historical policies which promoted industrial over agricultur- al production as the route out of poverty. Correcting several decades of neglect and underinvestment will take concerted and determined national action, with a focus on improving infrastructure (to minimize post- harvest losses and connect farmers to mar- kets), providing access to micro-finance for small farmers and technology transfer. 28 57 See Stern 2006. Such changes will be challenging, and will require the creation of appropriate inter- national policy space. Key to this will be ensuring that WTO members allow devel- oping countries to adapt to, and hopefully eventually benefit from, increased liberal- ization. Agreement on a comprehensive system of SSM and SP mechanisms which fully meet the needs of the most vulnerable nations in terms of hunger are essential to protect nascent agricultural sectors from surges. The international community can also support national efforts by providing financial aid \u2013 either by increasing direct aid to agriculture, or by funding research institutes such as IRRI. Increased investment in agriculture would offer huge benefits to small farmers. Better technology and access to inputs (particu- larly fertilizers at a stable price) would allow them to increase yields, directly enhanc- ing their ability to feed themselves (and, through selling their excesses) and their communities. Access to microfinance and microinsurance is particularly important in order to allow small farmers to invest in improvements, as well as to hedge against risks posed by climatic disturbances. Also critical are improvements in infrastructure such as roads \u2013 to connect farmers to mar- kets \u2013 and storage facilities to minimize post-harvest losses. These improvements are not only the responsibility of develop- ing country governments, but also the do- nor community that has a responsibility to reverse trends away from investment in the agricultural sector. The third major reason for the failure of the current international food policy architec- ture to deliver for the world\u2019s hungry is that it has treated food as primarily a trade issue. Trade is central to global agricultural pro- duction systems. But food, and the related issue of rural livelihoods, is a much broader issue, which encompasses development, international commodities trading, and, increasingly, the environment. Already, water scarcity and natural disasters such as flooding and drought threaten crop yields in many parts of Asia. These trends are likely to increase due to climate change57. It is vital that the international community increases the coherence of its food and ag- ricultural policies, to ensure that progress in one sphere is not undermined in another. Only in this way can the needs of small pro- ducers and others living in hunger in the Asia Pacific be fully reflected in the inter- national food policy architecture. The cur- rent Balkanisation of food policy, and the exclusion of the voice of small farmers from meaningful policy making, means that their needs are ignored in the current system. The existence of so many people in the Asia Pacific countries living in hunger reflects a massive failing of the international com- munity to deliver basic human rights. It is the responsibility of that community to pri- oritise the needs of these people above na- tional interests in remodeling international food architecture. 29 References ActionAid (2007) \u2018We know what we need: South Asian women speak out on climate change adaptation\u2019, Institute of Development Studies, November 2007 Anton , J. (2004) Analysis of the impact of decoupling: overview of on-going OECD work. Presentation at an Informal Expert Consultation on Domestic Support. FAO, Rome, 30-31 August 2004 Bandar, J.S. and Yu, W (2007) In Agricultural Trade: Planting the Seeds of Regional Lib- eralisation in Asia: A Study by the Asia-Pacific Research and Training Network\u2019 UNESCAP Studies in Trade and Investment 60 Bhagwati, J. (1971), \u201cThe generalized theory of distortions and welfare\u201d, in Bhagwati, J., et al., Trade Balance of Payments and Growth: Essays: Papers inInternational Economics in Honor of Charles P. Kindleberger, North-Holland Publishing Company, Amsterdam.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ef0c9c8c-a674-4851-b752-0403c9927a28": {"__data__": {"id_": "ef0c9c8c-a674-4851-b752-0403c9927a28", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "Unite