 "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rebuilding International Food Policy Architecture", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b9acd14e014b1bdbc3f0240cb0b88237e485ac20be2e075bdeaac69a47cf66ed"}, "3": {"node_id": "fb13ba36-c8ec-48c3-8ac8-ea3921373202", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "40cef5fd8b956a3b09ef7d8d3356092141fe6753a8cf9c103eb8a5a3396a52b2"}}, "hash": "5ed9ffea71a3b36a2e75667cd391b71ae5ee16311adbba5fc089e7e9e6469637", "text": "75% of the global rice export market. But the rice market is thin \u2013 only 6-7% of rice produced is traded, and this figure has remained consistent since the Agreement on Agriculture. This thinness means that new entrants into the import or export market can significantly affect the world price of rice. Rice in Asia is generally produced by small farmers with less than 1 hectare of land. Un- like other staple crops, rice is segmented into a large variety of types which are not easily interchangeable because of customer preferences. Farming is an inherently risky means of production, because effects such as climatic conditions can play a huge role in determining returns. However this type of small scale agriculture is particularly high in risk. Additionally, many of these farmers are relatively isolated from fluctuations in global rice markets because of poor infrastructure and/ or the influence of large agribusiness whose market dominance can be a bigger determinant of prices than changes in the market price. International trade in rice is characterized by high degrees of protection. The produc- tion is of rice is subsidized to some extent in most producing countries. The US, EU, Korea and Japan have the highest level of subsidy, though mostly in the form of WTO-permit- ted blue and green box measures. China provides significant direct payments to rice farmers. Tariffs and non-tariff barriers are high in most rice consuming countries \u2013 an average of 57% ad valorem bound rates, with higher rates for milled products. In practice, many countries in Asia Pacific are applying lower rates, especially since the price has risen. Only the EU subsidises rice exports, but many rice-producing Asia Pacific states have implemented export controls, especially since the food price crisis. Food aid from the US, EU and Japan accounts for around 5% of the world rice trade.There is also significant intervention in the market by state trading enterprises who procure grain to distribute domestically. According to the FAO1, models predict that full liberalization of the trade in rice would result in price increases of 10-14%, and an increase in the trade of rice by 29-47%. The results of partial liberalization, such as the removal of distorting measures in OECD pro- ducers, are less clear, with models predicting a price change range of -3% to 21%. Temperate parts of Asia are also significant producers of wheat, particularly South Asia, accounting for nearly 40% of world wheat ex- ports. The vast majority of diets in the region are grain-based, but 23% of protein needs in Asia are met from fish, whilst the increasing number of richer people in China and India has also driven increased consumption of animal protein. 58 2005a. Annex 2 RICE 34 In assessing comparative advantage in ag- riculture, we might begin by examining comparative yield rates. However, this is complicated by the fact that comparative advantage in agriculture is not static, but a result of previous approaches and policy on agriculture. These can include subsi- dies and other support (or alternatively, under-investment); as well as the applica- tion of new technologies (notably in cer- tain regions during the Green Revolution). In 2006, Asia as a whole showed slightly higher rice productivity than the world av- erage (4.181 t/ha compared with 4.11 t/ha). Within Asia, the most efficient producers of rice are China (6.27 t/ha), Japan (6.37 t/ ha), Korean Rep (6.60) Indonesia (4.77) and Vietnam (4.89). South Asia lags significantly from the rest of Asia, with the most efficient producer being Bangladesh (3.90). Even Japan and Korea lag significantly behind the world\u2019s most efficient producers such as Egypt (10.60), Greece (9,12) and the USA (7.69). However these figures only tell a par- tial story \u2013 as they ignore dynamic sources of comparative advantage. For instance, in 1961, China and Nepal had roughly compa- rable productivity (2.08 as opposed to 1.94 t/ha) but by 2006 China\u2019s productivity had nearly tripled to 6.27 t/ha whilst Nepal\u2019s had barely risen (to 2.72 t/ha). Moreover, even an examination of 1961 data (the earliest held by IRRI for most countries) tells only a partial story.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fb13ba36-c8ec-48c3-8ac8-ea3921373202": {"__data__": {"id_": "fb13ba36-c8ec-48c3-8ac8-ea3921373202", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rebuilding-international-food-policy-architecture", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": 