_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9f0fd2f05dc9be440b429d5ab483d19dfdd26fe1d9afe23dec69332aa6355506"}, "3": {"node_id": "30db0742-0084-4139-8ac2-9fc8efef730b", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "45be07a0f404f91d5213635f6a8541f7bb4290ebba90cfced609befaa8c42d6f"}}, "hash": "c9ed1ca6d236233a3d40833769e2938b70cfb24c043080107738ac0ddd2b1301", "text": "Working Draft Technical Report Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses UNDP Regional Centre in Asia and the Pacific December 2008 ii Contents 1. Introduction -------------------------------------------------------- 1 2. Trends in food and fuel prices Long \u2013Term Trends ------------------------------------------------ 5 Recent Trends------------------------------------------------------- 8 3. Underlying causes of soaring food and fuel prices Causes for rising food prices ------------------------------------- 12 Causes for rising fuel prices -------------------------------------- 24 4. Impact of soaring food and fuel prices at macro level -------- 28 5. Impact of soaring food and fuel prices at household level --- 50 6. Policy responses at the macro and sectoral levels ------------ 69 7. Key findings, recommendations and UNDP role ----------------- 87 References ---------------------------------------------------------- Annexes 1. Country experiences on food stamps systems------------- 2. Country experiences on food for work systems------------- 3. Country experiences on food public distribution systems----- 4. Country experiences on school feeding systems--------------- 5. Annex Tables and Charts -------------------------- Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses\u2217 1. Introduction Since 2001 the world has experienced a dramatic surge in the prices of oil, metals and agricultural commodities. Prices of these commodities reached record highs in 2008. The prices of oil and metals, which increased steadily but incrementally during 2001-2003, started rising rapidly since 2003. The price of oil has increased by 400% over the last five years - from about $30 a barrel in early 2003 to around $145 in June 2008.1 Metals\u2019 prices have also soared five-fold over the past six years, a rise that is unprecedented. Though prices of some food and agricultural raw materials started increasing since 2004, prices of most agricultural items started rising only from 2005. Initially agricultural prices increased gradually. But these started to increase rapidly from the mid-2007. In the recent months, the prices for major food commodities such as food grains and vegetable oils have risen sharply to historic highs of about 60 % above levels of just 2 years ago. The increases in commodity prices have not been uniform. However, increases have been broad-based covering all major commodity groups in the last 3 years. The impact taken together is much higher than individual price developments. In recent months, there is debate over the factors that have contributed to the dramatic rise of commodity prices, as well as the relative importance of each of the various factors. A review of earlier studies on the subject suggests the following causes for the food price increase: \u2022 a combination of sustained higher economic growth, rapid urbanization and changes in the consumption pattern in developing regions in the last decade led to higher demand for commodities, particularly non-food commodities; \u2022 a combination of high fuel prices as well as subsides and legislative mandates to increase production of bio-fuels led to an increased demand for food grains and oilseeds in recent years; \u2217 This report was prepared by Thangavel Palanivel, Senior Advisor, UNDP/RCC with inputs from RCB (Nandita Mongia, and Balachandra Patil) on the issues related to oil prices, RCC (Kirs ty Hayes, Biplove Choudhary, Taimur Khilji, and Kazuyuki Uji) on food safety net systems, macro policy responses and HIV/AIDS, and David Abbott of Pacific Centre on issues related to the Pacific Islands. This report, which is precursor for a short policy note on the Soaring Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific, was prepared under overall guidance of Dr. Ajay Chhibber, UN Assistant Secretary General and UNDP/RBAP Director. It is part of a large effort in the UNDP Regional Centres in Asia and the Pacific to analyse policy relevant topics rigorously with the best available information to support policy advisory services to countries in the region. The work has been facilitated by Omar Noman, Marcia Kran, Martin Krause, Caitlin Wiesen, Deodat Maharaj and Tanni Mukhopadhyay. The author would like to thank Sanath Manage and Indunil De Silva of the RCC/MDGI team for data collection and analysis. The author may be contacted at t.palanivel@undp.org for comments and suggestions. 1 With the world economies reeling under the fear of recession, the resulting decline in price is also equally sharp and has gone down below US$ 70 in November 2008.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "30db0742-0084-4139-8ac2-9fc8efef730b": {"__data__": {"id_": "30db0742-0084-4139-8ac2-9fc8efef730b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9f0fd2f05dc9be440b429d5ab483d19dfdd26fe1d9afe23dec69332aa6355506"}, "2": {"node_id": "48f58842-bafb-474e-814c-c75f8d282255", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c9ed1ca6d236233a3d40833769e2938b70cfb24c043080107738ac0ddd2b1301"}}, "hash": "45be07a0f404f91d5213635f6a8541f7bb4290ebba90cfced609befaa8c42d6f", "text": "Though the recent decline in oil prices has turned out be some kind of a solace for the countries of the region, the sharp depreciation of local currencies against US dollar in countries such as India, Nepal and Pakistan has negated some of these gains. Any suggested policy measures need to be robust enough to perform beneficially in the events of both oil price rise and decline. 2", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8cc99906-065c-4183-87b1-c904ab8c1de1": {"__data__": {"id_": "8cc99906-065c-4183-87b1-c904ab8c1de1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4886ee61097a1f6fd71c6a5e43e04031ba76151d28182ae86a46543f3e81e3ba"}}, "hash": "4886ee61097a1f6fd71c6a5e43e04031ba76151d28182ae86a46543f3e81e3ba", "text": "\u2022 higher oil prices that have raised prices for agricultural inputs such as fertilizer and fuel and thus cost of production and transportation of food products; \u2022 a sustained depreciation of the US dollar against other currencies in recent years added to the upward price pressure on dollar-denominated commodity prices directly, and indirectly fuelled speculative hedges against the declining dollar and low real interest rates; \u2022 short-term supply shocks due to adverse weather conditions; \u2022 declining real commodity prices in the last three decades together with slowing in agricultural public investment and stagnant land productivity growth in the last decade have reduced production incentives, which have led to sluggish agricultural growth; \u2022 declining stocks of food grains in recent years caused by demand outstripping supply; and \u2022 short-term trade policy changes such as increased restriction or ban on exports that in turn reduced supply availability in the world market. Rising food and oil prices have a significant impact on the economy and households. The impact, however, varies across countries and population groups. At the macro level, the impact of higher food and oil prices on the countries are likely to be very diverse, depending upon whether countries are Net Food Importing (NFIM) and Net Food Exporting (NFEX) countries as well as the relative weight of food and oil imports and exports in total imports or total domestic consumption or total domestic production. Net food and fuel exporting countries can benefit from improved terms of trade. By contrast, net food and oil importing countries are likely to suffer (UNCTAD, 2008). Soaring international food and oil prices are expected to undermine current macroeconomic stability in net importing countries by affecting inflation, economic growth, and fiscal and trade balances. These impacts are transmitted through supply, demand and the terms of trade mechanisms. In the exporting countries, supply (economic growth) could be accelerated through higher exports and greater investment. In the net importing countries, supply could suffer as production and transportation costs rise in the wake of an oil price shock. Oil and food price shocks also cause domestic price level to rise. The extent of the rise in inflation will depend on the share of food and oil in the consumption basket, as well as on the \u2018second round\u2019 effects. Rising domestic inflation and resulting high interest rates might affect consumption and investment scenarios adversely. The squeeze on consumption and investment demand might also affect GDP adversely. The price shocks affect the fiscal situation in several ways. On the expenditure side, there are fiscal costs when food and oil-importing countries do not adjust domestic prices of food and petroleum products in line with border prices. Costs also rise when domestic prices adjust to world food and oil prices, and governments then raise social benefit payments or other transfers to moderate the impact on consumers. On the revenue side, there could be revenue loss due to lowering and exemption of VAT, import tariffs and other taxes to mitigate the impact of higher world and domestic prices for food and petroleum products. Increases in oil and food prices also affect exports, imports and trade balance in many ways. The trade balance is expected to improve in food and oil exporting countries through the terms of trade effect, and to worsen in commodity importing countries due loss of export competitiveness and an increasing import bill. In addition to the financial burden of higher food and energy import bills, potential constraints on imports of necessities like food and raw materials have also sparked energy and food security concerns among importing countries. 3 At the micro level, the impact of higher food and oil prices on the households are likely to be very diverse, depending upon the reasons for the price change and on the structure of the economy (Ivanic and Martin, 2008). The impact could also vary depending upon household incomes and expenditures patterns, products involved, and policy responses of governments (World Bank 2008). Households usually spend about 40-60 % of their incomes on food items and therefore rising food prices are expected to increase households\u2019 consumption expenditure significantly. On the other hand, the incomes of farm households may be increased by higher food prices. Overall the impact of price shocks depends on whether the gains to farming households outweigh the adverse impact on consuming households. The benefits of higher food prices to average farm households may be less due to the limited extent of their net sales of food items. Since the majority of households, including in rural areas, are net buyers of food, the increase in food prices generally affects household consumption adversely.2", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2b15a733-6a1c-4104-bca9-5d772092525e": {"__data__": {"id_": "2b15a733-6a1c-4104-bca9-5d772092525e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "706556cf1a8811f55333b5f04b79e0f6bbf5a875382d50aeb01d78f3acb0d667"}}, "hash": "706556cf1a8811f55333b5f04b79e0f6bbf5a875382d50aeb01d78f3acb0d667", "text": "To maintain a basic diet, poor households, especially in urban areas, are forced to increase their food expenditures at the expense of non-food expenditures such as medical care and education. The increase in fuel price also affects households adversely through raising the cost of agricultural production. In addition, diverting food for bio-fuel production aggravates supply and demand imbalances. As poor households often spend about three fourths of their incomes on food, fuel and transport, soaring of food and oil prices jointly affect the poorest the most. This jeopardizes progress towards attaining the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs) by risking gains made in reducing poverty and in increasing social cohesion. Hence, it is not surprising that increasing food and oil prices have triggered riots in many developing countries. In order to mitigate adverse impact on consumers, governments intervene in food and energy markets in a variety of ways. Some governments in the food and oil importing countries directly intervene to control the quantity of imports as well as their distribution and prices. Some other governments allow the private sector to import and distribute food and petroleum products freely, but set price ceilings and compensate private sector distributors to cover any losses. In exporting countries, governments often set domestic prices below world levels, imposing an opportunity cost on farmers. Governments can also use fiscal and trade policies actively to mitigate the adverse impact of rising global food and oil prices. When rising food and oil prices cause an increase in overall inflation, countries\u2019 Central banks may be prompted to react with monetary tightening. At the same time, governments and central banks also need to protect the interest of domestic producers. This complicates the policy making process, as policy makers have to tread a fine line between containing inflation and supporting the growth process. While many of these issues are global in nature, there may be significant interregional and country differences in the impact and policy responses. To assess the impact and policy options, it is necessary to understand the causes of the high prices. This study, therefore, first examines the causes of rising commodity prices and then assesses the consequences of higher food and oil prices, as well as available policy responses. This study complements, rather than draws upon, the considerable body of analysis of food prices that has been undertaken in recent months by the World Bank and others. Some of the anecdotal information provided may not stand up to close scrutiny. Nevertheless, the analysis does provide a flavour of some of the issues that countries and households are currently facing as a result of soaring global food and fuel prices. 2 This may not be so true in rural Pacific households where often two -thirds to three-quarters of food consumed by the rural poor is from own production. 4 Chart 1: Long-Term Trends in Commodity Price Indices 0 100 200 300 400 500 1960 1963 1966 1969 1972 1975 1978 1981 1984 1987 1990 1993 1996 1999 2002 2005 2008 2000=100 Commodity Food Crude Oil Ag.Raw Metal This paper is thus organized as follows: To set the stage, recent trends in global food and oil prices as well as their long term trends are examined in Section 2. Section 3 discusses the causes of the recent surges in food and fuel prices by looking into global, regional (Asia- Pacific) and commodity specific factors. It also briefly looks into the future of food and oil markets in the context of the prospects of prices going forward or staying at higher level. Section 4 assesses the country and regional level macroeconomic impacts of rising food and oil prices on the economic growth, consumer price inflation, government revenue, public expenditure, fiscal balance, food and oil import bills, and current account balance in Asia- Pacific developing countries.3 This section also examines the extent to which increases in international food and oil prices have been transmitted to domestic prices in Asia and the Pacific countries. Section 5 assesses the household level impacts of the rise in food and oil prices, with a special focus on the incidence of poverty and inequality in Asia and the Pacific. Section 6 presents an overview of the policy responses adopted so far in Asia and the Pacific, with emphasis on fiscal, monetary and trade policies. Finally, section 7 provides some short- and long-term policy options at both national and regional levels to help mitigate the adverse impacts and take advantage of the emerging opportunities through investment aimed at improving productivity of agriculture and efficiency of energy consumption. This section also discusses the UNDP\u2019s work at the country and", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "33080e4c-5fd1-4355-a303-142617cd23da": {"__data__": {"id_": "33080e4c-5fd1-4355-a303-142617cd23da", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "170a52bac309c7be4babfdd6ade1ea100e8db0d6056567df3ed7b4e6e6b3b43d"}}, "hash": "170a52bac309c7be4babfdd6ade1ea100e8db0d6056567df3ed7b4e6e6b3b43d", "text": "regional level to support governments in responding food crisis and how this could be improved. 2. Trends in Commodity Prices 2.1. Long-Term Trends in commodity prices Let us examine the recent increase in commodity prices in a historical context based on the UNCTAD database. Chart 1 present the nominal price indices (2000=100) of major commodity groups - all commodity, food, crude oil, metals and agricultural raw materials from 1960 to 2008. Looking at historical price spikes, we notice the spikes in prices during the 1970s. It is clear from the chart that since 2001 there has been an upward trend in the nominal prices of major commodity groups. The current price spike like previous price shocks 1973-1974 and 1979-80 is broad-based covering all major commodity groups. The commodity price levels in recent years were generally higher than the previous peaks of the 1973-74, 1979-80 and mid-1990s. It is also clear that initially price indices started to rise gradually until 2005 and then climbing up rapidly. In 2008, price indices reached an all time high. 3 Due to data limitation, this assessment is done by a simple methodology of comparing pre and post price shock data instead of undertaking any comprehensive macroeconomic modelling exercise. 5 Chart 2 shows the nominal price for rice, wheat and maize4 over the period from 1960 to 2008. As seen, the recent price increases for rice, wheat and maize are quite dramatic and appear unparalleled over the past 50 years. Chart 2 also reveals that prices, particularly rice prices, have increased substantially during the early 1970s and early 1980s. The price indices in Chart 1 and 2 are in nominal terms, which may distort the picture. In order to get a more realistic impression of the burden commodity prices put on the economy and households, the price indices need to be adjusted for inflationary effects by an appropriate deflator.5 Since the US consumer price index captures better the changes in price of non-commodities and services, we use the US consumer price index as deflator. The deflated commodity price indices are given in Chart 3 and 4. Chart 3 shows that in real terms commodity prices were much higher in the past, especially during the years 1973-74 when OPEC countries imposed an oil embargo and during the years 1977-80- a period of very high inflation and negative political developments in Iran and Afghanistan. The 1973-74 event stands out. From 1972 to 1974 the price in real terms displayed a huge increase. The price remained at a high level for a few years, but eventually returned to its previous low levels in 1977. It is clear that since 1970s commodity prices (in comparison to the price of non-commodities and services) 4 Maize and corn are used interchangeably in this paper 5 The choice of deflator may be important in examining re al commodity price movements. Alternatives such as the CPI or GDP deflator or index of unit value of global exports will yield different estimates. Chart 4: Long-Term Trends in Real Prices of Cereals 0 250 500 750 1000 1960 1964 1968 1972 1976 1980 1984 1988 1992 1996 2000 2004 2008 2000=100 Rice Wheat Maize Chart 2: Long-Term Trends in Price Indices of Cereals 0 100 200 300 400 1960 1963 1966 1969 1972 1975 1978 1981 1984 1987 1990 1993 1996 1999 2002 2005 2008 2000=100 Rice Wheat Maize Chart 3: Long-Term Trends in Real Commodity Price Indices 0 100 200 300 400 500 600 700 1960 1964 1968 1972 1976 1980 1984 1988 1992 1996 2000 2004 2008 2000=100 Commodity Food Crude Oil AG.Raw Metal 6 Chart 6: Annual Changes in the Real Price of Food Item -50 -25 0 25 50 75 100 125 150 1961 1963 1965 1967 1969 1971 1973 1975 1977 1979 1981 1983 1985 1987 1989 1991 1993 1995 1997 1999 2001 2003 2005 2007 % Rice Wheat Maize have declined reaching an all-time low around 2000. In real terms, the recent price spike is less pronounced for all non-fuel commodity groups compared to 1970s level. But crude oil, the current prices in real terms are higher than those of earlier occasions. The current price in real terms is some 35 % above the earlier record high of 1979 (IMF 2008). Commodity prices in real terms have been much higher in the past, but they were also significantly lower in the 1980s and 1990s compared to current levels. Chart 4 presents the price trends in real terms for rice, wheat and maize. The recent price increases for rice, wheat and maize in real terms are not quite so", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "54cdfb12-e449-46cd-8d1b-5dc85ea6805d": {"__data__": {"id_": "54cdfb12-e449-46cd-8d1b-5dc85ea6805d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9f7d31787b08be5d24e8cccd744d0381cf5dad48867330b6cd47590d7a22af2e"}}, "hash": "9f7d31787b08be5d24e8cccd744d0381cf5dad48867330b6cd47590d7a22af2e", "text": "dramatic as when seen in nominal terms. Since 1973-74, food prices have declined reaching an all-time low around 2000. In real terms, the recent price spike is less pronounced for rice, wheat and maize compared to 1973-74. Chart 5 plots the annual change (i.e., percentage change over previous year) in the real commodity price indices for the period 1961 to 2008. As the Chart makes clear, recent increases in commodity prices are clearly not without precedent. Indeed, the 46 % rise that the commodity price index registered in 2008, the largest year-over- year increase in the current cycle, seems small compared to the 61 % spikes that occurred in 1973-1974. Similarly, the 36 % rise in the real food price index in 2008 is lower compared to the 68 % spikes in 1973-1974. This suggests that the year- over-year change in food prices in the recent years has not been as extreme as in 1973-1974. Chart 6 presents the annual change in the real prices of rice, wheat and maize for the period 1961 to 2008. The rate of increase in the rice price in 2008 is more or less matched with that of rice price spike in 1973-1974. However, the same is not the case for wheat and maize. For wheat, the 75 % rise in prices in 2008 is much higher compared to the 50 % spike in 1973-1974. The rate of increase in the price of maize in 2008 is also high compared to historical rises. It is also clear that the current price shock has two Chart 5: Annual Changes in the Real Prices of Commodities -40 -20 0 20 40 60 80 1961 1963 1965 1967 1969 1971 1973 1975 1977 1979 1981 1983 1985 1987 1989 1991 1993 1995 1997 1999 2001 2003 2005 2007 % Commodity Food AG.Raw Metal Chart 7: Annual Changes in the Price of Crude Oil -80 -40 0 40 80 120 160 200 240 280 1961 1963 1965 1967 1969 1971 1973 1975 1977 1979 1981 1983 1985 1987 1989 1991 1993 1995 1997 1999 2001 2003 2005 2007 % 7 phases: a gradual increase in basic food prices from 2003 to 2006 and then a rapid acceleration in price after 2007. Chart 7 plots the annual change in the real prices of crude oil for the period 1961 to 2008. The figure shows that the price of oil jumped sharply twice in the 1970s. In 1973-74, oil prices increased by an incredible 222% in real terms and 257 % in nominal terms. In this sense, the present price level is not unique. The increase in oil prices during 2003-08 occurred relatively gradually, allowing countries more time to adjust. For example, the oil prices in real terms rose by 13 % in 2003, 27 % in 2004 and 37% in 2005. Then it was decelerated to 16 and 8 % in 2007, before rising by a dramatic 69% in 2008. Though the real commodity prices have declined over the last four decades until recently, Charts 5 to 7 also confirm that volatility has increased in the recent decade. Volatility as measured by the annual changes in the real commodity prices over the past few decades reveals that volatility in the last decade is higher than in the 1980s and 1990s. Long term trends reveals that since 2001 commodity markets have been booming and the prices of commodities have reached new record highs during 2008. The exact beginning of the boom differs for each commodity. The rise in oil and metals prices started from 2003. Similarly, though prices of some agricultural commodities started increasing from 2004, prices of most agricultural items started rising only 2005 onwards. But it is clear that the price indices of all major commodity groups - foods, crude oil, metals and agricultural raw materials - have been increasing together over the last 3 years. In this regard, one can say that the current commodity price boom has been broad as it includes oil, metals, major Chart 10: Price level in 2008 compared to 2006 level, and to 2003 level (%) -50 0 50 100 150 200 250 300 2006-08 2003-08 Chart 9: Monthly Changes in the Prices of Food and Crude oil (YoY basis) -40 -20 0 20 40 60 80 100 2001-Jan 2001-Jul 2002-Jan 2002-Jul 2003-Jan 2003-Jul 2004-Jan 2004-Jul 2005-Jan 2005-Jul 2006-Jan 2006-Jul 2007-Jan 2007-Jul 2008-Jan 2008-Jul Food Crude Oil Chart 8: Recent Trends in Prices of Food & Crude Oil 0 20 40 60 80 100 120 140 2001-Jan 2001-Jul 2002-Jan 2002-Jul 2003-Jan 2003-Jul 2004-Jan 2004-Jul 2005-Jan 2005-Jul 2006-Jan 2006-Jul 2007-Jan 2007-Jul", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "65a5647c-99ca-455f-a2f8-17cfa1d90303": {"__data__": {"id_": "65a5647c-99ca-455f-a2f8-17cfa1d90303", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "