sed 15 % in 2007 and 42 % in 2008. Food price index increased by 57% over the 12 months period -between March 2007 and March 2008. The index value in 2008 had increased by 55% compared to the level just two years ago. Over the last five years, it has risen by 92% (chart 10). The price of oil has risen significantly \u2013From a relative \u201clow\u201d price of US$ 20 per barrel in December 2001, monthly average price of West Texas Intermediate (WTI) crude Oil rose to $30 a barrel in early 2003. The price of crude oil reached US$ 53 in October 2004 and US$74 per barrel in July 2006. It remained around US$70 in mid-2007, but it started rising rapidly to reach more than US$ 140 per barrel in mid-2008. It is clear that oil prices began their ascent in 2003, about the same time as other commodity prices. Over the last 5 years, the oil price has quadrupled. The oil price level in 2008 has increased by 75% compared to the level just 2 years before. Extreme volatility of oil prices \u2013 Unlike previous decades, the world has experienced a high volatility in oil price movements in the recent years. After surging to a then record US$77 per barrel in July 2006, the price of Chart 12: Monthly Changes in the Prices of Cereals (YoY basis) -50 0 50 100 150 200 250 2001-Jan 2001-Jul 2002-Jan 2002-Jul 2003-Jan 2003-Jul 2004-Jan 2004-Jul 2005-Jan 2005-Jul 2006-Jan 2006-Jul 2007-Jan 2007-Jul 2008-Jan 2008-Jul % Rice Wheat Maize 9 crude fell sharply reaching close to US$50 per barrel in January 2007, only to take off again in the next eighteen months and enter uncharted territory beyond US$145 per barrel in July 2008. Though the expectations were that prices would cross US$150 a barrel, the reverse happened. With the world economies reeling under the fear of recession, the resulting decline in price is also equally sharp and has gone down below US$ 70 in October 2008. Experience in recent years implies that any reasonable predictions on future oil prices can not be made. The price of cereals rose sharply -Cereals are the basic food commodities and on average they comprise about 46 % of the daily human calorie consumption in the world (FAO, 2003). Furthermore, cereals are a mainstay of animal feed from where meat and dairy products are derived. Even prices of other crops such as oilseeds are related to cereals prices through the competition for agricultural land. Rice is the most important and basic staple for over 2 billion people in Asia and the Pacific. Consequently, changes in cereal prices will affect the consumer as well as farmers in a significant manner. Therefore next few paragraphs analyse the changes in cereals prices in more detail. Chart 11 shows the development in monthly average world market price of rice, wheat, and maize in the period January 2001 \u2013 July 2008.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3a10f4bc-c832-4f54-a183-365b79cc3a3b": {"__data__": {"id_": "3a10f4bc-c832-4f54-a183-365b79cc3a3b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7c3b2462c66e5ea1d9cdd3ac46509976b6f402a74d852f8a74fe556d06283c05"}, "2": {"node_id": "65a5647c-99ca