s have two phases: a gradual increase in food prices during 2003-07 and a rapid acceleration in price increases after the mid 2007. The current commodity price shocks are unusual in several ways. The IMF (2008) and many others compare the current boom to previous episodes of rising commodity prices and shows that this boom has been notable for both its broad coverage and its duration.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f3fbbb93-ece4-4e9d-9f7a-bbfe7304066f": {"__data__": {"id_": "f3fbbb93-ece4-4e9d-9f7a-bbfe7304066f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d384e01b6850398f92725826f1e2d6b38333c8621563988b4b32dd3711a84654"}, "2": {"node_id": "eb015e66-4f0b-4dee-9b91-b855b47fec96", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fc89169a9de5c87fc8b1af6e582fc1f6454d46c3c891e9d062d7437cadd29bdf"}}, "hash": "86287683acd70c3e8360e9259b989352d6ea148aff5ad9c2df4412f0b16d8fe4", "text": "It has been large and rapid and in this respect is paralleled by only one other period during the last fifty years (in the 1970s) that was mainly driven by the temporary supply shortages of certain food and non-food items at the time. The present uptrend in commodity prices has lasted longer than previous cycles. That is the length of the current uptrend in commodity prices which has been in place since 2001 is unprecedented. The upswing continued even after global GDP growth", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "714fbce8-1bb7-411b-91a7-32e4c6895552": {"__data__": {"id_": "714fbce8-1bb7-411b-91a7-32e4c6895552", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "eab1b98d9fb9861a705b076dc9f3482bca69e5a62f5073421468fa1bf2d60bde"}}, "hash": "eab1b98d9fb9861a705b076dc9f3482bca69e5a62f5073421468fa1bf2d60bde", "text": "has started to slow down after mid- 2007. Nonetheless, the current boom, like its predecessors, will be reversed eventually as supply responses gain momentum, particularly in agricultural commodities, where long-term supply elasticity is relatively higher compared to crude oil. The price shock has also been accompanied by much higher price volatility than in the past, especially in the cereals and oilseeds sectors, highlighting the prevalence of greater uncertainty in the food markets. The oil prices have started moving down in the last 2 or 3 months. With the world economies reeling under the fear of recession, the resulting decline in price is also equally sharp and has gone down below US$ 70 in October 2008. Though the recent decline in prices has turned out be some kind of a solace for the countries of the region, the sharp increase US$ exchange rates with local currencies has negated some of these gains. Any suggested policy measures need to be robust enough to perform beneficially in the events of both oil price rise and decline. Though the recent decline in prices has turned out be some kind of a solace for the 11 countries of the region, the sharp increase US$ exchange rates with local currencies has negated some of these gains. 3. Underlying causes of food and oil price rises 3.1 Underlying causes of food price rises It is clear from section 2 that prices of food items have experienced a rapid increase over the last two years. Obviously the next question that needs to be examined is why food prices have gone up so dramatically? Recently, a number of studies attempted to analyze the underlying factors behind the soaring food prices. A review of earlier studies on the subject points to a complex set of supply and demand factors along with some trade and exchange rate factors. Most of the past studies recognize that the factors that were listed in the first page of the paper have contributed, either directly or indirectly, to soaring global food prices. But there are different opinions largely based on differing ideologies, as regards to the relative importance of these factors. An objective analysis is the only way to defuse these ideological claims. This section therefore attempts to provide such an objective assessment based on empirical evidence of the major driving forces of the rising international food prices. First let us analyze the factors that have affected the demand for food commodities. Changing consumption pattern \u2013 One of the demand factors that has been widely cited is the higher income and rapid urbanization in developing countries. Along with an absolute increase in the size of population, these changes in developing countries have all lead to growing food demand and dietary transition from cereals toward more animal protein. As per capita income rises and rapid urbanization takes place, people in developing countries are expected to increase per capita consumption of food grains by diversifying their diets towards meat and milk products. Although the household consumption of cereals tends to decline with rising incomes and the urbanization process, the use of grains as feed in livestock production increases, generating a net expansion in cereal demand. This is because it takes about 6-7 kilograms of grain to produce a single kilogram of meat (such as beef and pork). Thus the dietary shift from high dependency on grains towards meat and dairy products would be expected to increase overall demand for food grains. In the context, many studies argued that emerging and developing economies have been the main source of the growing demand for food commodities and for soaring global food prices. Available data do indicates that Chart 15: GDP Growth in the Regions & World -4 0 4 8 12 1981 1983 1985 1987 1989 1991 1993 1995 1997 1999 2001 2003 2005 2007 % World EAP LAC SA SSA Chart 16: Urbanisation Rate by the Regions 10 20 30 40 50 60 70 80 1981 1983 1985 1987 1989 1991 1993 1995 1997 1999 2001 2003 2005 2007 % EAP LAC SA SSA World 12 \u2022 Economic growth in emerging and developing regions has indeed been strong in the last decade. This is particularly so for East Asia and the Pacific, South Asia and Sub-Saharan Africa (Chart 15), which would have increased the purchasing power of the middle class; \u2022 Asia and the Pacific region, along with Africa, is still one of the least urbanized regions of the world. The urbanization process, however, has been growing at the fastest pace during the last two decades. In 1990, 33 % of the population of Asia lived", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "569a5d94-01fa-452d-b358-20f1b6e5cc9f": {"__data__": {"id_": "569a5d94-01fa-452d-b358-20f1b6e5cc9f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2d8feac021641a1aa710d29be2f9a244c7913f08ac9e010c8e107b928ab90f04"}}, "hash": "2d8feac021641a1aa710d29be2f9a244c7913f08ac9e010c8e107b928ab90f04", "text": "in urban areas, compared with 41 % in 2007 (Chart 16). This would have changed the consumer preferences towards meat and milk products. \u2022 The world\u2019s population growth rate has been trending down in the last two decades; this declining trend applies to nearly all regions of the world. In the recent decades, the population of Asia and the Pacific, and Latin America and the Caribbean has grown at almost the same pace, but at half the rate of Africa region (Chart 17). However, the number of people in developing regions is still rising by about 70-75 million per year. This rising population adds to the global demand for food and other products. \u2022 The growth rate of global production and consumption of meat products has been decelerated since 1996 (a period associated with higher GDP growth in the developing regions) compared to the period 1981-95 due to the slow down in global population growth. However, global meat consumption has still risen much more rapidly than consumption of food grains. During 1996 and 2008, consumption of meat products in the world increased by 2.5 % per year compared to 1.7 % observed for food grains. Since this was well above the world\u2019s population growth, per capita consumption of meat products must have increased. Available data do confirm that growth in meat production and Chart 17: Population Growth in the Regions & World 0.50 1.00 1.50 2.00 2.50 3.00 3.50 1981 1983 1985 1987 1989 1991 1993 1995 1997 1999 2001 2003 2005 2007 % World EAP LAC SA SSA Chart 18: Growth Rate of Production & Consumption of Meat Products -3 0 3 6 9 12 EA SA SEA AP LAC SSA MENA USSR DC NA EU Oceania World % Pro 81-95 Pro 96-08 Con 81-95 Con 96-08 Chart 19: Growth Rate of Production & Consumption of Dairy Products -2 0 2 4 6 8 10 EA SA AP LAC DC NA EU Oceania World % Pro 81-95 Pro 96-08 Con 81-95 Con 96-08 13 consumption has accelerated in most of developing and developed regions. The growth of meat production and consumption, however, has decelerated for developing regions as a whole mainly due to a strong deceleration experienced in East Asia. This (deceleration in meat consumption growth in East Asia) may be due to rapid slow down in population growth in China. \u2022 Growth rate of global consumption of dairy products has accelerated since 1996 in both developing countries as well as the world. The acceleration is more visible in East Asia. Available data also confirm that the growth rate in dairy production has also accelerated in developing regions and in the world. \u2022 Livestock feed account for around 65 % of total demand for maize, compared to 17 % of wheat and just 2 % of rice demand. This suggests that the higher growth in consumption of meat is likely to have the largest direct effect on consumption of maize rather than that of wheat and rice. Globally maize consumption indeed has increased at a faster rate (3.2%) during 1996-208 compared to the rate (1.8%) observed for1981-95. Available data, however, does not seem to support the argument that these changes have led to higher growth in the demand for maize in developing regions during the recent period. For example, in Asia and the Pacific as well as in Latin America and Caribbean, the annual growth in the corn (maize) consumption has decelerated from 3.3 % during 1981-95 to 2.8 % during 1996-08. Sub-Saharan Africa has also experienced a similar deceleration in corn consumption growth \u2013 from 2.9 % to 2.4% for the same period. This shows that although demand for animal products has increased recently, a corresponding increase has not taken place for animal feed in developing countries. The fact that there was no surge in use of corn for feeding in developing regions in the recent years implies that most livestock in developing countries are still feed mainly on crop by- products, household waste, and open grazing areas (Chart 20). The rate of growth in production and consumption of food grains has accelerated in the world since 1996 compared to 1981-1995 period. However, for developing countries as a whole, the rate of growth in foodgrains consumption has accelerated, Chart 20: Growth Rate of Production & Consumption of Corn -2 0 2 4 6 EA SA SEA AP LAC SSA MENA DC NA EU Oceania World % Pro 81-95 Pro 96-08 Con 81-95 Con 96-08 Chart 21: Growth rate of production & consumption of food grains -2 0 2 4 6 8 10 12 EA SA SEA", "start_char_idx": null, "en