n, but witnessed strong acceleration in the rate of growth of production. Sub- Saharan Africa witnessed acceleration in the growth of foodgrains production and consumption. The annual growth in the overall food grains consumption has decelerated in the Asia-Pacific - from 2.3 % during 1981-95 to 1.3 % during 1996-08. The situation for edible oil demand is also somewhat different since 1996\u2013 particularly in South Asia. There has been a significant deceleration in growth rate of edible oil production, while growth rate of consumption of edible oil products (oilseed, meals and oils) has accelerated dramatically resulting in huge imports of edible oil (Chart 22). As there has been a deceleration in consumption growth of maize and food grains (even after adjusting for animal feed) in many developing regions including Asia-Pacific, changes in per capita incomes and urbanization in developing regions arguably have not contributed for recent soaring of global food prices. Many experts and political leaders have suggested that growing prosperity in China and India as one of the reasons for rising food prices. But our analysis shows that the impact of these factors on food prices may be minimal and indirect. This is because (i) the demand for food items in China and India is in fact increasing at a much lower rate than the rest of the world, and (ii) they meet their slowly rising consumption demand through domestic production rather than imports (see Box 1). Chart 22: Growth rate of production & consumption of edible-oil -5 0 5 10 15 20 25 EA SA SEA AP LAC SSA MENA USSR DC NA EU Oceania World % Pro 81-95 Pro 96-08 Con 81-95 Con 96-08 15 Table 1: Per capita annual household consumption in China and India Urban \u2013 China Rural - China Product 1990 2006 Change in demand 1990 2006 Change in demand Feed-to- meat conversio n rates Change in cereal deman d Change in cereal deman d (kg) (kg) (kg) (kg) (kg) (kg) (kg) 1996 2006 Grain 131 76 -55 262 206 -56 -55 -56 Pork, beef, a