L": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a8a2d2f06f7938a66f46c356f1729b2b62c59185b217dcef6e22669f245f66a5"}, "2": {"node_id": "7cfbcd38-8865-4622-8338-8bc6b7770f1f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4b0c194c945b44f6b2e7f9e72bfc8ec02a06bb41fc97532e93a6ae55701b2300"}}, "hash": "9737694ccc7c8187d230e04a2695608bedc2f9a8d719a409c9519544dd45f8b3", "text": "First, it has been argued that sustained rapid economic growth in China and India, with nearly 40% of the world\u2019s population, has pushed up demand for food products. It has also been argued that growing", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c7b4cd2e-9f19-47f3-be9c-b90f125ce3b7": {"__data__": {"id_": "c7b4cd2e-9f19-47f3-be9c-b90f125ce3b7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ed3318fa4365ec92d37ec47d1fd918af0bf0813786ed2c3bc7f7a5eac4e374d4"}}, "hash": "ed3318fa4365ec92d37ec47d1fd918af0bf0813786ed2c3bc7f7a5eac4e374d4", "text": "middle class in India and China are end up eating more food on account of improving incomes, spending about 30-40% of their income on food grains, as against 10-15% in the developed world. Yet, available information indicates that the quantity of grains consumed has been declining rapidly with a rise in real per capita income in both China and India. The per capita annual consumption of cereals declined from 131 kg to 76 kg in urban China, and from 262 to 206 kg in rural China between 1990 and 2006. Similarly, the per capita annual consumption of cereals declined from 145 kg to 124 kg in urban India, and from 189 kg to 156 kg in rural India between 1988 and 2002. Some years ago experts have pointed out this paradox (i.e., higher incomes correlating with lower consumption of food grains). For example, Prof C.H. Hanumantha Rao 6 has found that the rural Indian poor were able to hold on to their former consumption levels, if they wanted to do so, but preferred to alter their consumption baskets in favour of other consumption items. The absolute drop in the per capita consumption of cereals in quantity terms was particularly pronounced as people moved from the lower to the middle levels of per capita consumption expenditure. Second, higher incomes in China and India mean higher consumption of meat products, which implies higher consumption of food grain\u2014as it takes about 6-7 kg of grain to produce 1 kg of meat. It is true higher incomes have made millions of people rich enough to afford meat and other foods. In 1990 the average rural Chinese ate 11 kg of meat a year; now he eats more than 17kg. In urban area, Chinese meat consumption has increased from 22 to 24 KG over the last 15 years. In this regard, China does play a dominant role in the world meat consumption. In India, per capita consumption of meats and fish rose from 20 kg to 24 kg in urban areas, and from 9 kg to 15 kg in rural households (Table 1). The rising incomes in these countries have not only led to more meat products, but more importantly led more consumption of milk, fruits, vegetables, and edible oils. The consumption of these items (dairy, fruits, vegetables and edible oil) has risen steadily as Chinese and Indian consumers improved their incomes. When it comes to meat consumption, India is different compared to China. India has a large vegetarian population, which limits rise in meat consumption. In India, beef and pork are not widely accepted partially due to religious preferences. But beef, pork and mutton are also expensive compared to poultry. In this regard, price also remains an important factor. Consequently, in India, consumption of poultry meat is growing faster than consumption of any other animal products (pork, beef, and mutton) in the last two decades. The share of dairy products in consumption has also increased in both rural and urban regions over this period: from 18.6% to 21.3% in urban households and from 14.3% to 17.4% in rural areas. This led to doubling of aggregate milk demand in India during the last two decades. Indian milk consumption amounted to 13% of the world's total and one third of milk consumption in all developing countries. As demand for milk products grows, livestock producers are likely to increase their use of cereal feeds. But as of now, only less than 10 million tons of cereals (less than 5 % of total cereal production) in India are fed to livestock each year\u2014most livestock still feed primarily on crop by-products, household waste, and open grazing areas. Moreover, China and India has been a net exporter of cereals in the last decade. China has been a net 6 in a paper `Declining demand for food grains in rural India: Causes and Explanations' 17 importer of food grains only one season - 2004-05. Similarly, India has been a net importer of cereals only once, in the 2006-07 season. In this context, the impact of China and India on world cereal prices may be minimal and indirect. However, as the consumption of meat, soybeans, edible oils and mineral products such as crude oil, steel, cement, aluminium and copper has increased rapidly in China a nd India, this could have contributed indirectly to increased food prices (The Economist, March 2008). Though both China and India witnessed a significant increase in their imports of oilseed, meals and edible oils in the last decade, there is no evidence that there has been a sudden increase in the imports from this source to", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4d9c6119-2c50-4c2c-8097-dc5d9d2b2d64": {"__data__": {"id_": "4d9c6119-2c50-4c2c-8097-dc5d9d2b2d64", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b2f8ed88e54c05615f1f392ff2439ab50a0d90332ed4b166740daff13a8b8e7c"}}, "hash": "b2f8ed88e54c05615f1f392ff2439ab50a0d90332ed4b166740daff13a8b8e7c", "text": "indicate that they have contributed to the recent price hike for oilseeds, meals or oils (FAO 2008). Since the change in diet in China and India has been slow and incremental, it cann ot explain the dramatic global food price movements of the past year. Increased bio fuels production has increased the demand for food commodities. Food and fuel prices have been increasingly inter-wined. High fuel prices have made agricultural production more expensive by raising the cost of food production and transportation. However, the main link between food and fuel prices is the competition between grain and oil seed for human food and animal feed, and their use for bio fuels. When crude oil prices started to increase from 2003, countries began to raise their bio fuel production. Brazil, a long-term player, accounts for a significant portion of the world\u2019s ethanol production and its production based on sugar cane. The U. S, which also accounts for the majority of world\u2019s ethanol production, mainly uses corn as a feedstock. The EU, the largest bio diesel producer, uses rapeseed oil is feedstock. China produces ethanol initially by using corn and wheat, but is now attempting to use cassava and sweet potatoes (Rosen and Shapouri, 2008). The issue is not limited to which crops and how much of them are used for bio fuels instead of food and feed, but how much planting area is diverted from producing other crops to those used as feedstock for production of bio fuels. For example, high maize prices since mid-2006 encouraged farmers in the US to plant more maize in 2007. Maize plantings increased by nearly 18 % in 2007 by reducing land allocated to soybeans and wheat.7 The decreasing level of production of wheat and soybeans was one reason for their sharp price increases in 2007. The surge in wheat prices is reflected in rice prices because wheat and rice are substitutes for each other. 7 Maize and rice are not in direct competition for land as they have different climatic requirements. Moreover, as rice is not used for bio fuel production and rice land is not easily switched to biofuel crops, the impact of biofuel use on rice market is less when compared to maize or oilseeds markets. 18 Historically, the amount of grain used to produce bio energy has been a small percentage of the global grain consumption. In the 1990s, the annual increase in grain used to produce bio fuel was relatively low. But in recent years this trend has been accelerated dramatically. The use of maize for ethanol grew especially rapidly from 2004 to 2007. The utilization of cereals globally for ethanol production has more than doubled in the last four years \u2013 from 43 million in 2004-05 to 95 million in 2007-08. In 2008-09, it is projected to increase to 124 million. It increased by 32% in 2007-08 and an estimated 31% in 2008-09 (Table 2). Between 2004 and 2007, use of maize for animal feed, which accounts for 65 % of global maize use, grew by only 1.5 % per year while maize use for ethanol grew by 36 % per year. This suggests that the emerging bio fuels market is a new and significant source of demand for maize, oil seeds and other agricultural commodities. The increase in demand for these commodities has been one of the leading factors behind the increase in their prices in world markets which, in turn, has led to higher food prices. A few studies attempted to apportion the share of the price increases that can be attributed to bio fuels. For example, The IMF estimated that the increased demand for bio fuels accounted for 70% of the increase in maize prices and 40% of the increase in soybean prices (Lipsky, 2008). Collins (2008) estimated that the increased demand for bio fuels accounted for 60% of the increase in maize prices for the period 2006-08. Rosegrant et al. (2008) calculated the increase demand bio fuel accounted for 30 % of the increase in real cereals prices, 39% of the increase in real maize prices, 22 of the increase in real wheat prices and 21% of the real rice prices for the period 2000-07. These increases in nominal prices of these commodities are much higher. The USDA also attributed much of the increase in farm prices of maize and soybeans to bio fuel production (Glauber, 2008). Estimates differ widely due to differences in time periods, prices, and food items considered. Despite all the differences, these studies unambiguously reveal that increased demand for bio fuel production is indeed a major driver of soaring", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "45b68b52-ef78-4a50-870c-74ba934e1a3a": {"__data__": {"id_": "45b68b52-ef78-4a50-870c-74ba934e1a3a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "37161f62ef82d482100ab53ab8893d14fcbacf1d37f3677f30696ee8174bd6bd"}, "3": {"node_id": "342986a3-1129-4cbf-a501-849c5bc4a260", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fbc73cfdcdc0bcf4ce6332cd3b63e51fd07f25f8b6a045b12860e53620ec36ba"}}, "hash": "dd1964d37a25637c009ac7fb3f1c30f513c05084cac05441993530d448b25e6b", "text": "global food prices. A recent World Bank paper (Mitchell 2008) has concluded that the most important factor for soaring global food prices was the large increase in bio fuel production from grains and oilseeds in the U.S. and EU. Without these increases, the paper added that \u201cglobal wheat and maize stocks would not have declined appreciably and price increases due to other demand and supply factors would have been moderate. Land use changes in wheat exporting countries in response to increased cultivation of oilseeds for bio diesel production limited expansion of wheat production that could have otherwise prevented the large declines in global wheat stocks and the resulting rise in wheat prices. The rapid rise in oilseed prices was caused mostly by demand for bio diesel production in response to incentives provided by policy Table 2: Utilization of Cereals for Ethanol production (2004/05 - 2008/09) 2004/05 2005/06 2006/07 2007/081) 2008/092) change in 2007/08 over 2006/07 change in 2008/09 over 2007/08 in Million Tons % % USA - All crops 34.1 41.3 54.5 76.8 101.7 40.9 32.4 USA \u2013 Corn 33.6 40.7 53.8 76.2 100.4 41.6 31.8 EU-27 1.1 3.2 3.4 2.9 5.2 -14.7 79.3 Canada 0.5 0.7 1.5 1.8 2.5 20.0 38.9 China 6.5 9.5 11.0 11.5 12.0 4.5 4.3 Other countries 0.8 1.1 1.4 1.9 2.4 35.7 26.3 Total 43.0 55.8 71.8 94.9 123.8 32.2 30.5 1) estimate, 2) projection Source: International Grain Council, June 2008 and Joachim von Braun (2008), Bio fuels, International Food Prices, and the Poor, International Food Policy Research Institute (IFPRI), Washington D.C, 19 changes in the EU beginning in 2001 and in the U.S. beginning in 2004. The large increase in rice prices was largely a response to the increase in wheat prices rather than to changes in rice production or stocks, and was thus indirectly related to the increase in bio fuels. Recent export bans on grains and speculative activity would probably not have occurred without the large price increases due to bio fuels production because they were largely responses to rising prices\u201d. The paper also showed that Brazilian ethanol production from sugar cane has not contributed appreciably to the recent increase in food commodities prices, because Brazilian sugar cane production has increased rapidly and sugar exports have nearly tripled since 2000. Brazil\u2019s share of global sugar exports increased from 20 % in 2000 to 40 % in 2007, and that was sufficient to keep sugar price increases small (Mitchell 2008). Even with record high fuel prices, grain-based bio fuel production would be significantly smaller if it was not driven by subsidies and mandates. Ethanol subsidies range from about US$0.30 to US$1.00 per litre, while the range of bio diesel subsidies is somewhat wider (FAO, 2008). Imposing mandatory blending targets (e.g. mandating that gasoline contains a minimum of 5 % bio ethanol) also encourage bio fuels production. Supply side factors It is clear from the above that demand for agricultural commodities has increased sharply in the last decade - mainly due to bio fuels production. Now let us analyse the supply side factors. At the macro level agricultural output expanded globally by an average of 2.0 % a year over the last 25 years, more than the population growth of 1.6 % a year. Developing countries achieved much faster agricultural growth (2.6 % a year) than developed countries (0.9 % a year) for the same period. The Asian economies accounted for two-thirds of the developing world\u2019s agricultural growth. This growth is mainly driven by increasing productivity rather than increasing land area (WDR 2008). Since 1996, however, agricultural growth, particularly food grains output growth has been decelerated substantially in Asia and the Pacific - from 2.7% per year in 1981-95 to 1.4 % per year in 1996-2008. Though deceleration in food grains growth has been broad based covering all sub-regions in Asia and the Pacific, the extent of deceleration was relatively high in East Asia.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "342986a3-1129-4cbf-a501-849c5bc4a260": {"__data__": {"id_": "342986a3-1129-4cbf-a501-849c5bc4a260", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "37161f62ef82d482100ab53ab8893d14fcbacf1d37f3677f30696ee8174bd6bd"}, "2": {"node_id": "45b68b52-ef78-4a50-870c-74ba934e1a3a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pac