o 6.4 % in 1990 to 2.5 % in the recent years. India also witnessed a similar decline. This trend will have to be reversed if countries are to accelerate Chart 24: Agriculture's share of Public Expenditure 0 5 10 15 20 Bangladesh China Fiji Indonesia Malaysia Nepal Philippines Sri Lanka % Early 1990s Early 2000s 21 agricultural productivity and growth in the region. The greatest impact on agricultural productivity comes from investment in rural roads, irrigation, village electrification, and from outlays on agricultural research and development and extension. The decline in agricultural productivity may also be an outcome of the long-term decline in real prices of foodgrains. Such a market environment provides little incentives for large scale private investment in agriculture which plays a complementary role to public investment in promoting agricultural productivity.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "89c41164-2983-4f47-80d3-77135f90d253": {"__data__": {"id_": "89c41164-2983-4f47-80d3-77135f90d253", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "545cbac13868cdc69d0efefcc96514259b402ab5aa520eadcd086d5cabb30e1a"}, "2": {"node_id": "a560c248-c191-4d3e-9cd1-9fed2613be7c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7fc8a088b46b93aa402941a0f4b9f39b9813cd7d03ceef30c6fb1ff121960df6"}}, "hash": "b2abd4f75e75457bb8e9b769df105e47730a8f558683095344ad792ec9c374a0", "text": "Diversification of agriculture into areas such as horticulture and livestock could also increase profit incentives. This may require intervention by the state initially in the process of marketing and in providing minimum support prices to help farmers manage the risks of moving into new economic activities. Weather-related production decline is another supply side factor that played a trigger role in the recent soaring food prices. Major exporting countries such as Australia and Canada experienced drought conditions causing declines in the production of cereals during 2005-06 (output reduced by 60%", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7fb097bb-ad35-4f83-8a20-7479cbcf75d6": {"__data__": {"id_": "7fb097bb-ad35-4f83-8a20-7479cbcf75d6", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5d0a6d05b4c4dfec3375dfabea5127987c577676b53eced99aa6637f4eaa41ee"}}, "hash": "5d0a6d05b4c4dfec3375dfabea5127987c577676b53eced99aa6637f4eaa41ee", "text": "for wheat and 51 % for coarse grains in Australia in 2006). Together, Australia, EU and USA produced 57 million tons less wheat and coarse grains in 2006 compared to 2005. Flooding in parts of South Asia reduced rice production in 2007. Consequently global food grains production declined by 1.3% in 2006, but there was a significant increase (4.7%) in 2007. Droughts reduced Australian grain exports by an average of 9-10 million tons per year in 2006 and 2007 compared to 2005, and poor crops production level in the EU and Ukraine reduced their exports by an additional 10 million tons in 2007. However, these declines were more than offset by higher growth in Argentina, Kazakhstan, Russia and the U.S. Total grain exports from these countries increased by about 22 million tons in 2007 compared to 2006. The quick supply response for cereals in 2007 came at the expense of reducing land allocated to oilseeds in some countries. The 2006 weather problems aggravated an existing situation of low stocks in many food commodities even further and helped to trigger the rapid rise in food prices. The gradual reduction in the level of food grains stocks since 2000 is another supply side factor that has had a significant impact on markets recently. Countries such as India reduced foodgrains stocks to reduce fiscal cost. International agencies particularly IFIs also encouraged such a move because of the perceived opportunity cost of holding big foodgrains stocks. This combination (trends of decelerating demand expansion with ever higher deceleration in production expansion) contributed to declining global demand for stocks of grains and oilseeds since 2000. The levels of food grains stock both at the globally and regionally have declined (Chart 25). Weather induced supply shocks in 2006 at recent low stock levels helped set the stage for rapid price hikes. Crude oil and its products are important inputs in agricultural production. Fossil fuels are not only used in powering farm machinery, but are also important inputs in the production of Chart 25: Food Grains Stocks as % of Consumption in the World 10 15 20 25 30 35 40 45 50 1981 1984 1987 1990 1993 1996 1999 2002 2005 2008 % Rice Wheat Corn Food grains 22 fertilizers and transportation of food grains. Available data show that fertilizer prices have risen enormously in recent years. Over the years, energy intensity of the agricultural sector has increased the cost of critical inputs like fertilizer, fuel, and power. In this context, rising energy prices and energy intensity of the agricultural production and thus increased production cost are additional supply side factor that could have also pushed food prices higher. The energy share of total crop production costs varies from country to country and from crop to crop, but available evidence indicates that it goes as high as 43 % (OECD 2006). Some studies conclude that oil prices and rising production and transportation costs have helped drive current food price increases. But many of these impacts occur with a significant lag. Higher crude oil prices have definitely pushed up the cost of agricultural production, but the long-term impact of these increases has yet to be felt. Short-term policy actions and exchange rate swings The explosive developments in the price of rice witnessed during the first four months of 2008 cannot be explained by market fundamentals alone (i.e. changes in demand and supply). The situation is mainly explained by a sense of panic spreading among the major rice exporting and importing countries (Slayton and Timmer, 2008). Short-term policy actions by some countries to isolate their domestic markets and protect their own consumers through export restraints also made the situation worse, as these measures (export bans and increased export taxes) exacerbated the short-run volatility of international food prices as well as increased uncertainty in the international food market. For example, faced with rising domestic prices and stimulated by events in other cereal markets, mainly wheat, rice exporting countries such as Cambodia, China, India, Pakistan and Viet Nam imposed export restrictions during September 2007 to April 2008. These export bans and price controls reduced supplies in the world rice markets and increased uncertainty about future rice supplies, contributing significantly to the surge in rice price especially since October 2007.8 Wheat exporting countries such as Kazakhstan, Ukraine, and Uzbekistan also imposed such bans. However, some of these restrictions have been withdrawn recently. Nonetheless, this contributed to wheat price volatility and uncertainty in the international wheat market. Exchange Rate movements Most commodities, including food grains and crude oil, are priced in U.S. dollars, but are purchased in the local currency. When", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "86b0e59e-add1-4109-b2ba-bbfafa79ba4f": {"__data__": {"id_": "86b0e59e-add1-4109-b2ba-bbfafa79ba4f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7ecf672baa92855e69bcf2a0875eeaf1a3254a8891621d4a5308fd97c3933e5e"}}, "hash": "7ecf672baa92855e69bcf2a0875eeaf1a3254a8891621d4a5308fd97c3933e5e", "text": "the dollar falls, as it has over the past six years, there is a link with rising commodity prices. The decline of the dollar is linked not only to higher demand for agricultural commodity exports, but also to higher prices. Beginning in 2002, the U.S. dollar began to depreciate, first against OECD country currencies, and later against many developing countries\u2019 currencies. As the dollar lost value relative to the currency of an importing country, it reduced that country\u2019s cost of importing. The decline of the US dollar against major currencies in the past few years has contributed to increase in the prices of food and other commodities. To sum up, a major factor pushing up international prices of basic foods has been the low level of exportable surpluses resulting from domestic utilization outstripping aggregate 8 Nepal relies upon rice imports from India. In a move to secure its own food supply, India banned rice exports in February 2008, leading to both rice shortages in Nepal and increased inflationary pressure on rice prices. Similarly, Bangladesh\u2019s dependence on rice imports has plunged the country into a crisis following India rice export ban, given it desperately needed food grains after Cyclone Sidr in December destroyed $600 million worth of its rice crop. 23 production growth for several crops in a number of major exporting countries. Diversifying diet patterns were not really the main cause of the sudden spike that began in 2006. Rather diverting food for bio-fuel production (due to rising crude oil price) is the primary reason for the sudden increase in the demand for food grains as well as the rapid increase in food prices. Restrictions on exports announced by major foodgrains-exporting nations such as Argentina, Kazakhstan and Russia for wheat and Cambodia, Egypt, India, Pakistan and Vietnam for rice continue, imposing pressures on the global food price inflation. Weather related production losses, surging oil prices and the weaker dollar have also fuelled speculative demand for agricultural products. The FAO has placed its latest forecast for world cereal production in 2008 at a record 2180 million tons, 2.8 % up from last year\u2019s record level as producers in all regions have responded to high market prices by increasing cereal cultivation. The bulk of the increase is expected in wheat which is forecast at 658 million tons, representing an increase of 8.3 % over the level in 2007. Global paddy production in 2008 may rise by 1.4 % to 666 million tons. The FAO\u2019s forecast for global coarse grains output in 2008 at 1078 million tons is virtually unchanged from last year\u2019s record high. The expected good harvest in the current year along with reduced fuel cost of inputs and reduced demand for bio-fuel production due to decline of oil prices may exert a dampening effect on food inflation. 3.2 Underlying causes of oil price rises9 Both structural factors and speculations have contributed to steep increases in crude oil prices. Important structural factors are growing demand, supply pressures and constraints, depleting reserves and turbulent geo-political situations. However, more recently speculative investments have played a key role in the oil futures market. More than causing the price rise, speculations have contributed to the volatility of prices, further complicating the problems of policy makers. Growth in world oil demand The rise in crude prices in recent years has been driven partly by the rapid growth in demand. The analysis of the last 10 years data on oil consumption (BP, 2008) shows this trend (Chart 26: World Crude Oil, consumption and production, 1990- 2007). The annual growth rate of oil consumption has accelerated from 1.1% during the first half (1997-2002) of last decade to 1.8 % during the second-half (2002-2008). Much of this growth in demand came from the United States and emerging economies such as Brazil, China and India. The countries of the Asia and the Pacific accounted for nearly half (47%) of the increase in oil consumption. This prompted increased production, thereby absorbing much of OPEC\u2019s surplus capacity and a looming fear of capacity constraints, making the oil market more vulnerable to supply-demand fluctuations. Chart 1 shows oil consumption to be consistently higher than that of oil supply. Before 2003, the gaps were due 9 This sub-section draws heavily on UNDP report \u201cOvercoming Vulnerability to Rising Oil Prices: Options for Asia and the Pacific\u201d, UNDP Regional Centre, Bangkok, 2007,with data updates where available 24 not to a real supply shortfall but mainly to the OPEC cartel\u2019s control of production. But in recent years, growth in demand is straining physical supply boundaries, as the supply gap is more real and market-determined. Since", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e7adf977-ab9b-4828-862e-fd4d50267400": {"__data__": {"id_": "e7adf977-ab9b-4828-862e-fd4d50267400", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b54743bc3efd7a3cb94f2854a130410a81fd00a90c68731bc4243bfbc682d78b"}, "3": {"node_id": "8228d3af-6e5a-45b4-84de-dc5d1c30c7fb", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a8a5bda2ac1846b262cd43d8ae2615a18b4f452e64fdabe689e39ce11e5ad2bb"}}, "hash": "f7e8a45e1f3b76531fb695443362f1d942f3827f155adff579aa3eda60a83818", "text": "2006, the supply and demand gap has been further widening. A closer look at the data suggests that China\u2019s demand for oil might have played a very significant role in contributing to the price rise starting in 2003 -2004. The annual growth in Chinese oil consumption has accelerated sharply from 3.1% during 1997-2001 to 8.5% in 2002, 9.7% in 2003 and 16.7% in 2004. Though the annual growth in China\u2019s oil consumption has sharply decelerated since 2004 but it is still high at about 5% providing enough cues for upward movement of prices (Chart 27: Annual growth rates in oil consumption and oil price). Consequently China accounted for about 36% of the increase in global oil consumption between 2001 and 2004. During the same period, the US consumption too increased by 3.5% (highest since the last 15 years). The rapid rise in oil demand in China and the US accompanied by similar record rise in oil demand from other economies caused the markets to move upward. Shrinking buffers In the past, fluctuations in oil supply and demand have been dampened by three main buffers: surplus production capacity among OPEC members, large oil inventories, and surplus refining capacity in consuming countries. All three buffers have, however, been shrinking. As a result, the world oil market has become more vulnerable to even slight change in supply and demand situations. The average surplus production capacity of 3.9 million barrels per day during 1996-2002 has now decreased to 1.9 million barrels per day in 2003 and then reaching a low level of 1.0 million barrels per day in 2005 (chart 28: World surplus crude oil production capacity). Subsequently it rose, reaching 2.2 million barrels per day in 2007, but is still relatively small (EIA, 2008). It is estimated to further reduce to 1.7 1.9 1.3 1.0 1.5 2.2 1.7 0.0 1.0 2.0 3.0 4.0 2003 2004 2005 2006 2007 2008 (est.) Million Barrels per Day 1996-2002 Historic Average (3.9 million bbl/d) 25 million barrels per day in 2008. Moreover, this surplus comes from just a few countries, notably Saudi Arabia and Iraq, so any problems with their exports will have major repercussions for the world oil market. A further cause of tightening oil markets is shrinking oil stocks (Chart 29: Difference in OECD oil inventories from 1996-2002 average stock levels). To cut costs, oil companies have been holding lower stocks of crude oil and gasoline. Compared with the average stock levels of 1996-2002, OECD stocks were at record lows in 2003. Though the situation improved since 2006, again during the first part of 2008, the inventory levels have fallen below the historical average. Refineries too are working with less slack. Despite rising demand, the oil companies have not been building many new refineries, preferring instead to reduce their surplus refining capacity. The combination of tighter supplies, and changing demand \u2013 or speculation about such changes \u2013 has made prices much more volatile when compared to earlier years of 2000 to 2004. Security and political issues Oil prices also have been affected by security and political issues, linked primarily to unstable situations in the Middle East. In May 2004, for example, oil facilities in Saudi Arabia suffered two terror attacks. These attacks did not reduce Saudi production significantly, but they did have a psychological impact, raising doubts about sustained oil supply causing price hikes. The situation in Iraq too contributed to the uncertainty. During the Iraq War, oil production fluctuated wildly before returning in March 2004 to pre-war level of 2.4 million barrels per day. Since then, deteriorating internal safety and terror attacks by insurgents on oil facilities have again undermined production. Such skirmishes have resulted in disruptions in oil supply. For example, on June 2006, a fire damaged the Khor al-Amaya oil export terminal in Iraq, forcing it to close. A mortar attack on November 2006 struck one of two crude oil processing plants at Iraq\u2019s Kirkuk field, cutting output at the field to 100,000 barrels/day from 300,000 barrels/day (Fattuh, 2007). The long-simmering political conflict between Iran and the US is also keep upward pressure on oil prices (Brown, et al, 2008). Short-term oil supply disturbances have also occurred in other parts of the world.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8228d3af-6e5a-45b4-84de-dc5d1c30c7fb": {"__data__": {"id_": "8228d3af-6e5a-45b4-84de-dc5d1c30c7fb", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b54743bc3efd7a3cb94f2854a130410a81fd00a90c68731bc4243bfbc682d78b"}, "2": {"node_id": "e7adf977-ab9b-4828-862e-fd4d50267400", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f7e8a45e1f3b76531fb695443362f1d942f3827f155adff579aa3eda60a83818"}}, "hash": "a8a5bda2ac1846b262cd43d8ae2615a18b4f452e64fdabe689e39ce11e5ad2bb", "text": "Short-term oil supply disturbances have also occurred in other parts of the world. For example, in 2004, legal problems with the government led to the collapse of Russia\u2019s largest oil company- Yukos; in Mexico, devastating hurricanes hit the oil-producing Mexican Gulf coast; and in Nigeria, intermittent militant attacks on facilities have made it more difficult to maintain supplies (Brown, et al, 2008). Since December 2005 Nigeria has experienced increased pipeline vandalism, kidnappings, and militant takeover of oil facilities in the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "660f93ed-88d3-4a98-9a30-b2ccfcb86bfa": {"__data__": {"id_": "660f93ed-88d3-4a98-9a30-b2ccfcb86bfa", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b8bd1be22cb287c22669d1afcd94c2df310cc54f58537ed453eb5d40d6667d35"}}, "hash": "b8bd1be22cb287c22669d1afcd94c2df310cc54f58537ed453eb5d40d6667d35", "text": "Niger Delta. As of April 2007, an estimated 587,000 barrels per day of crude production is shut-in (EIA, 2007). The situation has been further aggravated by the nationalization of oil and gas industries (e.g., Bolivia and Venezuela) or increased control of oil markets by governments (e.g., Russia). Furthermore, in some parts, notably Mexico and OECD Europe, production prospects are deteriorating because of low levels of investment in exploration. All these factors have been adversely affected overall oil supply. Buyers who fear the prospect of damage to oil facilities in the Middle East are prepared to pay more to secure supplies (OECD/IEA 2004) in other part of the world. This is said to be contributing to between 20 and 25% of the current oil price rise. Underinvestment in exploration and refining Over time, prices tend move upwards for extractive industries because resources need to be extracted from greater depths or less accessible fields. This is compounded by historic underinvestment in most extractive industries (because of initial high returns for low 26 investment). In the case of oil, key players in the global energy industry - OPEC national companies and the large multinational companies - failed to anticipate the growth in demand and did not sufficiently expand their output. Moreover additional capacity in the oil industry tends to come on stream only after a lag depending on the geological structures of the oil reserves. This made it difficult for suppliers to respond quickly to increasing demand. Indeed, at the end of the 20th Century, following the collapse of the oil price, they had often reduced or even stopped investment and then did not subsequently step up production as prices rose. Some argue that the recent price rises have actually served a useful purpose in stimulating investment across the oil supply chain. However, underinvestment in the oil sector may not simply be a case of inadequate response to rising demand, but rather a reflection of a general situation of uncertainty and price volatility, leading to a vicious circle whereby the lack of investment could once again propel prices upwards. As well as underinvestment in exploration, there has also been inadequate investment in refining capacity, particularly for the lighter products that have to be processed out of heavy/sour crude: mainly gasoline, diesel and ATF. Speculation in the world oil market Oil supply-demand imbalances and uncertainties have been exacerbated by a massive influx of speculative money into the market for crude oil futures. Speculators, reacting to vulnerabilities in supply and external shocks, have expanded their trading, often basing their judgments on media reports. In so doing, they have heightened the price volatility in the short-run. Speculative activity can push oil prices higher, since this unstable situation adds a larger \u2018risk premium.\u2019 Over the short term, futures prices thus may be subject to excessive hikes that bear no direct relation to current supply or demand fundamentals. However, these prices can themselves trigger further changes in supply or demand situation, leading to another round of wild fluctuations. Oil price hikes also incorporate an element of \u2018geopolitical risk premium.\u2019 Some experts hold the speculative trading solely responsible for the price rise and according to them, if purely based on supply and demand fundamentals, the current crude-oil prices should not be above US$ 60 per barrel. Large multinational energy trading firms have been mentioned for such a situation. For example, in June 2006, oil traded in futures markets at about US$ 60 a barrel and at that time, the US Senate investigation estimated that some US$ 25 of that was due to pure financial speculation (Engdahl, 2008). Similarly, an analyst estimated in August 2005 that US oil inventory levels suggested WTI crude prices should be around $25 a barrel, and not US$ 60 prevailing at that time. Extending the logic, that would be equal to a present day share of US$ 50 to US$ 60 or more of today\u2019s US $115 a barrel price is due to pure hedge fund and speculation by financial institutions. Given the unchanged equilibrium in global oil supply and demand amid the explosive rise in oil futures prices traded on NYMEX and ICE exchanges in New York and London in the first half of 2008, it is likely that as much as 60% of the oil price is pure speculation (Engdahl, 2008). There are contradictory views too, which claim that speculating/hedging activity accounts for a mere 3 to 4 % of the total price (Hutter, 2008). According to Hutter (2008), the extraction cost accounts for 34% of the oil price and the major factors contributing to the steep price rise are windfall", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "32d06521-d3ef-4d8e-9eab-e7642529e183": {"__data__": {"id_": "32d06521-d3ef-4d8e-9eab-e7642529e183", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "