ed international policy dialogue, and for identifying actions that it can take, in collaboration with its member governments, at national and regional levels. 4.1 Net Importing and Net Exporting Countries At the macro level, the impacts of higher food and oil prices on countries are likely to be diverse depending upon whether countries are net importing or net exporting countries as well as the relative share of net food and oil exports (exports-imports) in total imports or total domestic consumption or total domestic production. In this context, it is necessary to identify which countries are net food exporters or net food importers. A recent World Bank study classifies 196 countries according to net food trade status (NG & Aksoy, 2008). It shows that two thirds of the countries (131 out of 196) in the world are net food importers. It also shows that as many as 42 out of 58 low-income countries and 69 out of 105 middle-income countries are net food importers. Even among the high-income countries, 20 out of 33 are net food importers (Table 4). In terms of percentages, 61 % of high income countries, 66 % of middle-income countries, and 72 % of low-income countries are net food importers. Table 4: Country Classifications by Raw Food Trade (2004/05) No. of Countries Net Exports as % of All Goods Imports Country Group Net food Exporter Net food Importer Total 1980/81 1990/91 2000/01 2004/05 High income 13 20 33 0.8 0.3 0.3 0.1 Middle-income, all 36 69 105 -3.4 -0.6 -0.1 0.1 Oil Exporters 3 17 20 -4.4 -4.5 -3.6 -2.8 Small Islanders 5 25 30 -2.9 -1.6 -1.5 -1.8 Low-income, all 16 42 58 -2.0 -0.6 0.0 -0.2 Oil Exporters 2 5 7 -3.4 -2.8 -4.8 -4.6 World, Total 65 131 196 Source: Francis NG & M. Ataman Aksoy, \u201cWho Are the Net Food Importing Countries\u201d, Policy Research Working Paper 4457, The World Bank, Jan 2008. Available data also show that the group of middle-income countries has switched from being a large net importer in 1980/81 to a marginal net exporter in 2004/05 (Table 4). The group average disguises large net imports by oil exporters and small island economies. The group of low-income countries has also witnessed an improvement in their food trade deficits from 2.0 % of its imports in 1980/81 to 0.2 % in 2004/05. Low-income countries, which are not oil- exporting and not in conflict, turned out to be net food exporters (NG & Aksoy, 2008). Countries that have net food imports of more than 5 % of their total imports will be considered as potentially vulnerable to soaring food prices. This is because a 50 % increase in food prices, as actually happened recently, with net food imports of more than 5 % (but less than 10 %) imports will have an impact equivalent to about 3-5 % of the imports bill. Countries that have net food imports of more than 10 % of total imports will be viewed as highly vulnerable because a 50 % increase in food prices with net food imports of more than 28 10 % imports will have an impact equivalent to more than 5 % of their imports bill. There are 20 low-income countries whose food trade deficits are more than 5 % of their total imports.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "116c4e04-b9bc-4d1e-b1ed-5b44ef9a4721": {"__data__": {"id_": "116c4e04-b9bc-4d1e-b1ed-5b44ef9a4721", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-f