rts) as % of domestic consumption. If this figure is close to zero, then most of the domestic food consumption has been supplied from domestic produced rather than imports. On the other hand, if it is close to 100, then the most domestic consumption comes from imports. The IDR can be calculated for individual commodities and groups of commodities. Table 8: Food Import Dependency in Asia and the Pacific during the last five years 2003-07 Food grains Cereals Rice Wheat Corn High import dependency countries - more than 60 % of domestic consumption are from imports Papua New Guinea, Fiji, Malaysia, Rep Korea, Mongolia Papua New Guinea, Malaysia Indonesia, Vietnam, Sri Lanka, Malaysia, Thailand, Philippines, Mongolia, Bangladesh, Rep Korea, PNG Malaysia Modest import dependency countries - more than 10 % but less than 60% of domestic consumption are from imports Sri Lanka, Philippines, DPR Korea, Iran, Afghanistan, Indonesia Malaysia, Rep Korea, Mongolia, Sri Lanka, Bhutan, Philippines, DPR Korea, Indonesia Iran, PNG, Malaysia, DPR Korea, Iran, Philippines DPR Korea, Bhutan Rep Korea, Bangladesh, Iran, DPR Korea, Indonesia, Vietnam Low import dependency countries - less than 10% of domestic consumption are from imports Bangladesh, Bhutan, Nepal, Laos Bangladesh, Nepal, Afghanistan Mongolia, Sri Lanka, Bangladesh, Indonesia, Nepal, LAOPDR, Fiji, Rep Korea Iran, Nepal, Pakistan, China Philippines, Nepal, Pakistan, Bhutan, Afghanistan, Fiji Source: Estimated from data obtained from USDA database Similarly, for net food exporting countries, questions such as how much of the domestic food production has been exported and how much has been used for the country\u2019s own consumption need to be analysed to assess their potential gains from changes in food prices. The Exports Orientation Ratio (EOR) can answer these questions. It could be defined as net exports (exports \u2013imports) as % of domestic production.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "