eport"}, "hash": "2e5abf677741100460b79e063bfc59b6f0d2675a23e1feb56efafdb5fd44a268"}, "2": {"node_id": "3c5c285b-2946-488f-8029-547e5f1b91c4", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "49cc3b0b7942484c946ea5556d391c5c4a65e15f3c2cec6971a89fd0a7f95985"}}, "hash": "ee4b8315532e64ecef2f6dd2944b16ba13be1934fc76d4b44592dbbf03f1b629", "text": "South Asia witnessed a fluctuating net food trade situation: moving from a food trade deficit (0.2% of GDP) region in 2000 to a food surplus region (0.1% of GDP) in 2006. Again, in 2007, it moved back to a food trade deficits region (0.1% of GDP). Net food imports of West Asia fell from 1.7 % of GDP in 2000 to 1.1 % in 2007. Similarly, net food imports of the Pacific decreased from 1.9 % of GDP in 2000 to 1.5 % in 2007 (UNCTAD, 2008). Some countries in the region produce crude oil. This includes Iran, China, India, Indonesia, Malaysia, Vietnam, Brunei Darussalam, Thailand, Papua New Guinea (PNG), and Timor- Leste. Out of this, only some countries are net oil exports. These few will realize large benefits from the high prices. Countries such as Mongolia and PNG are also benefiting from the surge in gold and copper prices. For Timor-Leste, government revenue from crude oil exports rose very significantly in 2007, while in Mongolia and PNG, government revenue from mineral exports rose substantially. In Timor-Leste and PNG, the high prices of exports will more than offset the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a46451fb-c13a-4857-a63b-3f622ceaef0b": {"__data__": {"id_": "a46451fb-c13a-4857-a63b-3f622ceaef0b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c87e7cad9292053359347c2e82d27d08f92a557bce716488595c21ee74ac2ff4"}}, "hash": "c87e7cad9292053359347c2e82d27d08f92a557bce716488595c21ee74ac2ff4", "text": "effect of high prices of imported food and petroleum products and in net terms they are large winners. For PNG the ADB (2008) estimates show that price increases for its exports has added almost 45 to GNI since 2006. This compares with a negative impact averaging between 5 and 6% and of GNI for other Pacific economies. 4.3 Terms of trade and income distribution between countries At the international level, the soaring global food and fuel prices is expected to affect income distribution among countries. The inter-country income distribution effects are largely determined by the changes in the terms of trade, which is the ratio between the prices of exports and the prices of imports. The changes in the terms of trade themselves vary depending upon countries trade structure and relative weights in the total trade. An improvement in the terms-of-trade for a country or group of countries indicates a relative increase in real income, where as deterioration in the terms-of-trade indicates a relative loss of real income. Available data (UNCTD 2008) show that trends in the terms-of-trade have changed significantly in the last decade because of sharp increase in the prices of commodities compared to manufactures. At the regional level, Middle East and North Africa, which includes several major petroleum exporters, is the region that experienced the most impressive improvement in terms of trade. Sub-Saharan Africa (SSA) region also benefited from the rise in the prices of oil and mining products as well as prices of agricultural products. However, the gains for the region were not evenly distributed. The situation of 24 sub-Saharan countries that do not export fuels or mining products has actually deteriorated, as the prices of their agricultural raw material exports have been outpaced by those of their imports (fuels, food and capital good items). Latin America and the Caribbean region also witnessed improvement in terms of trade, although more moderate than those of SSA and MENA. Gains have been bigger in South America, while most Central American and several 34 Caribbean countries (most of which depend heavily on the import of fuel) have suffered losses from their terms of trade. Finally, Eastern, South-Eastern and Southern Asian countries show a significant deterioration in their terms of trade, owing to their dependence on the imports of energy and industrial raw materials and their specialization in labour-intensive manufactures exports. The UNCTAD report also indicates that developing manufactures exporters suffered losses from changes in their terms of trade equivalent to 1.2 % of GDP per year during 2004 -06. On the other hand, oil exporters and exporters of mining products obtained windfall revenues from improving terms of trade, exceeding 7 and 5 % of GDP per year, respectively. The terms of trade of transition economies comprised of former USSR and allies such as Russian Federation, Kazakhstan, Azerbaijan and Mongolia have improved due to exports of oil, gas, and other mineral or mining products. Most of the Asia-Pacific countries experienced adverse terms-of-trade arising from high commodity prices. Only countries such as Brunei Darussalam, Indonesia, Iran, Malaysia, Mongolia, Myanmar, PNG, Timor Leste, and Viet Nam who are net exporters of commodities would have faced neutral effects or some gains from the terms of trade movements. The deterioration of the terms of trade has already begun to affect exchange rates in some countries such as India, Pakistan and Nepal. The terms of trade losses have also impacted the external positions (current account balance) of economies that are net commodity importers. However, as exports remained resilient in many Asia and the Pacific countries despite a slowing US economy and capitals are still flowing into the region, current account position has not moved into dangerous levels. The FAO has identified 82 \u201clow-income food importers\u201d that are vulnerable to food price hikes. For 48 of these countries, which do not export oil or minerals and mining products, food price increases have led to deterioration in the terms of trade by 20 % since 2001. In the remaining 34 countries, the terms of trade effect was offset by substantial increases in the prices of the oil or minerals and mining exports (UNCTAD, 2008). The adverse terms-of-trade effects of higher food prices have also been mitigated, to some extent, by rising non-food commodity prices in countries. When all primary commodity price changes are considered, the terms-of-trade impacts become large and positive for resource rich countries as exports of oil (Iran) and other commodities (Malaysia, Mongolia and PNG) more than compensate for higher food prices. Consequently balance of payments has not been adversely affected. 4.4 Transmission of world food and fuel prices on domestic consumer prices", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f495783d-6c2f-47d8-9859-1a8b09353d43": {"__data__": {"id_": "f495783d-6c2f-47d8-9859-1a8b09353d43", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "54344a3228147b658cd8a3d618b20f15ba07e3024145f8695b64f0dfc58df922"}, "3": {"node_id": "07bcc184-f022-4c33-b2b2-9850c46f5a0c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "037cfb58175402d55ada681efc88d881c7d71f226df6a5e074c30251d259fbde"}}, "hash": "7361be34db47b578e99eca5024eb1a19a5c27841d8d22e498eb282ba217d99fd", "text": "The impact of higher international food and fuel prices on domestic economies will depend on the extent to which changes in world prices have been transmitted to domestic economies in recent years. In an open economy, movement in domestic prices of food and fuels depends on the behaviour of world prices. The pass through, however, is often incomplete and may be influenced by administrative and fiscal interventions. The depreciation of the US dollar against many Asian currencies also tends to reduce transmission of world market prices to domestic markets. An indicator of the extent to which soaring food and fuel prices are being transmitted into domestic retails markets is the \u2018pass-through coefficient\u2019. This is the ratio of the cumulative 35 annual rates of change in domestic retail prices over a given period to the cumulative annual rates of change in corresponding international prices during the same period. The pass- through coefficient usually ranges from 0 to 1 (or 0 to 100 in percentage terms) implying that international price movements would not transmit fully to domestic prices in a short run. A pass-through value of 1 indicates that international price movements are transmitted fully to domestic prices, while the value of zero indicates that international price movements have not been transmitted to domestic prices. In some cases, changes in domestic prices are not related to events on international markets. In these cases, pass-through value of more than 1 may happen, implying that a higher rate of change in domestic prices than international prices. It may be noted that pass-through of global prices to higher domestic prices, though not necessarily immediate, is ultimately unavoidable. Efficiency considerations require full pass-through, as this encourages appropriate responses by consumers and producers and mitigates macro impact. But at the same time full pass- through decreases the real incomes of many households with adverse poverty impacts that require mitigating measures. Regulation of pass-through is typically done through providing subsidies to producers and traders; reducing in import tariffs and sales (VAT) tax rate; implementing price control; adjusting exchange rate, etc. It is clear that less than full pass- through involves huge fiscal subsidies which could crowd-out other critical public expenditures such as basic education and primary health. Reducing taxes results in forgone revenues and price controls result in escalating subsidies. Moreover, studies indicate that benefits of universal subsidies, tax reduction and price control are likely go mainly to higher income groups reflecting unequal distribution of consumption. For pass through analysis, assessment must be done at country level, because different countries have experienced different exchange rate movements and adopted different policy responses. Table 11: Pass-Through Coefficients for food prices during 2006-08 Country Cumulative Change in domestic food prices Cumulative Change in world food prices Cumulative Changes in Exchange Rate World prices adjusted for exchange rate changes Domestic price to world price (%) (Col-2/Col-5) Col: 1 2 3 4 5 6 Mongolia 60.5 67.4 -5.0 62.3 96.9 Sri Lanka 55.5 67.4 6.6 74.0 75.0 Maldives 45.0 67.4 1.1 68.6 65.6 Pakistan 40.7 67.4 27.2 94.6 43.0 Indonesia 35.5 67.4 -3.7 63.7 55.7 China 34.1 67.4 -17.4 50.0 68.2 Nepal 28.4 67.4 9.1 76.5 37.1 Bangladesh 28.1 67.4 6.5 74.0 38.0 India 21.9 67.4 4.6 72.0 30.4 Philippines 19.2 67.4 -25.7 32.9 41.7 Thailand 18.6 67.4 -16.0 51.5 36.2 Hong Kong 16.6 67.4 0.3 67.7 24.5 PNG 16.0 67.4 -15.0 52.3 30.6 Malaysia 13.3 67.4 -9.7 57.8 23.1 Singapore 13.3 67.4 0.5 67.9 19.7 Korea 10.2 67.4 3.3 70.7 14.5 Source: Estimated by the author 36 Rising global food prices are contributing to high food inflation in many countries in recent years. There have been significant surges in domestic food price inflation in countries such as Mongolia (61%), Sri Lanka (55%), Maldives (45%), Pakistan (41%), Indonesia (35%) and China (34%) over the last three years - 2006-08.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "07bcc184-f022-4c33-b2b2-9850c46f5a0c": {"__data__": {"id_": "07bcc184-f022-4c33-b2b2-9850c46f5a0c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-