ges in domestic consumer food price indices are lower than the changes in international", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "aeb27a23-a1ff-4000-bd4c-2a25b234d8c3": {"__data__": {"id_": "aeb27a23-a1ff-4000-bd4c-2a25b234d8c3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "206ed2331075dfb027bef926fc46716e0d5988886773f72a52f424aa3685b2bd"}, "3": {"node_id": "1a483a35-c353-4a13-aa09-095f5fe71064", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "bd9dcaf0e1ef4699ce75b3c7979dfc7b2cdd0d2532270ccedef28598ba2b0aa5"}}, "hash": "ad1d3e852ac8a693303d8289232840260e383fbdff2e5b3e9a2ccb0617f67101", "text": "food prices during 2006-08. For most of countries, the pass-through coefficient for food is less than 50 %. A comparison of changes in international food price indices in US dollar terms and changes in domestic consumer food price indices shows that only about half of the increase in real US dollar prices has been passed through to domestic markets. Highest pass-through ratios are observed for Mongolia, Sri Lanka, China, Maldives and Indonesia. In these countries, the pass-through ratios range between 97% in Mongolia to 56% in Indonesia. These countries have been content to allow most of the changes in world prices to pass through to domestic markets. On the other hand, lowest pass-through ratios of food are observed for South Korea, Singapore, Malaysia, and India. In these countries, the pass-through ratios of food range from 15% in Korea to 30% in India. Data on food prices for 2008 are not yet available for several countries. However, if available information for 2006 and 2007 is taken into consideration, then food inflation in Myanmar, Viet Nam, Lao PDR, Cambodia and Afghanistan are also very high in recent years. The pass- through ratios are also high (more than 60%) in these countries. Available data also show that the rates of increase of consumer food prices are generally low for the Pacific Island countries. Consequently the pass-through ratios are low in almost all the Pacific Islands. This shows that consumers in the Pacific countries have not been affected much from the global food prices. China and India present contrasting cases. Both countries have shifted from net food importing countries into net food exporting countries in recent years, though their food exports as s share of total merchandise exports or imports or food production is negligible. Chinese currency has appreciated against the US dollar while Indian currency has depreciated. Consequently, world food price equivalents in domestic currency terms have increased at higher rate (72%) in India than China (50%) during 2006-08. Yet, domestic consumer food prices in India increased only by 22%, while retail food prices in China rose by 34% for the same period. It indicates that while India has been more restrained in allowing passing through of food price rises to the consumers, China has been content to allow of the changes in world market prices to pass through to domestic markets. 37 Bangladesh and Sri Lanka also present contrasting cases. The results indicate that Sri Lankan consumers have shouldered more of the increase in world food prices than Bangladesh\u2019s. Similarly, if one compares Mongolia and Korea - both are net food importers - the results show that Korean consumers have been more shielded from the price rise than Mongolian consumers. Table 12: Pass-Through Coefficients for food prices during 2006 -07 Country Cumulative Change in domestic food prices Cumulative Change in world food prices Cumulative Changes in Exchange Rate World prices adjusted for exchange rate changes Domestic price to world price (%) (Col-2/Col-5) Col: 1 2 3 4 5 6 Myanmar 56.0 25.7 -2.7 23.1 242.5 Lao PDR 17.5 25.7 -10.1 15.6 112.2 Viet Nam 19.9 25.7 2.0 27.7 71.6 Bhutan 14.1 25.7 -6.0 19.7 71.3 Cambodia 16.4 25.7 -0.9 24.9 66.0 Afghanistan 16.9 25.7 1.0 26.7 63.1 Solomon Is. 15.7 25.7 1.6 27.4 57.5 Fiji Islands 11.6 25.7 -4.6 21.1 55.0 Samoa 11.7 25.7 -3.3 22.4 52.2 Vanuatu 7.4 25.7 -6.1 19.6 37.6 Tonga 7.1 25.7 1.6 27.3 25.9 Tuvalu 3.7 25.7 -8.6 17.1 21.6 Cook Islands 2.6 25.7 -3.2 22.5 11.3 Kiribati -3.5 25.7 -8.6 17.1 -20.4 Source: Estimated by the author The exchange rate in both countries has depreciated against the US dollars during the past few years. Both countries are net food importers.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1a483a35-c353-4a13-aa09-095f5fe71064": {"__data__": {"id_": "1a483a35-c353-4a13-aa09-095f5fe71064", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publ