international prices \u2013 whether they are net importing or net exporting countries in the medium term. In many countries, food and fuel price inflation is higher than aggregate inflation and contributing to underlying inflationary pressures. The inflation impact of food price increases is of particular concern, especially for emerging and developing economies, because food expenditure accounts much larger share than those of oil-related spending in the consumer price index. Higher food prices have already led to substantial increases in overall inflation in many Asian countries (Chart 30). The rises in the price of food have contributed about 2-3 percentage points to headline inflation. In addition, in some countries domestic demand pressures have pushed up inflation. 40 Chart 30: Overall, Food, and Fuel Inflation in Asian Countries in Recent Years 0 10 20 30 40 Jan 07 Jan 08 Jun 08 Dec 06 Dec 07 Jul 08 Apr 07 Jan 08 Jun 08 Jul 07 Jan 08 Jul 08 2006 2007 Jun 08 Jul 07 Jan 08 Jul 08 Aug 06 Jul 07 Jul 08 Jun 07 Jan 08 Jun 08 Jan 07 Jan 08 Jul 08 Mar 07 Aug 07 Mar 08 Jan 07 Jan 08 Aug 08 BNG CHA IND IDO IRA MAS NEP PAK PHI SRL THA % ALL Food Fuel The increase in the prices of petroleum products also could have stoked inflation. At the regional level, though it did not happen in the immediate aftermath of crude oil price rise, i.e., till 2006, continuous sharp rises in oil price coupled with soaring food prices has been a contributing factor affecting the inflation rates (Chart 30). While the impact of rising international food prices on overall domestic inflation tended to be somewhat muted until mid 2007 due to the relatively small size of international price movements and the appreciation of many local currencies against the dollar, the large scale of international food price inflation since mid-2007 is likely having a bigger impact. Inflation in the region expected to rise sharply in 2008 compared to 2007. Inflation in East Asia is expected to increase from 3.9% in 2007 to 6.1% in 2008. In South Asia, it is likely to rise to 11.8 % from 5.5 % for the same period. Inflation in South East Asia also expected to rise by more than double \u2013 from 4.0% in 2007 to 9.4% in 2008. Inflation in Asia and the Pacific as a whole is forecasted to rise substantially from 4.8 % in 2007 to 8.2 % in 2008 \u2013 by about 70 % increase. Inflation is likely to be in double digits in 2008 in 14 out of 36 countries in our region. In fact six countries namely Afghanistan, Cambodia, Marshall Islands, Mongolia, Sri Lanka and Vietnam are likely to witness inflation rate of over 20% in 2008. Chart : Inflation Rates by Sub-Regions 0 2 4 6 8 10 12 14 2000 2001 2002 2003 2004 2005 2006 2007 2008- est 2009- est % EA-4 SWA-9 SA-8 SEA-9 Pacific-14 Asia-Pacific-36 41 Inflation has thus emerged as the biggest risk to the regional outlook, having risen to very high levels across Asia-Pacific countries, levels that have not been generally seen for last 10- 15 years. Many countries reported multi-year highs in inflation, driven mainly by soaring food and fuel prices. Overall inflation is already at or is rapidly heading to double-digit levels in most of Asia-Pacific countries. In many countries, overall inflation increased by 2 - 6 percentage points since January 2008. With food and oil accounting for a large share of consumer price indexes in Asia and the Pacific, and with a majority of countries being net food and oil importers, the consequent rise in domestic prices is not surprising. Inflation expectations have also risen markedly. There are growing concerns across countries that rising food and energy prices are triggering a more generalised inflation spiral through second-round effects. In fact, in recent months core inflation that excludes food and energy has begun to", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e720d9e4-910c-4967-8bc1-1c01fb346142": {"__data__": {"id_": "e720d9e4-910c-4967-8bc1-1c01fb346142", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "239f519404b65a7a49b05a506d0b1fd4177c4442d13946b67b714f7081e8cc40"}}, "hash": "239f519404b65a7a49b05a506d0b1fd4177c4442d13946b67b714f7081e8cc40", "text": "rise in many of Asia-Pacific countries. The rise may also hint that inflation expectations have begun to drift. Higher inflation has also led to wage increases in some economies. Although the surge in global oil and food prices remains the main driver of the inflationary surge, rapid liquidity growth in the region over the past few years has been an important underlying factor. This indicates that a much more broad-based second-round effect may be underway. However, in recent months, inflation decelerated in many countries. While high inflation is now a region wide phenomenon, country responses have differed widely depending on perceptions of the nature of the shock, how long it will last and the stage of the inflation cycle in terms of the onset of the second-order impact. In some countries like China, the policy response to inflation has been proscribed by relatively overarching concerns for economic growth. Consequently China reduced interest rates in the recent months while many countries increased interest rate to fight inflation. Prices of food has fallen a bit in the last few weeks. But the outlook even for the next couple of years is uncertain and depends on policies put in place now to encourage increased production. Nevertheless, the pressure on food prices from the underlying structural influences will likely remain and keep prices at higher levels than in the past. Oil prices are likely to remain high and volatile, as oil production is expected to remain broadly stagnant. Though the rising bio fuels production should continue to exert pressure on food prices, food prices should ease more substantially, as farmers are expected to respond strongly for higher food prices. It is clear that global commodity price increases translate to higher prices globally, particularly since food carries a large weight in the CPI of many of the region\u2019s economies. Rising fuel and food prices have soaked headline inflation both in developed and developing countries. In developed countries, headline inflation has become uncomfortably high at a time when economic activity is slowing down. While measures of core inflation so far have remained quite well anchored, there are some signs that expectations are edging higher. The inflation concerns are even more serious in Asia-Pacific countries. Inflation pressures have risen sharply in recent years, as the effects of the rising prices of oil and other commodities have come on top of pressures from domestic overheating and rapid credit growth. Risks are that the impact higher fuel and food prices could feed into inflation expectations, which may lead to second-round effects on inflation. 42 4.6 Impact of world food and fuel price changes on countries GDP growth One of the greatest worries about a steep rise in the commodity prices is that they may stifle economic growth by raising cost of production directly and contributing to soaring headline inflation thereby indirectly affecting aggregate demand and investment climate adversely. The policy responses of countries to contain inflation through tight monetary policy could also stifle economic growth. As Chart 32 indicates, commodity price rise does not appear to have affected growth significantly either at the regional level or within the Asian developing countries. The GDP impact of the recent increase in oil prices seems to be less severe than in the past because the shock has been gradual spreading into number of years which allowed countries to adjust. Currency appreciation vis-\u00e0-vis the U.S. dollar has also mitigated the impact of higher oil prices in local currency terms for a number of other countries. Most of the increase in oil prices due to increased demand rather than supply reduction (as in the 1970s). Oil intensity has fallen significantly in the past two decades in most countries. Economic growth in Asia and the Pacific during the first half of 2008 was decelerated compared to 2007 levels. Supported by stronger investment and resilient exports, GDP growth was stronger-than-expected in the first quarter of 2008. However, economic growth in the second quarter of 2008 decelerated at much higher level as slower growth in the US and other western economies began to impact the region. High growth economies such as China, India and Vietnam witnessed stronger moderation. In China, GDP growth has decelerated from 11.9% in 2007 to 10.4% in the first half of 2008. Similarly in Vietnam GDP growth has slowed down from 8.5% in 2007 to 6.5 % during the first half of 2008. In India, growth decelerated from 9.2 % in the first quarter of last fiscal year (April-June 2007) to 7.9% in the corresponding period of 2008. As per ADB forecasts, GDP growth is likely to decelerate from 9.6 %", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "53dbaa04-9606-4258-93a4-112a3ec6be29": {"__data__": {"id_": "53dbaa04-9606-4258-93a4-112a3ec6be29", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c5a6fe6903afbf3b9a65de1aea7561338dab6bf38a54496b4da6479e07f0e0b3"}, "3": {"node_id": "9a931511-9210-4cda-9b95-133764880b7d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d7d4d3e85c5356df6987bfc5c27e7bf5be2a613ef86ab6c31f2abad29d8019fb"}}, "hash": "d98c696432820c189176a3d0339eef27e40ecf511ec5f2686e20dcfed0328b81", "text": "in 2007 to 7.7% in 2008 in East Asia. For the same period, it will be from 8.6% to 7.1 % in South Asia and 6.5 % to 5.4 % in South East Asia. The growth in the Pacific, however, is forecasted to double in 2008 (4.8%) from lower level of 2007 (2.4%). This is Table 14: GDP projections are being revised down by governments Country Projected 2008 Revision for 2008 2009 Bangladesh 7.0 6.2 6.7 China 9.4 9.8 9.2 India 8.0 7.7 7.7 Indonesia 6.8 6.2 Malaysia 6.0 \u2013 6.5 5.0 Pakistan 7.2 5.8 5.0 Philippines 4.8 4.0 