odity price movements extends well beyond inflation and growth. On the external side, the recent oil price surge is expected to lead to balance of payments difficulties in some fuel- and food-importing low-income countries that have not benefited from offsets from other commodity exports. At the macroeconomic level the most pressing issue of rising global food and oil prices for low- income countries is the impact on the current account. Two factors determine the sign and magnitude of the change in the current account: (i) the size of net exports or imports, and (ii) the exchange rate vis-\u00e0-vis the US dollar. Soaring food and fuel prices are likely to increase countries\u2019 import bills which might lead to substantial widening of the current account deficit. This in turn could impact other macroeconomic variables such as the exchange rate, forex reserve and indebtedness. In recent months, the growth of both exports and non-food and oil imports has moderated in many countries. Food and fuel imports, however, have expanded substantially on account of higher global food and crude oil prices. For many developing countries, the steady rise in world prices of food and fuel has pushed up the food and fuel import bill. The terms of trade losses have also impacted the external positions of some emerging economies that are net commodity importers.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9a931511-9210-4cda-9b95-133764880b7d": {"__data__": {"id_": "9a931511-9210-4cda-9b95-133764880b7d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_me