 null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b0a65f0251041b975a8465e08546a1244c81a487f5f1d61afca0408002dc1898"}}, "hash": "b0a65f0251041b975a8465e08546a1244c81a487f5f1d61afca0408002dc1898", "text": "2007. This is an increase of 26 %. The combination of rapidly rising prices and higher freight costs is behind the higher global bills for imported foodstuffs. Among economic groups, the most economically vulnerable countries are set to bear the highest burden in the cost of importing food, with total expenditures by LDCs and Low-Income Food-Deficit Countries (LIFDCs) is likely to climb by 37-40 % in 2008, after rising 30 and 37 %, respectively, in 2007. In our region, food imports bill is forecasted to rise in 2008 compared to 2007 level by about 60 % in Pakistan, about 40 % each in Sri Lanka, Philippines and Bangladesh, and 35 % in Indonesia. The sharp increases in food and fuel prices have led to higher import bills and strained the balance of payments position of many countries. Asia and the Pacific region as a net importer of fuel and food is likely to witness an increased import bill - by over 2 -3 % of GDP in 2008 and 2008 compared to previous years. Depending upon the import dependence for domestic consumption, the import bill as % of GDP could increase 1-2 % in 2008 compared to previous years. This would imply a widening of the current account deficit as a share of GDP by more than 1-2 percentage points. In this regard, the vulnerable countries from a macroeconomic perspective are those countries that imports significant portion of their domestic food and fuels consumption and already have high current account deficits. In Asia and the Pacific, one third of countries that include Cambodia, Lao PDR, Maldives, the Pacific Islands (except PNG), Pakistan, Sri Lanka and Vietnam are already have large trade deficits (>4 % of GDP). With significant increase in the growth of their food and fuel import bill as a result of higher food and fuel prices, some of these countries could experience severe balance of payments problems. The combined price shocks are expected to deteriorate in the region\u2019s trade balance in 2008 and 2009. Chart 33b: Share of Food imports in Total Imports (%) 0 5 10 15 20 25 Bangladesh Indonesia Malaysia Nepal Pakistan Philippines Sri Lanka % 2004 2005 2006 2007 2008 Chart 33: Cereal import bill in LIFDCs by region 0 10000 20000 30000 40000 2002/03 2003/04 2004/05 2005/06 2006/07 est 2007/08 fst USD million LIFDC Africa Asia LAC Oceania Europe 45 Fortunately, reserve positions of the Asia-Pacific governments have generally remained strong and, thanks to continued capital inflows, the overall balance of payments position has not experienced stress, and depreciation pressures have not emerged. Available data indicates that in the first six months of 2008, import bills of food and fuels has increased significantly and consequently growth in imports has accelerated sharply. Consequently trade deficits widened in many of South Asian countries, while trade surplus narrowed down in some East Asian countries. However, as exports remained resilient in many Asia and the Pacific countries despite a slowing US economy and capitals are still flowing into the region, current account position has not moved into dangerous levels. Higher food and fuel prices have the potential of generating serious balance of payments problems. But, until recently, the effects remained relatively limited. In particular, the large increase in world oil prices since 2003 has had a relatively small macroeconomic impact on developing countries. This is because increase in world oil prices was more gradual than during earlier episodes, giving countries time to adjust. A rise in oil prices is expected to have a larger balance of payments effect than a similar food price increase. Because oil imports are 2-3 times larger than food imports for developing countries. The oil price increase would severely weaken the external position of many poor countries, while the food price increase would have a severe negative effect only for small number of countries. In US dollar terms, many Asian countries experienced significant increases in the food and fuel import bill. However, in recent years many Asian countries have had an appreciation of domestic currencies vis-\u00e0-vis the dollar. If the appreciation continues in 2008 and 2009, the increase in the value of the import requirement, measured in local currencies, will be somewhat lower. Furthermore, for many countries the net imports of grains and fuels, constitute less than 50% of total imports. Hence, the impact on the current accounts is expected to be manageable for most countries. 4.8 Impact of world food and fuel price changes on government revenue, expenditure, fiscal balance and monetary indicators With regards to government budgets, all of the domestic measures to cushion the burden of rising prices", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "421e1b16-b62f-480f-848f-0cb040695591": {"__data__": {"id_": "421e1b16-b62f-480f-848f-0cb040695591", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "