e their overall fiscal performance. The problem would be more severe in countries with large fiscal deficits like Sri Lanka, Pakistan, India, and Bangladesh. Thus, governments have yet another challenge to confront in allocating scarce resources. Available data show that many countries increased fuel and food subsidies. Many countries also reduced fuel and food taxes. A recent IMF study (IMF, 2008) show that food subsidies are relatively high in the Maldives and Timor Leste (more than 1% of GDP), it is modestly high in Indonesia, India, China, Pakistan and Afghanistan ( more than 0.5 % of GDP), Bangladesh and Malaysia (0.2 to 0.5% of GDP). Similarly, Fuel subsidies as % of GDP are relatively high (more than 2 %) in Indonesia, Malaysia, Cambodia, Pakistan, Bangladesh and Nepal. In India it is about 1.5 %. In other Asian countries, either subsidies are low or data are not available (IMF, 2008). Targeted transfers (safety nets and agricultural subsidies) as % of GDP are relatively high in the Philippines (over 4 %), Bangladesh, Singapore and India (2 %), modest in Sri Lanka and China (1%), and low in Pakistan and Indonesia (0.5%). Total fiscal cost of policy responses of food and fuel prices is high (2 \u2013 3% of GDP) in Indonesia, Maldives, Bangladesh and Timor Leste. It is modest level in Malaysia, India and Cambodia (more than 1%); It is low in Solomon Islands, Sri Lanka, south Korea and Philippines (about 0.5 to 0.1%), and Singapore, Laos and Nepal (about 0.3 to 0.5%). Available data shows that fiscal developments in 2008 indicate stress on the financial position of the many countries. Available data show that the fiscal deficit indicators have generally worsened in 2008 from their levels a year ago. Government tax and non-tax revenues have remained buoyant. Aggregate on social and other services has risen significantly due to rise in food and fuel subsidies. Higher salaries that is likely to occur following rise in inflation rate also a source of concern from the point of view Chart 35: Government Revenues (% of GDP) by sub-regions 15 20 25 30 2000 2001 2002 2003 2004 2005 2006 2007 % 30 40 50 60 Pacific EA-4 SWA-9 SA-8 SEA-9 Asia-Pacific-36 Pacific-14 Chart 36:Government Expenditure(% of GDP) by Sub-Regions 15 20 25 30 35 40 45 2000 2001 2002 2003 2004 2005 2006 2007 % EA-4 SWA-9 SA-8 SEA-9 Pacific-14 Asia-Pacific-36 47 of fiscal management. As fiscal situations becoming tight, any new social safety net measures will require effective targeting of assistance; otherwise, these may add to further fiscal pressure. There are some signs of moderation in key monetary indicators in response to monetary measures which have withdrawn liquidity from the system and tightened interest rates. The growth rates of money supply and deposit growth have started to dip in recent months. Financial markets have generally experienced some tightening of liquidity conditions and hardening of interest rates, particularly in recent months as monetary measures took effect. Fiscal policy will need to be tightened to reinforce the monetary response, especially in rapid growing countries where demand pressures are already contributing to inflation. 4.9 Equity, Currency and financial markets World market prices have increased substantially in real US dollar terms in recent years for rice (56%), wheat (91%), and maize (40%). During that time, however, the US dollar has depreciated substantially against many currencies. Chart - shows the percentage appreciation of the real exchange rate for the Asian countries in the recent years.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "66a83d47-5787-4df5-a9ee-9dace2392f3f": {"__data__": {"id_": "66a83d47-5787-4df5-a9ee-9dace2392f3f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-imp