and Oil prices at the household level The aim of this section is to contribute to improving understanding of the impact of soaring global food prices on the households, particularly poor households across the developing Asia. Consumers make their food purchase decisions based on a budget that also must cover expenses for clothing, housing, and other goods and services. The overall budget available for food depends on the amount of total household budget spent on other goods and services. Therefore, in-depth study on the impact of soaring food and fuel prices requires an understanding of the complete consumption patterns of households. Consumption patterns of 114 countries were examined by USDA study (Seale, Regmi, Bernstein, 2003) by dividing them into low-, middle-, and high income countries. The simple average budget shares for the nine aggregate consumption categories for each of the three country groups are presented in Table 15. As expected, the budget shares for food tend to decrease as income rises. Households in low-income countries spent about 53 % of their consumption budget on food, while households in high-income countries spent only about 17 of their consumption budget on food. Although the households\u2019 consumption shares for clothing and footwear are not hugely different between low-and high-come countries as in the case of food, the simple average budget shares are also higher for low income countries compared with the other two groups. The budget shares for fuel and lighting is higher for high income countries compared with the middle-income and low-income countries implying that the budget shares for fuel and power; transport and communication generally increase as income levels increase.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "012a8966-e028-46a4-96cb-00614d52e4cc": {"__data__": {"id_": "012a8966-e028-46a