, one would expect poor will benefits from food prices rise, as they are producers of food. In fact, a common criticism of OECD farm policies is that these policies lower international food prices and contribute to world poverty by undermining the profitability of smallholder agriculture in developing countries. If this claim is correct, it seems that the recent price rise would alleviate poverty. When farm policies lower international prices they are denounced as increasing world poverty; and when food prices rise on international markets they are also blamed as contributing to a rise in world poverty. Clearly, there is a need to identify the 50 gainers and the losers in the current situation of rising international food prices. The division is likely to be quite different across a range of countries. A detailed mapping of who is gaining and who is loosing is important for designing any social safety nets. Impacts from the price changes depend on access to land, educational levels, gender, ethnicity, and access to rural non- farm employment opportunities. Because the problem is not yet reflected in household poverty and human development statistics, its impact is hard to analyse or quantify. The effect on the poor will depend on whether they are net buyers of food or net sellers. Before analysing the households\u2019 impact of soaring food and fuel prices, it will be useful to examine who is the poor and who is the non-poor, where they live and the recent poverty trends in Asia and the Pacific. Recently the World Bank has released a new set of poverty estimates based on improved methodology (PPP in 2005 prices compared to 1993 prices). A simple comparison of old and new poverty estimates shows that the old estimates based on 1993 PPPs led to a severe underestimation of the true level of global poverty. In other words, old 1993 PPPs translated poverty line was underestimated the number of poor in the world by 50 % compared to the new 2005 IPC-translated poverty line. The use of the latest poverty estimates may be appropriate for our analysis. As per the World Bank estimates 879 million people in 2005 lived on $1 a day -the old benchmark of absolute poverty. As per the new benchmark of absolute poverty, about 1.4 billion people lived on $1.15 a day. Between 2.6 and 3.1 billion lived on $2.0 to $2.5 a day. Available information also reveals that Asia and the Pacific region has made significant progress in poverty reduction over the last two decades. Chart 41: Poverty Incidence by regions based on $1.00 and $1.25 a day definition in 2005 0 10 20 30 40 50 60 SA EAP China India EECA LAC MENA SSA % $1.00 per day $1.25 per day Chart 40: Poverty Incidence in Asia and the Pacific - Comparison of old and new estimates 0 20 40 60 80 1981 1984 1987 1990 1993 1996 1999 2002 2005 EAP - $1 a day EAP - $1.25 a day SA - $1 a day SA - $1.25 a day 51 Available data shows that about 86 % of the world\u2019s poor lived in Asia and the Pacific in the early 1980s. Now this share has declined to 67 %. The number of poor (based on 1.15$ a day) in the region has declined from 1636 million in 1981 to 1466 million in 1990 to 932 million in 2005. This shows that, despite continued growth of population, Asia and the Pacific region lifted about 170 million people out of poverty (1$ a day) in the 1980s and 533 million people out of the poverty during 1990-2005. This reflects that both the incidence of poverty and absolute number of poor declined", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4c5435f1-29ac-4ea9-a01d-b1c71f884505": {"__data__": {"id_": "4c5435f1-29ac-4ea9-a01d-b1c71f884505", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3e1361d21ce0d728aed368e587bfec3f649eca21c304a192bfb53b7762016fd4"}}, "hash": "3e1361d21ce0d728aed368e587bfec3f649eca21c304a192bfb53b7762016fd4", "text": "at a faster rate in Asia and the Pacific compared to other regions in the world. The progress in poverty reduction has varied widely among sub-regions in Asia and the Pacific. The poverty incidence dropped dramatically in East Asia and the Pacific from 78.8 % in 1981 to 56.0 % in 1990 to 17.9 % in 2005. It is the region that achieved the highest and unprecedented rate of decline in the incidence of poverty during the last two and half decades. The absolute number of poor in East Asia has also declined significantly \u2013 from 1088 million in 1981 to 893 million in 1990 to 337 million in 2005. This shows that East Asia has lifted more than 750 million people out of extreme poverty within a generation. Despite this achievement, East Asia and the Pacific, still accounts for 24 % of the world poor. South Asia also achieved substantial reduction in the incidence of poverty over the last two and half decades \u2013 from 59.4 % in 1981 to 51.1 % in 1990 to 40.3 % in 2005. However, the absolute number of poor in South Asia has increased marginally \u2013 from 548 million in 1981 to 572 million in 1990 to 596 million in 2005. This indicates that Chart 42: Share of Asia Pacific in the World Poor, based on $1.25 a day definition 0 20 40 60 80 100 1981 1984 1987 1990 1993 