s in the range of 3 - 5 percentage points in global poverty rates. This could mean \u201cseven lost years\u201d in the fight against worldwide poverty. As per recent growth elasticity of poverty, the poverty rate in East Asia and the Pacific is expected to decline from 17.9% in 2005 to 11.7 % in 2009 if growth is sustained at similar rate of last few years. However, available data shows that growth will decelerate about 1 -2 percentage points in 2008 and 2008. This deceleration is likely to slow down progress in poverty reduction. A simple back of envelope calculation shows that poverty incidence will at least one percentage point be higher than anticipated earlier by 2009. Similarly, the poverty rate in Chart 44b: Poverty Incidence in South Asia 35 36 37 38 39 40 41 2005 2006 2007 2008 2009 BAU Low growth Chart 44a: Poverty Incidence in East Asia and the Pacific 10.0 12.0 14.0 16.0 18.0 20.0 2005 2006 2007 2008 2009 BAU Low growth 53 South Asia is expected to decline from 40.3% in", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c30083cf-02d5-4f65-b077-a4d95246155e": {"__data__": {"id_": "c30083cf-02d5-4f65-b077-a4d95246155e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "40a7482c0eb4471173e3b496422b4b8ad215cadb245238af2590a771c8006537"}}, "hash": "40a7482c0eb4471173e3b496422b4b8ad215cadb245238af2590a771c8006537", "text": "2005 to 37.2 % in 2009 if high growth is sustained. Now with decelerated economic growth, poverty incidence in South Asia will at least one percentage point be higher than expected earlier in 2009. This suggests that economic slow down due to soaring of global commodity prices and financial crisis could push at least 57 million people into poverty in Asia and the Pacific during 2006-09. Increased malnutrition Malnutrition is not new consequence of high food prices in the free market. With rising food prices comes increased evidence of malnutrition. Across Asian households are reducing their daily food intakes. In some countries, households are reducing their non-staple foods (meat, oil etc); in some other countries, households are devoting a greater proportion of resources to food and cutting back on non-food consumption; and in some countries, households cope by cutting down the quantity and quality of food, or number of meals. The impact is already being seen in increased levels of malnutrition and under-nutrition in 2007/08. According to the World Bank, the number of malnourished people globally will grow by 44 million due to food price crisis. Provisional FAO estimates show that the number of undernourished people in 2007 increased by 75 million, over and above FAO\u2019s estimate of 848 million undernourished in 2003-05. FAO says that much of this increase in malnutrition is due to high food prices. At regional level, the largest increases in the number of undernourished people as a result of rising food prices have taken place in Asia. FAO estimates that rising prices have plunged an additional 41 million people in Asia and 24 million in sub-Saharan Africa below the hunger threshold. Chart 44c: Changes in the Number of Poor in Asia and the Pacific due to GDP Deceleration 800 820 840 860 880 900 920 940 2005 2006 2007 2008 2009 Million BAU Price shock 54 Box: Growth \u2013 Poverty relationships based on recently released poverty indicators One of the ways to capture the relationship between economic growth and poverty is to compute the growth elasticity of poverty. This indicates the percentage change in the incidence of poverty associated with a one percent increase in per capita income. Estimates of this elasticity for the sample countries in different decades are given in Chart -- which demonstrates a wide variation in the elasticity estimates two conclusions can be drawn from Chart. First, the elasticity is both positive and negative. Positive elasticities are generally observed in cases where the growth of per capita income is low and poverty has increased (e.g., Philippines). Second, the elasticity tends to be more negative in the case of countries, which experience faster growth. This is case in most of Asian countries. Growth Elasticity of Poverty in Recent Period -1.60 -1.40 -1.20 -1.00 -0.80 -0.60 -0.40 -0.20 0.00 0.20 Bangladesh Cambodia China India Indonesia Lao PDR Malaysia Mongolia Nepal Pakistan Philippines Sri Lanka Vietnam Asia Impact on the poor and rich households By dividing households as net sellers and net buyers Rising food prices can either reduce or increase poverty, depending on how poor households earn their income and how they spend it. For example, households that produce and sell food crops will benefit from an increase in prices, unless they buy more food than they sell. In addition to direct selling and buying of food, the poverty impact will also depend on how price changes are transmitted through labour markets. For example, if rising prices lead farmers to expand production and hire more farm labour, landless farm workers may benefit. Because about three-fourths of the world\u2019s poor live in rural areas where agriculture is the main economic activity, one might assume that rising food prices would tend to reduce poverty levels. However, because most of the poor households were net food buyers rather than net food sellers, lower food prices would tend to reduce poverty (Sandra Polaski, 2008). 55 There were relatively few studies that used actual data on sources of household incomes as well as household food expenditures to explore this question. A recent World Bank paper (Aksoy and Isik-Dikmelik, 2008) using detailed household data has examined this issue in detail. The paper shows that on average only 6 % of urban households, 32 % of rural households and 23 % of all households were net food sellers (Table 16). In Cambodia, these figures are 15, 44 and 40 respectively. In Bangladesh, the corresponding figures are 4, 23, and 19. In Vietnam, these figures are 7, 48, and 38 respectively. Though Bangladesh is a rural economy, it has a low share of households that are net food sellers.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3f181486-2528-4c15-8e4e-59ea0818c019": {"__data__": {"id_": "3f181486-2528-4c15-8e4e-59ea0818c019", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ce9bd670e3c8b2efb4808fc6cf319aea8f60314388a3a0dc70d7d08b982b5fb6"}, "3": {"node_id": "6b328525-e117-45b2-9b1e-edac415a186b", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8e1ba09808b962a2fc6edbe25f4e39f3657d7586a0d274913b23bba667aa290f"}}, "hash": "227d299bed82031d0d501dc7d30faeb5d6539fc7ddb7f0978c95e2813da0d0ff", "text": "The lowest shares of net buyers are observed in Cambodia and Vietnam. Given the much smaller share of households who are net sellers, a related question is whether net seller households are predominant among the rich or poor households. The general presumption has been that net food sellers are relatively well to do households with larger farms, while the net buyers are assumed to be poor labourers or small farmers. At the national level, on average, about 27 % of poor households versus about 13 % of rich households are net food sellers (Aksoy and Isik-Dikmelik, 2008). Poor households that are net sellers of food benefit from higher prices. But these households comprises only one fourth of the rural households and one sixth of the rich households. Households that are net buyers lose. As three fourths of poor households are net food buyers, rising food prices would affect them adversely. Table 16: Share of Rich and Poor Net Sellers of Households ( %) National Rural Urban Poor Rich All Poor Rich All Poor Rich All Ethiopia, 2000 21.8 23.3 23.1 24.3 31.4 27.3 6.0 7.2 6.3 Zambia, 1998 23.9 13.0 19.1 28.1 29.1 29.6 2.7 2.7 2.8 Cambodia, 1999 43.7 21.7 39.6 45.4 30.7 43.8 23.1 8.5 15.1 Bangladesh, 2000 13.5 19.9 19.0 14.7 33.6 22.9 0.3 3.5 3.7 Vietnam, 1998 43.3 12.4 38.1 45.4 36.9 48.2 12.2 2.2 6.6 Madagascar, 2001 41.0 14.0 31.7 42.7 22.7 37.6 28.2 3.6 13.2 Nicara