her profitability. Although farmers may take advantage of the new opportunities that such products offer for increasing income, they face serious obstacles to entering markets.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f735d577-0620-4282-bf00-b48c6ccd88a6": {"__data__": {"id_": "f735d577-0620-4282-bf00-b48c6ccd88a6", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d5499364d6045d6abe5eab4fe3117ca41289561890c684f192a6cf0b170ef40a"}, "2": {"node_id": "b5d60968-ca0f-46dd-9618-96e040d1320a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6eed1e9f56dd4534550e650f1f5233c37c4ad1efec3b4bfd0907e2dd1a330df8"}}, "hash": "66a28fe5cb6a75d7a438e041d5e34dac2ac902673468dc4b5fb98edcf681440c", "text": "On the other hand, some other view that given the fact that globally 862 million people were undernourished in the period from 2002 to 2004, of which 830 million were in developing countries, this rise in food prices could aggravate the malnutrition/ hunger problem. The impact of rising of crude oil price of households depends on the extent of usage of kerosene, gas and electricity for their cooking, lighting and transportation. Available data shows that households spent about 3-8 % of their budget on fuels and lighting items and 5-8 of their budget on transportation (Table 20). Table 21 presents the distribution of households by their primary cooking and lighting fuel in India. Fuel consumption patterns also display a clear rural-urban divide. Table suggests that only 8% of rural households and 66% of urban households in India use some form of oil products (kerosene or LPG) as their primary fuel for cooking. On other hand, an overwhelming 86% of rural households and 25 % urban households use some form of biomass (firewood or dung cake) as their primary fuel for cooking. This suggests three things. First, rising of crude oil would not affect much consumption expenditure of rural households on cooking fuel. Second, subsidies on LPG are inherently biased towards the urban Table 20: Relative Importance of food and fuels in the consumption budget (Weights used for CPI Calculation) Food Fuel Transport Bangladesh 58.00 4.00 Bhutan", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1ceb4b2a-2f5f-4737-9da2-3f42ea525fa9": {"__data__": {"id_": "1ceb4b2a-2f5f-4737-9da2-3f42ea525fa9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and