ld in Asia 12. While the macroeconomic impact of HIV is negligible in Asia and the Pacific, it can exert devastating effects on households. The Commission on AIDS in Asia estimates 13 that every AIDS death could result in an income loss of $5,000 on average. The Commission also projects that an additional 6 million households in Asia will have been pushed below the poverty line by 2015 given the cu rrent level of HIV the problem and response. This could jeopardise the achievement of the MDGs. Recent food and fuel price inflation in Asia warrants a careful analysis of its impact on households affected by HIV. Given the impoverishing effects of HIV s uch as lost income and higher medical expenditures among HIV - affected households, 14,15,16,17 the recent food and fuel price inflation could cause a greater number of vulnerable HIV-affected households to fall below the poverty line. Although the link between f ood security risks and HIV infection has been well established in Africa 18, only recently some studies have been conducted in Asia. Recently UNDP RCC 19 attempted to examine the potential economic impact of HIV on HIV -affected households with particular focus on food security by using some relevant studies/surveys. Three of the studies, from China (A total of 2,043 households were surveyed) 20, India (8,292 households) 21 and Thailand (600 households)22, include matched samples from HIV -affected and non-HIV- affected households. The Cambodian study (684 households) 23 examined two types of HIV-affected households (including people living with HIV [PLHIV] and with orphans (due to AIDS) and vulnerable children [OVC]) and compares households who were beneficiaries of an integrated food support and home -based care program with those of similar income and composition who were not. Finally, the Vietnam study 24 investigated expenditure patterns of 125 households that included a PLHIV in four cities. The analysis indicates that rises in food prices will likely impact the quality as well as the quantity of diets for 12 Commission of on AIDS in Asia (2008): Redefining AIDS in Asia: Crafting an effective res ponse. Oxford University Press. 13 Ibid. 14 Pitayanon P. et al. (2000). The Economic Impact of HIV/AIDS Mortality on Households in Thailand. In The Economics of HIV and AIDS: the case of South and South East Asia. Edited by D. Bloom & P. Godwin. Delhi: Oxford University Press. 15 Kongsin S. et al. (2000). The Economic impact of HIV/AIDS on households in rural Thailand: The analysis of household coping strategies. Paper presented at the XIII International AIDS Conference, Durban. South Africa. 16 ADB/UNAIDS (2004). Asia -Pacific\u2019s Opportunity: Investing to Avert An HIV/AIDS Crisis. 17 ADB (2006). Poverty implications of HIV/AIDS in the Pacific. 18 Gillespie S and Kadiyala S (2005). HIV/AIDS and Food and Nutrition Security: Evidence to Action. Food Policy Review 7: International Food Policy Research Institute. 19 Kerry, R. (2008). Unpublished study. UNDP RCC. 20 Yuan J. et al (2008) Unpublished study . 21 UNDP (2006) Socio -Economic Impact of HIV and AIDS in India. 22 Kongsin, S. (2002).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "82d5567f-f09f-43a3-a70a-7c38910197d2": {"__data__": {"id_": "82d5567f-f09f-43a3-a70a-7c38910197d2", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-