saved on food and medical expenses on children\u2019s education and \u201cother\u201d expenses. The HIV -affected households show similar differences in expenditure patterns between the con trol and intervention samples, although the difference in food expenditures is less sharp. Intervention households spent less on grains, as rice was provided to the households as part of the food support program. They also spent more money on protein - rich foods, indicating that the food support program had enhanced both the quality and quantity of food for these households. Additionally, the program enabled HIV -affected households to invest in children\u2019s education. The Vietnam study focused on HIV -affected households only. When asked the major sources of payment for health expenses, only the poorest households reported that they had sold assets to pay for healthcare costs. The use of savings increases with household income while the use of borrowing decrease s. The study found that HIV - affected households reduced consumption expenditures that they would otherwise make by between 37% (for the poorest households) and 42% (for the wealthiest households). With regard to poverty, they found that all households below the wealthiest quintile (i.e. 80% of households) would fall below the poverty line as a result of the income and expenditure effects of HIV/AIDS. Food insecurity and subsequent malnutrition bring detrimental health outcomes to people living with HIV. A study in Singapore unveiled a strong significant association between survival rates and malnutrition at the start of HIV treatment. 25 Malnutrition is also associated with a greater risk of opportunistic infections and mother -to- child HIV transmission, and c hildren living with HIV are more susceptible to severe malnutrition. 26 On the other hand, adequate food intake could help improve adherence to HIV drug intake by mitigating adverse drug side effects, which could intensify on an empty stomach. 27 Potentially far-reaching negative impacts of food insecurity on poverty reduction, HIV prevention, treatment and care & support in light of the recent food and fuel price increases and limited evidence in Asia and the Pacific require urgent attention, further examinati ons, and timely action. Discussion based on spot surveys -the impact of fuel prices The discussions presented in the following pages are based on the households survey results for the period 2004-05 in China, India, Indonesia, Lao PDR conducted by the UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok for its report on \u201cOvercoming Vulnerability to Rising Oil Prices: Options for Asia and the Pacific\u201d. While the sample size was very small (only 500 households), the purpose of the sample survey was to conduct a spot check of vulnerable sections of the population and confirm the point that macro level analysis can and often does miss out the specific pockets of impacts when aggregated across large sample sets. A similar survey for Mongolia in 2008 indicated the same trends of micro analysis averaging over pockets of increased impoverishment while tracking direct and indirect impacts of oil price rise on weaker sections of the population. Before oil prices began their upward spiral in 2003, the prices of oil products that matter to the poor were largely regulated through subsidies by governments in most developing countries of the region. However, as the price of crude oil in 25 Paton NI et al. (2006). The impact of malnutriti on on survival and the CD4 count response in HIV -infected patients starting antiretroviral therapy. HIV Med. 2006 Jul;", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "51573c89-24e2-4562-b5d4-0a5ff3f9d3d3": {"__data__": {"id_": "51573c89-24e2-4562-b5d4-0a5ff3f9d3d3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "04423fecbfce825fbb232e2f45c876ced4dca72550404f67de4ec6cf06381045"}}, "hash": "04423fecbfce825fbb232e2f45c876ced4dca72550404f67de4ec6cf06381045", "text": "7 (5): 323 -30. 26 USAID (2004). Nutrition and HIV/AIDS: evidence, gaps and priority actions. April 2004. 27 The Lancet (2007). Food crisis in Cambodia. Vol 369, March 31, 2007: 1056. 63 world markets continued to surge, the mostly oil-importing countries of the region have struggled to sustain this policy. Within the group of countries studied and the chosen survey sample set, the direct impact of oil price rise on the poor has been very steep. Between 2002 and 2005, the average poor household paid: \u2022 171% more for cooking fuels; \u2022 120% more for transportation; \u2022 67% more for electricity; \u2022 55% more for lighting fuels; \u2022 33% more for petroleum-based fertilizers and other agricultural inputs; and \u2022 74% more for energy as a whole. China: Since 1998, China has linked petroleum prices to average crude oil prices in the international market. It also adjusts retail product prices, generally when there is a difference of more than 8% between domestic prices and the weighted average of prices in New York, Singapore and Rotterdam. Oil product prices in the country have been rising steadily according to this formula since 2002. In March 2006, the government imposed a special oil income levy on revenues earned by state-owned oil enterprises from the sale of locally produced crude oil. As a result, ex-refinery retail prices of gasoline and diesel increased further, by 10 to 15%. To counter the increases, the government provides targeted subsidies for certain groups: fishers, farmers, state-owned forestry enterprises and urban public transportation firms. Early in 2006, for a limited period, some provinces also offered cash compensation to poor residents to offset rising LPG prices. \u2022 Against the national average increase of 100% in the price of coal and 56.5% in the price of LPG, rural households reported an increase of about 215% in their expenditure on cooking fuels. The increase was steeper among urban households, at around 290%. \u2022 Diesel and petrol prices increased across the country by 174% and 129% respectively. Transport expenditure among households in the communities surveyed rose faster, by about 218% in the two villages and by 305% in the two urban areas surveyed. \u2022 Public transport tariffs paid by households were, however, kept low resulting in an increase of between 25 to 35% as a result of government subsidies to the transport companies. India: Until 2003, India had an administered pricing mechanism for petroleum products. This has now been dismantled. However, while the price of indigenously produced crude oil is linked to international crude prices, the oil marketing companies are not free to set the prices of petroleum products and have to absorb losses arising from government control. In spite of the subsidies, India has South Asia\u2019s highest retail prices for both petrol and diesel. This is due to high levels of taxes and duties. To protect the most vulnerable consumers, the government subsidizes the prices for household consumption of LPG and kerosene, on which it has removed customs and excise duties since 2004. As part of the 2006 primary sample survey, the following was noted: \u2022 Households in the communities surveyed reported an increase of about 20% in kerosene prices, half the increase in the national average. This reflects the government\u2019s measure to remove customs and excise duties on domestic cooking fuels. \u2022 Household expenditure on transport rose at a rate of 63% in rural communities surveyed and 60% in urban communities. This was somewhat lower than the average increases of 64 88.5% in the price of diesel and 61% in the price of petrol, mainly because of reduced consumption of these fuels. \u2022 Overall energy expenditures in rural households rose faster than in urban households. However, urban households were worst affected by the price rise in cooking fuels since most often the rural households rely on traditional fuels. Indonesia: Since the Asian financial crisis of 1997, the Indonesian government has provided large subsidies for domestic retail fuels, equivalent to 5.5% of GDP in 2000 (IMF 2003). In 2002, it introduced an automatic price adjustment system under which Pertamina, the state- owned oil company, resets prices of domestic oil products each month (except for kerosene), at 75% of international prices. In September 2005, the government announced another sharp rollback of subsidies, which more than doubled the retail prices of gasoline and diesel. To protect the poor from the effect of these increases, the government uses some of the savings from the reduction in subsidies to introduce a programme of cash transfers. These are aimed at financing poverty reduction, rural development, education and health programmes. The government still maintains subsidies on kerosene", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fe126f15-f831-441d-933b-e3b6e4c6d66d": {"__data__": {"id_": "fe126f15-f831-441d-933b-e3b6e4c6d66d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "28a40256e0caffaec780653f5be2333c353b0504a83cfa08eede5c7f2c15b793"}, "3": {"node_id": "e64ba871-b9a3-4865-8181-d31b485e4060", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e2dcedec558c04702b4ff02f25958de3fd1ba8f3c12241589019d80544170ea0"}}, "hash": "23ba7a4bb9c61e26a9f6331c84fab0286ab43f10eb6359208fb327d070bd26b4", "text": "prices, although there have been moves toward more targeted subsidies. \u2022 Both rural and urban households experienced a 210% increase in their expenditure on kerosene at unofficial (black market) prices, which were nearly double those of official prices. In fact, the unofficial price prevailed across the country. \u2022 Petrol prices rose by 140%, which affected households with motorcycles, though these were not necessarily the poor. \u2022 Expenditure on public transport rose faster among rural households, at 50%, compared to 30% among urban households, because of longer distances covered by the former. \u2022 Urban households, however, experienced significantly higher energy expenditure due to their greater reliance on petroleum products and their lack of recourse to biomass fuels for cooking \u2013 a 70% increase compared to the 30 % rise among rural households. Lao PDR: Retail prices of petroleum products in Lao PDR generally reflect changes in import prices. But some price control exists through tax and duty structure, along with other charges. Between 2003 and 2006, retail prices of gasoline and diesel almost doubled, though the government has intermittently introduced duty exemptions to slow the pass-through. In order to reduce the costs of transportation and production, the government has kept diesel prices around 15% below gasoline prices. \u2022 Kerosene prices increased by 90.5%, while LPG prices grew at a much lower rate of 20%. Since only urban households, mainly the non-poor, use LPG, the rural poor have suffered more through the steep rise in prices for kerosene, which is essential for home lighting. \u2022 The average increase in diesel and petrol prices has been 85.5% across the country. However, expenditure on public transport among rural households rose by 118%, suggesting a scarcity premium imposed by transport service providers. \u2022 The rise in transportation expenditure among urban households was 63% in one district and 178% in another district of Vientiane. The higher expenditure was incurred by households owning motorcycles, and the rate of the increase, compared to the official price, suggests the existence of a black market for petrol. \u2022 Overall expenditures on energy increased by 90% among rural households, somewhat higher than the 85% increase experienced by urban households. 65 Results of 2008 Mongolia HH survey conducted by UNDP Mongolia in collaboration with CSD (UNDP, 2008): On an average, for the urban households, retail petrol prices have gone up by 58.8 % and diesel prices by 56.9% due to the oil price rise. In comparison, for the rural households, retail petrol prices have gone up by 92.3% and diesel prices by 74.9%. \u2022 Transport expenditure has gone up by 90% in the urban and 104% in rural areas. \u2022 Public transport related expenditure went up by 60% in urban and 120% in rural \u2022 In the post-oil price rise scenario, for the urban households, the share of transport expenditure in income has risen to 15.9% and it is 24.1% in expenditure. Whereas these percentages are 8.9% and 18.2% for rural households. \u2022 In the cases of both urban and rural households, the share of expenditure on food and water in total expenditure has reduced from pre- to post-oil price rise times. However, this share has increased by about 8% in the case of transport related expenditure. Other Countries \u2022 When oil prices exceeded US$ 130 per barrel, the Malaysian government decided to increase the pump prices of gasoline and diesel by 41% and 63% respectively (Malaysia Economic Report, 2008). \u2022 To reduce the burden, Malaysian government introduced on 14 June 2008, to cover the period April 2008 to March 2009, cash payouts of RM 625 per vehicle, for owners of four-wheelers and RM 150 for two-wheeler owners. In the interiors, these payouts are RM 200 and RM 50 respectively (Malaysia Economic Report, 2008). \u2022 Malaysian government continues to subsidise diesel at RM 1.43 litre for fishermen and transport operators. For petrol powered taxi operators, they can continue buying petrol at subsidized price of RM 1.92 per litre subject to a maximum of 720 litres per month. \u2022 In Pakistan, though the prices of petroleum products in the international market have increased in the range of 91% to 104% during the period May 2004 to April 2007, the domestic sale prices have increased only in the range of 45% to 55% in the same period (Afia, 2008).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e64ba871-b9a3-4865-8181-d31b485e4060": {"__data__": {"id_": "e64ba871-b9a3-4865-8181-d31b485e4060", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "28a40256e0caffaec780653f5be2333c353b0504a83cfa08eede5c7f2c15b793"}, "2": {"node_id": "fe126f15-f831-441d-933b-e3b6e4c6d66d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "23ba7a4bb9c61e26a9f6331c84fab0286ab43f10eb6359208fb327d070bd26b4"}}, "hash": "e2dcedec558c04702b4ff02f25958de3fd1ba8f3c12241589019d80544170ea0", "text": "Till 2003-04 inflation in Pakistan was below 3.9%, which climbed to 9.3% in 2004-05 and remained high at 8 and 7.9% during 2005-06 and 2006-07 respectively. Climbing down the energy ladder The energy ladder is a concept describing the process of people switching from conventional to increasingly modern energy carriers as their incomes", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fd375d0d-ae2b-4e1f-b3d0-8a80f449b70e": {"__data__": {"id_": "fd375d0d-ae2b-4e1f-b3d0-8a80f449b70e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "be0dd02650f535d55aa1dc44b761ac695ee17473a33e8dc2640ee8ba732c4ed4"}}, "hash": "be0dd02650f535d55aa1dc44b761ac695ee17473a33e8dc2640ee8ba732c4ed4", "text": "rise. For those at the bottom rungs of the ladder, the poor, it means moving up from a labour-intensive way of life that consumes a disproportionate amount of their time to an energy-intensive way of life that unleashes their human potential for betterment. Increases in the prices of oil products have reversed this process for many poor households, forcing them to either consume less of these products or to fall back upon inferior sources of energy. For certain critical uses, these households have had little option but to pay ever-increasing prices for fuels and other oil products, which has encroached upon their other needs. The sample HHs surveyed indicated the following: \u2022 Some 36% of kerosene-using households in India and 80% in the rural communities of Indonesia have reduced their consumption of kerosene for cooking. Instead, they have reverted to biomass and dung cakes wholly or partly. Urban households in Indonesia that do not have these options continue to pay higher prices for kerosene, but at the cost of other household expenditures. \u2022 In China, 89% of the rural households using LPG and coal for cooking have switched partly or entirely to fuel wood and crop residue. Some 29% of the urban households have 66 reached the limits of their ability to absorb higher LPG prices and plan to shift to coal if LPG prices climb further. \u2022 Higher public transport costs have curtailed the poor\u2019s access to essential services, especially those in rural communities. Several villagers in Lao PDR have gone back to travelling by foot or horseback to the nearest district centre, where the health care services and markets are located. \u2022 Urban migrant workers in India now travel less frequently to their home villages. Motorcycle users in China, Indonesia and Lao PDR, unable to restrict their essential travels have borne higher petrol prices, with adverse implications for their other expenditure. \u2022 Lacking other options, most poor households have continued to incur higher expenditures on kerosene for home lighting. Some very poor households in India, unable to pay the price, stay in darkness during long hours of power outages. On the whole, rising oil prices have left the poor with few choices other than to cut back on their consumption of oil products or, for uses that cannot be avoided, to bear the higher prices and look elsewhere in their household budgets to find the additional money. Since the urban poor rely more on oil products like kerosene and LPG, they are worse off than their rural counterparts who are either biomass users or have the biomass option to fall back upon. On the other hand, the rural poor are at a greater disadvantage when it comes to transport fuel costs, because inability to pay for these means forgoing essential services not available in the villages. Pacific Islands are particularly impacted by increases in transport costs as in many countries the only rural transport is by outboard-engined skiffs and livelihoods rely on fishing in these vessels. On the other hand few rural Pacific households have access to modern energy sources and rely primarily on bio-mass fuel for cooking, although kerosene is often used for lighting. Impact on lifestyles and livelihoods Across all countries, wherever families have switched to biomass fuels, the worst-affected have been women and children, who not only suffer from increased pollution at home but also have to spend more time and effort gathering fuels. This has been a particularly critical phenomenon in China and India, where such a switch has occurred in large numbers. As a result of rising transport costs, 64% of the surveyed rural households in Lao PDR reported scaling down their expenditures on children\u2019s education and 35% said they are able to spend less on items other than the most essential like food, clothing and health care. In India, rising transport costs have compelled a few households, in both rural and urban, to move their children to schools closer to their homes from better ones farther away. Rising household expenditures due in part to higher energy costs have obliged women to take on extra work. Among urban households surveyed in India, many women have started working, mostly as domestic help in other houses, in order to supplement family incomes. The majority of families interviewed are contemplating loans from moneylenders, self-help groups, banks and family members to cope. To overcome the burden of high fuel prices, about 66% of the urban and 76% of the rural households in Mongolia have stated that they have partially reduced consumption of relatively expensive food items like meat and moved to cheaper forms of bread", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a1f2f8e9-42b5-4864-a488-1d70a40c04a8": {"__data__": {"id_": "a1f2f8e9-42b5-4864-a488-1d70a40c04a8", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a6690d79b5ecedd04973b88f60c08fdfd68d80910cbd7e8e10fbec252fbce8f6"}}, "hash": "a6690d79b5ecedd04973b88f60c08fdfd68d80910cbd7e8e10fbec252fbce8f6", "text": "and 51% of the urban and 25% of the rural households have said that they have switched to less expensive alternatives, both food and fuel types. As a strategy to overcome the crisis due to oil price rise, majority of the households in Mongolia have modified their food consumption patterns preferring cheaper options, resorted to partial reduction in fuel 67 consumption and opted for loans from friends and relatives as well as commercial banks as a short term solution expecting a turnaround in the economic situation. Implications for the MDGs The survey data revealed that the higher public transport costs have curtailed the poor\u2019s access to essential services like hospitals and markets. In the case of Mongolia, travel to work, hospital and shopping are the most important transport needs of the urban households whereas travel to hospital and shopping are the most important transport needs of rural households. Increase in cost has forced the sample group of households to make compromises on accessing these services with serious negative implications for poverty removal and universal health care goals. Higher retail prices of fuels and petroleum products like fertilizers have economy-wide inflationary and/or recessionary impacts, leading to higher unemployment. Forced climb down the energy ladder reported in the survey has implications for maternal and child health care. Such climb down results in usage of traditional fuels for cooking causing indoor pollution. In households forced to switch back to traditional biomass fuels, demands upon the time of women and children for fuel collection and cooking has increased. This will eat into the time they will have for other, more productive activities. This has implications for gender equality and women empowerment. 6. Policy responses to the Food and Fuel price Inflation Policy responses adopted by governments to address fuel and food price increases have been varied. Some of the measures implemented are more cost-effective and less distortionary than others. A number of countries may have moved to implement universal rather than targeted measures because they allow a quicker response. First let us analyse macro policy responses: 6.1 Macro policy responses Monetary responses to the Food and Fuel price Inflation Monetary policy stance in many countries in Asia and the Pacific has moved towards more tightening given sharply rising inflation, but at the same time policy stance also become more cautious given the worsening global economic outlook and the increased volatility of the financial markets. Central banks in India, Indonesia, Pakistan, Philippines, Thailand, Taiwan (China), Vietnam have raised policy rates and/or cash reserve requirement ratios. Central Bank of China has raised the bank reserve requirement ratio several times in the recent years to absorb the excess cash from its BOP surplus. However, it has not raised policy interest rates. In fact, in mid-September 2008 it has cut interest rates and reserve requirement ratios to maintain stable economic growth. The Central banks in Malaysia and Korea have maintained their key rate, pointing out that inflation is generally supply-driven and that increasing the rate may dampen demand and weaken overall economic growth. Some Central banks indicated, however, that they may change their policy should inflation risks persist. Singapore tightened policy through a stronger currency, while Sri Lanka tightened its monetary policy stance by issuing its own securities to mop up the excess liquidity and contain reserve money growth. Bangladesh: To curb inflation expectations, the spread between short term and long term rates of government securities has been reduced through adjustments in yields on short term bills and long term government bonds. In the foreign exchange market, Bangladesh Bank (the central bank) undertook measures to arrest undue volatility in the exchange rate to reduce the impact of world inflation on the domestic price level; keeping due attention to impact on 68 exports and inflow of remittances. Bangladesh has been able to, by and large, keep inflation under check. The targeted inflation rate for 2009 FY is 9 %. The policy stance also targets a GDP growth rate of 6.5 %. The Bangladesh Bank (BB, hence forth) is also thinking of rationalization/reduction of duties, appropriate phasing and timing of import of food grains and essential food items, strengthening internal procurement of food grains, increasing the efficiency of food grain trading and marketing, installing effective market monitoring and surveillance system, efficient programming of targeted distribution and open market sale operations, and other measures to reduce any undue strain on market operations. The monetary policy stance of FY08 also aimed at supporting the government\u2019s growth stimulating and poverty reduction programs through using the monetary instruments at the disposal of BB. The imperatives identified for H2 FY08 covered two strategic", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8bc4efde-1ad4-4842-b304-9c33e1bdee29": {"__data__": {"id_": "8bc4efde-1ad4-4842-b304-9c33e1bdee29", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "018348a5586b61b06d1aa550927ad57d541a1dc90b02e8029122ef70d8609225"}}, "hash": "018348a5586b61b06d1aa550927ad57d541a1dc90b02e8029122ef70d8609225", "text": "thrusts: first, ensure reasonable price stability and support the building up of the economy\u2019s adjustment capacity to internal and external shocks; and second, put in place more effective monetary and financial measures to accommodate growth augmenting policies. China: after five years of running a tight monetary policy, it has cut interest rates (Sept 15, 2008) and eased bank lending restrictions indicating a cooling of the economy. The People's Bank of China cut its one-year lending rate by 27 basis points (bps), lowering the cost of one- year bank loans to 7.2%. However, for now, the benchmark deposit rates remain unchanged with the one-year rate at 4.14%. The Chinese central bank will also lower the reserve ratio for all except the country's five biggest banks and the Postal Savings Bank by 1%. The central bank aim in terms of monetary policy is to maintain fast, stable and equitable economic growth. The interest rate cut marks a partial reversal of a steady stream of increases in reserves, which the People's Bank of China raised on 18 occasions between July 2006 and June 2008 to absorb the excess cash from its balance of payment surplus. India: Keeping in view the liquidity conditions and inflationary pressures in the economy, the cash reserve ratio was raised by 75 basis points to 8.25 % during April-May 2008 in three stages of 25 basis points each effective from April 26, May 10, and May 24, 2008. On May 30, 2008, special market operations were announced to alleviate the binding financing constraints faced by public sector oil companies in importing POL as also to minimise the potential adverse consequences for financial markets in which these oil companies are important participants. On a review of the current macroeconomic and overall monetary conditions and with a view to containing inflation expectations, the repo rate under the Liquidity Adjustment Facility (LAF) was raised by 25 basis points to 8.0 % with effect from June 12, 2008. To check inflationary pressures the repo rate was increased under the LAF by 50 basis points to 8.50 % on June 25, 2008 and the CRR by 50 basis points to 8.75 % in two stages of 25 basis points each with effect from July 5, 2008 and July 19, 2008. However, as recently as September 6th, India's most widely watched price measure, rose 12.14 % in the 12 months to Sept. 6, marginally above the previous week's 12.10 % and exceeding a Reuters forecast for 12.09 %. Further tightening of monetary policy is expected to keep inflation in check; however it is likely to slow down over all growth, as indicated by a revision in the forecasted growth rates. Philippines: Against the background of a continuous surge in energy and food prices, average headline inflation rose to 9.7 % from 5.6 % in the previous quarter (Q2). The strong price dynamics of food and oil have also started to feed into other prices, as evident in the uptrend in core inflation. Core inflation, which measures the underlying trend in inflation by excluding specific food and energy items, accelerated to 6.2 % during the review quarter from 4.1 % in the previous quarter (Q2). Consequently, in June, the Monetary Board raised 69 the Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas\u2019 (BSP) key policy interest rates by 25 basis points to 5.25 % for the overnight borrowing or reverse repurchase (RRP) facility and 7.25 % for the overnight lending or repurchase (RP) facility. Then again in July, both these rates were driven further upwards: RRP by 50 basis points to 5.75% and RP also by 50 basis points to 7.75%. The Monetary Board believed that a more decisive monetary action was necessary as price pressures have increased and second-round effects have already set in. Thailand: as consistent with measures most other countries have taken in the region in light of the upward price pressure due to the oil and food inflation, Thailand also opted to also raise the main interest rate. The Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) on July 16 decided the raise the policy interest rate from 3.25 % to 3.50 % per annum. Indonesia: The Board of Governors' Meeting at Bank Indonesia (BI) on August 5, 2008 decided to raise the BI Rate by 25 basis points to 9.00%. This decision was taken to bolster the stability of the Indonesian economy and financial system and specifically to support the medium-term outlook for the inflation target. To reinforce monetary policy effectiveness, the decision to raise the BI rate was taken in tandem with optimisation of other monetary policy instruments for control exchange rate volatility and absorption of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7b4b008d-8d99-4410-95b8-0568ac7d599f": {"__data__": {"id_": "7b4b008d-8d99-4410-95b8-0568ac7d599f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "51fdca4ad0af54aee50101eaedf80fb979e70f5c3787163c422aac9ba649e362"}}, "hash": "51fdca4ad0af54aee50101eaedf80fb979e70f5c3787163c422aac9ba649e362", "text": "excess liquidity in Open Market Operations (OMO). Under this integrated policy, the targeted inflation of 6.5%-7.5% in 2009 is regarded as achievable. Pakistan: In FY08, oil and food imports requirements constituted around 40 % of total import payments. With non- oil non- food imports registering a strong growth momentum (24.2 %), aggregate growth in imports was 31.2 % that is much higher than the last five years average of 24 %. Therefore, as a net food importer, not only is Pakistan\u2019s Balance of Payments affected, it carries a heavy financial burden in light of the hike in market prices of oil and food commodities. There has been significant domestic borrowing and they continued unabated with additional borrowing of Rs149.8 billion during May 25 to June 30, 2008. Budget for fiscal year FY09 estimates put the fiscal deficit at 7 % of GDP, while financing data available to SBP for the full FY08 shows that this could be as high as 8.3 % of GDP. The burden of subsidies and rising consumption demand have widened macroeconomic imbalances in addition to pressures felt by the exchange rate. With regard to the interest rate, it has only been increasing. As far back as July 2007, the State Bank of Pakistan (SBP) policy rate was raised by 50 bps to 10 % simply to allow for sterilization of excessive foreign inflows, which came in the last two weeks of FY07, and stem anticipated inflationary pressures. Then in January 2008, viewing the developments in H1- FY08 and outlook for future, SBP advocated the need for strengthening demand management and raised policy rate by another 50 bps to 10.5 %. Then again in May 2008 the SBP increased the policy discount by 150 basis points to 12.0 %. Sri Lanka: inflation has been rampant, primarily driven by the global rise in food and oil prices. It reached a value of 28.2 % in June and since then has come down to around the 25 % mark. Given this scenario the Central Bank has decided to tighten its monetary policy stance by restraining the expansion in reserve money. Accordingly, the Bank further revised downwards its reserve money targets for the third quarter of the year over and above the already tightened reserve money targets announced in April 2008. With this revision, the targeted rate of expansion in the annual average of reserve money has been lowered from 12.50 % to 11.75 %. Credit to the private sector, which was as high as 26 % in April 2007, had decelerated to 12.7 % by end June 2008. In terms of the Central Bank\u2019s policy of restraining from investing in new Treasury bills, the Bank had exhausted its stock of Treasury 70 bills available for open market operations. Hence, the Bank has moved to issuing its own securities to mop up the excess liquidity and contain reserve money growth. However, in the past month (August 2008) there has been a decline in food prices globally and also a containment in demand pressures due to an active contractionary monetary policy. The inflation, in addition to high fuel and food prices can also be attributed to the expenditure of approximately $1.5 billion (2008) towards the war effort. Pacific Islands: More than half of the Pacific Island countries are constrained in their use of monetary policy as a tool of macroeconomic management due to their use of third-country currencies as their medium of exchange. In most of those that are able to use monetary instruments their capital markets are relatively undeveloped and interest rates are not regarded as an effective tool for influencing economic behaviour. Exchange rate policy is likewise also constrained and few countries have been able to adjust exchange rates to provide compensatory movements to mitigate the inflationary impacts of the rising prices. In Fiji, one of the most developed in the region, the Reserve bank recently relaxed some of the tight monetary restraints that had been in place since the military coup of December 2006. The need to stimulate investment and employment would appear to be paramount at the present time. It is clear that countries generally accommodated the first-round effects of higher food and fuel prices on inflation. However, in the recent months, many countries are tightening their monetary policies to prevent the first-round effects of higher food and fuel prices on inflation from spilling over to higher prices of other goods and services. This is because the second- round effects may trigger a wage-price spiral. This is particularly important for countries where inflation has already been rising because of overly expansionary macroeconomic policies. Fiscal responses", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c41f2cf4-33c7-4957-b97a-4668788d83ab": {"__data__": {"id_": "c41f2cf4-33c7-4957-b97a-4668788d83ab", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5b21b38bcb15f51b4055958473492ba254737a87079b95032d561638e000a04e"}}, "hash": "5b21b38bcb15f51b4055958473492ba254737a87079b95032d561638e000a04e", "text": "to the Food and Fuel price Inflation Along with monetary tightening, countries also use various fiscal measures to mitigate adverse effect of inflation. As the course of monetary tightening often incurs undesirable costs of slowing growth, it is critical to closely monitor the situations and ensure essential fiscal support to cushion the weaker segments of society. Countries have adopted various fiscal measures in response to high oil and food prices. One notices, in the 2008 or 2009 budget, an increased emphasis on planning towards mitigating future food and fuel crisis through expansionary fiscal spending on agriculture. Even in the short run a number of countries have to bear the brunt of the increased subsidy bill towards food and fuel. In the medium-term this is leading to a mounting and unsustainable deficit. Consequently, some countries like India, Indonesia, Malaysia and Sri Lanka are trying to phase out food and fuel subsidies. In 2008, Indonesia reduced fuel subsidies and raised fuel prices by 30%. However, the reduction was only partial as remaining subsidies remain high. Moreover, the direct cash assistance programme to protect the poor from the fuel price also increase fiscal burden. Malaysia also reduced fuel subsidies and raised fuel prices by 40% in 2008, as it introduced subsidies programme to boost agricultural production. Korea and the Philippines have reduced or exempted import tariffs on agricultural and fuel products. Thailand reinstated fuel subsidies in March 2008 for 6 months to limit the impact on domestic prices. In Bangladesh the subsidies and transfers bill accounts for about 35% of government expenditure during the period July 2007 to April 2008. This is a 15% increase since 2005. To increase future agriculture production, the government has given Taka 1100 crore as 71 agriculture subsidy for FY 2005-06. Due to price hike of fertilizer in international market and recent increase of fuel price, the agricultural subsidy for FY 2006-07 has been estimated at Taka 2000 crore, of which Taka. 1100 crore will be needed for fertiliser subsidy. In addition to the subsidy, the government is also providing incentives for agricultural development such as 30 % cash incentive for agricultural exports and 20 % rebate on utility bills of agro-based industries. Bangladesh has also reduced interest rates of agriculture credit from 8 % to 2 % to boost agricultural production. With regard to the \u2018food account\u2019 section in the latest budget 2008-2009, the subsidy allocated for food (which is different for subsidy for agriculture) is Taka 1316 crore. This figure is likely to be revised. In any case, it is substantially more (almost double) than the Taka 733 crore subsidy for food in 2007-2008. Indonesia continues to subsidize fuel and electricity consumption by maintaining a sizeable gap between domestic and international oil prices. Subsidies are expected to make up about 20% of central government expenditure during 2008, with those on fuel taking up the lion\u2019s share of the total. In an attempt to limit the negative impact of high oil prices on the state budget, the government was forced in May 2008 to increase subsidised fuel prices by an average of 29%, in order to reduce the budget cost of the subsidies. Moreover, given recent trends showing a decline in oil prices, the Indonesian government has proposed to cut fuel subsidy by 44% in 2009. To cope in general with the food and fuel price inflation, the Indonesian government has come up with a targeted response. The salient elements of this comprehensive plan include \u2022 subsidized rice distribution (to be raised in 2008 to 15 kg per household per month for 9 months (Rp 1,600/kg)); \u2022 import duty on rice to be lowered to Rp 450 per kg; \u2022 higher rice production in 2008/2009 through accelerated provision of high quality seeds; \u2022 retention of progressive export taxes on palm oil and derivative products with adjustments; \u2022 retention of zero-rated (government paid) VAT for domestic sales of bulk cooking oil and with expanded coverage to include packaged cooking oil; \u2022 subsidized sales of unbranded cooking oil to low income earners and MSEs for 6 months (average subsidy Rp 2,500 per litre); \u2022 elimination of import duties on soybeans, reduction in tax on imported soybeans from 2.5% to 0.5%, subsidized sales of soybean for small-scale fermented soy bean cake/tofu production for 6 months (average subsidy Rp 1,000 per kg), continuation of existing program for promoting domestic soybean production with expansion for development of soybean estates; \u2022 elimination of import duty on flour, introduction of zero-rated VAT policy for wheat, revision with deferment of compulsory Indonesian National Standard for wheat imports, MSMEs encouraged to participate in kerosene", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f61d7043-3b4e-4005-8735-c7732fe265bc": {"__data__": {"id_": "f61d7043-3b4e-4005-8735-c7732fe265bc", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f265874f0b88f0befaf2be7dee4ea4db7ffd057b232322fa6c788788bc12e81f"}, "3": {"node_id": "8cbea4c8-5b8e-44b9-94f0-43c417d73c10", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d18302474febde4ff095b128baaff47617a35760bf77716b6913bf69f2cad261"}}, "hash": "49e106f71b8cf64bb40d241bb1fc5078ab070452f05af3eadf7bda566cc3a312", "text": "to gas conversion through distribution of gas storage tanks and burners. More medium to long-term measures include (i) food diversification, including promotion of the development and use of flours produced from local cassava and other tuberous plants; (ii) Promote ownership and implementation of Environmental Development Partnership Program for food crops; (iii) closed system for kerosene distribution along the lines of the rice for poor\" (Raskin) system, accelerated kerosene to gas conversion, intensified enforcement operations against fraudulent use of kerosene and 1% reduction in distribution expenses and margin on fuel sales. 72 India is mostly self-sufficient in terms of food staples with the exception of wheat. 2007-08 was a bumper crop year of India with food grain production estimated at about 220 million tonnes with rice production at 94 million tonnes, maize at 17 million tonnes, and soya bean at 9.5 million tonnes. Many of these numbers are all time records. Nonetheless, the public distribution system, the largest food distribution system in the world runs a food subsidy of about 25,000 crore Rupees per annum. This has increased more than four fold since a decade ago. Together with other food welfare programmes Rupees 32,667 crore will be provided next year for food subsidy. The government is trying to make the PDS a more effective and efficient system in light of the enormous fiscal burden it currently poses. In addition and towards this end, the thirteenth Finance Commission to be requested to revisit the roadmap for fiscal adjustment and suggest a suitably revised roadmap, after the obligations on account of the Sixth Central Pay Commission becomes clear. With regard to the next year\u2019s budget, some pertinent highlights in terms of spending are; Under agriculture and cooperation, the government has allocated 1100 crore rupees for the national food security mission; 500 crore rupees for Micro Irrigation, 644 crore rupees for the National Agriculture Insurance Scheme (NAIS); 299 crore rupees for a Technology Mission on Horticulture in NE Region, Jammu & Kashmir and Uttrakhand; 320 crore rupees for Integrated Oilseeds, Oil Palm, Pulses & Maize Development Scheme. Under Animal Husbandary, dairying and fisheries 130 crore rupees has been allocated for a Livestock Census; 160 crore rupees for a special package for farming population in 31 suicide prone districts in the country; and 75 crore rupees for a National Fisheries Development Board. Under agricultural research and education the government intends to spend 315 crore rupees for research issues in Crop Sciences; 350 crore rupees for agricultural education to improve the quality of human resource, upgrade infrastructure and educational reforms; 281 crore rupees for agricultural extension programmes to disseminate frontline technologies; 257 crore rupees for National Agricultural Innovation Project and 45 crore rupees for Fisheries research and quality fish seed. Thailand: Internal price stability is facing higher risks from increasing inflationary pressure. Headline inflation in July increased to 9.2 % (y-o-y), from 8.9 % (y-o-y) in June, due to continued rising oil price and food-related prices. However, it is expected that the inflationary pressure will be subsided in the near future as result of the six economic assistance programs, and the declining trend of oil price. Unemployment rate in June 2008 remained low at1.2 % of the total labour force. Public debt to GDP as of June was at 35.8 %, remained well below the 50 % public debt ceiling under the Fiscal Sustainability Framework. In terms of fiscal expenditure during the first 10 months of fiscal year 2008 (October 2007 - June 2008), the spending amounted to 1,359 billion Baht, expanding at 4.4 % (y-o-y). This is 76.4 % of the Fiscal Year 2008 budget expenditure. The fiscal expenditure is expected to meet the target disbursement rate of 94.0 % of the Fiscal Year 2008. Vietnam is on balance a food exporting country which has not borne the brunt of the food price hike. Also, the government has cut fuel subsidies, which will lead to a reduction in its overall expenditure. Although the government may cut back some spending programmes in an effort to cool the economy, expenditure will remain high, as the government is still committed to programmes to improve social welfare provisions.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8cbea4c8-5b8e-44b9-94f0-43c417d73c10": {"__data__": {"id_": "8cbea4c8-5b8e-44b9-94f0-43c417d73c10", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f265874f0b88f0befaf2be7dee4ea4db7ffd057b232322fa6c788788bc12e81f"}, "2": {"node_id": "f61d7043-3b4e-4005-8735-c7732fe265bc", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "49e106f71b8cf64bb40d241bb1fc5078ab070452f05af3eadf7bda566cc3a312"}}, "hash": "d18302474febde4ff095b128baaff47617a35760bf77716b6913bf69f2cad261", "text": "The new income tax structure will broaden the tax base by making benefits as well as salaries taxable, and will apply the same tax rates to Vietnamese and foreign workers (the tax threshold for foreign workers will fall to match that for local workers. it is currently twice as high as that for local workers). The boost that the government received in 2007 from the oil price boom will be repeated this year-the continued upward trend in global crude", "start_ch