ign debt. The government thus does not have much space for fiscal manoeuvring and must pass on the burden of prices to the consumer. As such it will increase the support price of wheat from Rs 510 to Rs 625 per 40 kg. Also, it envisions a programme of phasing out subsidies on energy and food over time (time horizon has not been specified). However, there are some exceptions to this general rule, as the government proposed to more than double the subsidy on fertilizers from rupees 470 to rupees 1000 per bag. The total subsidy is increased from rupees 25 billion to rupees 32 billion. The government does however wish to scrap duty on imports related to food and agriculture. For example, exemption from 10% custom duty on import of rice seeds and also a waiver is proposed for the 5% excise duty on premium of crop insurance policy. Also, equipment and machinery for proper storage of food items is to be imported free of duty. In terms of improving tax collection, the government has proposed a broad based plan, which includes, (i)widening the tax base, (ii) reducing exemptions, (iii) providing incentives and concessions wherever required, (iv) reducing multiplicity of tax rates, (v) lowering tax rates, (vi) shifting the incidence of tax burden from production to consumption, (vii) moving away from the excessive reliance on manufacturing and taxing all value additions including services, (viii) enhancing the neutrality between present and future consumption, (ix) enhancing the neutrality of the tax system to forms of business organizations and sources of finance, (x) re- engineering the business process of the tax system to overcome the culture of tax avoidance and evasion, (xi) effecting business process changes in tax administration to establish an effective and efficient tax system. These are the guiding principles of the tax policy which the Government should focus on and employ. In Malaysia the cut in the fuel price subsidy announced in June, 2008 will help to keep the fiscal position stable. Revenue collection is likely to be boosted by high international oil prices, and also by the government\u2019s recently announced move to impose windfall taxes on palm oil producers and independent power-generating companies. The fiscal deficit will average 3.2% of GDP in 2008-09. The savings made as a result of the latest cut in the fuel price subsidy are unlikely to lead to a dramatic reduction in the budget deficit, as the subsidy on fuel was treated as an off-budget item. That said, the savings made as a result of the reduction in the fuel subsidy will be used to offset the cost of subsidies on food and other items that are expected to be introduced soon as part of a restructured subsidy scheme; these subsidies are included in the budget. Food security has become a high priority for the government, which has already set aside M$1.5bn (US$470m) in 2008 to subsidise rice farmers and to import rice to expand the national stockpile. The government\u2019s recent decision to postpone some large infrastructure projects will also lighten the fiscal burden this year. Pacific Islands: Almost all pacific Islands are heavily dependent on imported food particularly to supply the growing number of urban households. They are also almost totally dependent on imported fuel products. For the urban poor rice, cereal products and cooking oil are major components of household food expenditure. Taxes on imports are also a major source of government revenue, thus reductions in tariff rates to ease the burden of price rises 74 on the poor has the impact of increasing the pressure on, often already stretched, government finances. In many Pacific Island countries state-owned enterprises are at the forefront of power generation and inter-island island transport, thus the additional fuel costs associated with these activities impacts directly on budgets. In Tuvalu, for example, one of the smallest and most vulnerable, it", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7b9babac-24f0-4d76-9fb0-84c77e40463e": {"__data__": {"id_": "7b9babac-24f0-4d76-9fb0-84c77e40463e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6f1918058a333ed62f5e450b8b0534c6d854324049e4a22c77dc5c8d6db675f7"}}, "hash": "6f1918058a333ed62f5e450b8b0534c6d854324049e4a22c77dc5c8d6db675f7", "text": "has been estimated that the direct budget cost of increased food and fuel prices will amount to around 5% of GDP in 2008, causing the governments budget deficit to double. In Marshall Islands the government was so concerned at the impact of fuel prices on its power generator that a \u201cState of Emergency\u201d was declared to enable the government to gain control of the situation. Those Pacific island states that rely on revenues generated from trust funds or sovereign wealth funds, notably Kiribati and Tuvalu, to support their budgets are also being severely impacted by the sharp falls in global asset values that have occurred in recent months. A global recession will hurt Pacific states even further if fishing license fees should decline and the opportunities for overseas employment and the generation of remittances is adversely impacted. The scope for a fiscal response from Pacific governments to mitigating rising prices and the impact on the poor is therefore very limited. Only in Fiji has the government attempted to reduce tariffs on \u201cessential\u201d food items, including rice and cereal products, to mitigate the price increases. In other countries the primary response has been to exhort the public to return to consuming traditional crops, and thus to supporting local agriculture. It is clear that governments use actively fiscal policy response and pass-through effects. However, governments need to assess the overall fiscal cost of subsidies, transfers, safety net programmes, etc. Even the most efficient and effective policy responses to higher fuel and food prices can result in fiscal costs The available options to deal with the fiscal costs of policy responses depend in turn on individual countries\u2019 macroeconomic situation and their capacity to create fiscal space. For example, countries without binding debt sustainability, financing, or macro-stability constraints have scope to loosen their fiscal positions to accommodate the costs of measures taken in response to higher fuel and food prices. In countries with fiscal constraints, governments should create fiscal space to offset these fiscal costs without jeopardizing the sustainability of their financial position or the stability of the economy. Fiscal space can be created in a variety of ways, including by increasing revenue, reducing non-productive spending, raising borrowing in a non inflationary and sustainable way, and securing higher external grants or concessional loans provided by donors. Countries that find it difficult to create fiscal space would need to limit the size and duration of the fiscal response and pass-through the increase in international prices to domestic consumers more rapidly. To the extent possible, this should be accompanied by strengthening and expansion of cost-effective social safety nets. Trade related responses to the Food and Fuel price Inflation As food prices soared, a key component of the national policy response has been to stabilize food prices domestically thought the use of tariff and other trade related measures in the Asia Pacific region. Consolidated detailed information/data on national trade policy responses for the Asia Pacific region are not available and current applied tariff rates structures being maintained by countries are not available yet in the public domain. The analysis based on a secondary literature review and country level desk top research however does bring out a broad pattern of responses across countries in the region providing a snapshot of the trade related aspects of the food crises. Reduction/Elimination of Import Tariffs 75 When food price rise, governments have the option of either reducing or eliminating applied tariffs on import of food commodities (and vice versa of raising it up to the bound levels if prices fall to protect the agricultural sector from cheap commercially displacing imports). Although country by country current applied tariff levels are not readily available, it is fairly well known that applied MFN tariffs on basic food commodities in majority of developing countries are quite low already being in the range of 8-14% for the five basic food items (wheat, rice, maize, soya oil, palm oil).28 Given the sharp food price increase (when prices rose between 88 to 160% in early 200829), reduction or even elimination of import tariffs would have a limited impact on stabilizing domestic prices. For the select countries surveyed in Asia, the tariff instrument has been indeed been utilized as a mechanism to cushion the impact of high prices. Export Prohibitions, Restrictions and Export Taxation A typical response in some of the food exporting countries has been to put in place export prohibition measures including through restraining or banning exports for certain periods of time subject to review. Export taxes and fixing of minimum prices and quantitative restrictions have also been used as a response. The main idea", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "abe498c2-3a1c-464b-b763-438425d68b35": {"__data__": {"id_": "abe498c2-3a1c-464b-b763-438425d68b35", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fdbf018c8e735135134af2bc7d1a9f2bb3aaadebbaafba16a1ecaab971a48298"}}, "hash": "fdbf018c8e735135134af2bc7d1a9f2bb3aaadebbaafba16a1ecaab971a48298", "text": "has been to contain prices at a certain level while also ensuring that adequate food supplies are maintained. Thus countries like India, Indonesia, Pakistan, China, Cambodia, Vietnam have taken resort to these types of measures to varying degrees for basic commodities like wheat, rice, pulses, maize and edible oils. It may be useful to highlight a few specific instances of countries resorting to export prohibitions and other domestic policy measures of different types. In Indonesia, the government imposed controls over medium grade rice exports, since international rice prices were double that of the local prices. The State agency Bulog can now sell medium grade rice overseas only when national stocks are above 3 MT. Domestic prices also have to be set below a set government target price. Cambodia, except for border areas in Vietnam, placed a temporary ban on paddy export while removing the ban on pork imports. Domestically around 300 MT of rice was released to the market at lower than market price. Soft loans (US 10 m) were provided to state owned Green Trade Company and private rice millers for increasing paddy rice stock. In June, the government has lifted the export curbs on rice exports except for shipments in excess of 1 MT. The government is also considering a no tax policy on agricultural inputs and reduction of taxes on food imports. An additional focus is to increase agricultural productivity and taking steps to augment yields while increasing irrigated land and land available for cultivation. In the long run, the government would try to create grain storage facilities at the provincial and national levels, examine the feasibility of having a second rice crop, assessing the short term and medium term requirement for agricultural inputs including fertilizers and high yielding seed varieties, reduction of post harvest losses, promote aquaculture, improve information databases and examine policy options of tariffs, taxes and minimum support prices. Vietnam, after curtailing exports in March and April, extended a ban on signing of new rice export contracts and capped rice exports to 3.5 MT. It also banned speculators from its domestic market. In June, the government has lifted the export bans on news of an increase in rice production subject to the minimum price of USD 800 per Ton on an f.o.b. basis. In South Asia, the Indian government prohibited exports of non-basmati rice since February 2008 barring honouring of previous export contracts. In addition, minimum price fixation and export tax were also imposed on export of basmati rice. Restrictions also apply 28 Ramesh Sharma and Panos Konandreas, WTO Provisions in the context of responding to soaring food prices, FAO Commodity and Trade Policy Research Working Paper No. 25, FAO, August 2008 29 Ibid 76 on export of other varieties of rice. Other commodities which have been banned until April 2009 include wheat, edible oils, maize. Earlier, in 2007, the ban on export of pulses was freed of quantitative restrictions. Pakistan banned exports of wheat flour and export of pulses. While Thailand desisted from export ban measures, in May 2008, announced that the government would seek to create a cartel of rice producing countries in partnership with Vietnam, Cambodia, Myanmar and Laos. The move if successful would then sustain the current phase of high prices and worsen the impact to poor consumers across Asia. Thailand is the largest exporter of rice in the world (10 MT annually) followed by Vietnam. Two important questions arise in this context: one relating to the broad implications of these prohibitions on agriculture production and trade including on food insecurity for food importing countries and whether or not these types of measures are permissible under the WTO. Trade policy prohibitions and restrictions can have several adverse perhaps unintended consequences: \u2022 Trade related restrictions especially when implemented in an ad hoc and uncoordinated manner30 contribute directly to price instability in international markets by limited global supplies. This tends to worsen the food security situation in other countries especially when international trade in these commodities is thin. Thus for instance, global rice trade is thin with only about 7 % of rice production being traded internationally. Given the limited number of supplier countries any government intervention in the export or import market has the potential to affect the prices in a significant way. Thus for instance, net food importing countries like Bangladesh and Philippines took a big hit due to restrictions placed on global rice supplies. \u2022 Discourage domestic production since the due the wedge in domestic and international market price, producers stand to lose out on profits thereby influencing future investment and production decisions \u2022 they may lead", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "54f4bf58-ba3b-4b89-a564-664bd3542a45": {"__data__": {"id_": "54f4bf58-ba3b-4b89-a564-664bd3542a45", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3e8fca656706c5c802ee2bdff7e8cec57aa794afcb0d0c1b54caa715230f672f"}}, "hash": "3e8fca656706c5c802ee2bdff7e8cec57aa794afcb0d0c1b54caa715230f672f", "text": "to a dent in the reputation of the country as a reliable exporter by importing countries and loss of future trading opportunities especially when more than one supplier country is available which may potentially affect future export earnings; \u2022 lead importing countries to reassess their reliance on international trade as an assured way of meeting food security objectives and initiate national self sufficiency plans in food for the medium and long term; Are trade related prohibitions WTO Compatible? In general, the WTO provisions do not prohibit Member countries from undertaking steps to address national food shortages. Under the Agreement on Agriculture (AoA), export prohibitions and restrictions can be enforced by Member countries to relieve critical shortages of foodstuffs or other products essential to the exporting contracting party. (Article 12, reference to para 2(a) of the GATT Agreement)31 The only limiting factor is that for the net food exporting developing countries of the specific foodstuff concerned will have to give due consideration to the effects of such prohibitions or restriction on the food security of the 30 Soaring Food Prices: Facts, Perspectives, Impacts and Actions Required, FAO Background Paper for the High Level Conference on World Food Security: The Challenges of Climate Change and Bioenergy, June 2008 31 Ramesh Sharma and Panos Konandreas, WTO Provisions in the context of responding to soaring food prices, FAO Commodity and Trade Policy Research Working Paper No. 25, FAO, August 2008 77 importing member and to the extent practicable must be done with advance notice in writing and in consultation with the importing Member concerned. It is obvious that global food markets need to be kept open to avoid any distortion in the economy. Restrictive trade policies, such as export bans or export taxes imposed by net food exporters tend to have unintended negative consequences at the domestic level, and at the global level. They push up world prices even further and hurt net importers. From a global perspective, maintaining free trade in commodities while fostering incentives for production and using efficient policies to protect the urban poor (e.g., targeted cash transfers) is a priority. An ambitious Doha Round conclusion, including on agriculture, can help broaden and stabilize international food trade. While an ambitious Doha Round conclusion may not lead to lower food prices in the short term, it will foster efficient agricultural production in the medium and long term and boost global growth. As noted earlier, reduced tariffs on imported food can alleviate food prices pressures and improve efficiency. However, many poor countries have narrow tax bases and rely on tariffs and other trade taxes for a large part of government revenue. In such countries, it is important to ensure that the revenue loss from tariff or trade tax reductions can be accommodated without destabilizing countries\u2019 macroeconomic policies. To sum up, given the various constraints on monetary and fiscal policy, authorities have frequently resorted to administrative controls to reduce inflationary pressures. Such administrate measures include price controls, and increasing domestic supply by limiting exports or reducing import restrictions/duties. Countries such as China, Mongolia and Sri Lanka resorted to domestic price regulation. Similarly, many countries such as Cambodia, India, Indonesia, the Philippines and Vietnam have tried to improve domestic supply reducing import duties or limiting exports. Similarly countries such as Bangladesh, Malaysia and Philippines have trying to boost agricultural production by offering various incentives. Countries attempt to strike a balance between helping the poor to cope with the significant price increases, ensuring macroeconomic stability, and encourage increased agricultural production. Countries need to smooth adjustment to higher food and fuel prices by adopting short-term fiscal measures such as fiscal subsidies, tax exemptions, etc. As of now, the fiscal policy stance (in terms of the overall deficit) in most of the countries is in an acceptable level. However, a further increase in food and oil prices could require some fiscal tightening to counter inflation expectations. To that end, on helping the vulnerable groups in the short-term, there is a need to develop well-targeted social safety programmes such as food stamp systems or school feeding programmes. This is because many countries lacked any well-developed social safety net programmes. On the macroeconomic stability, countries need to monitor actively the fiscal situations and balance of payments implications of the food and fuel price developments. In the medium- term, macroeconomic stability requires full pass-through of food and fuel price increases to consumers. As of now, pass-through of food and fuel adjustment is low in many countries due to subsidies and tax cuts. But this aggregate fiscal burdens. Therefore, governments make an effort to full pass through food and fuel", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2bc58c34-2ced-4abd-a6d8-a1c418a58f27": {"__data__": {"id_": "2bc58c34-2ced-4abd-a6d8-a1c418a58f27", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8a828e96384ad61d23bf3df67f2dde9dbf421cccc50627edfd915d404ff1c298"}}, "hash": "8a828e96384ad61d23bf3df67f2dde9dbf421cccc50627edfd915d404ff1c298", "text": "price increases to rich consumers in order to safeguard the government budget. In this regard, there is need to close the gap between pump 78 prices and prices mandated by the price adjustment mechanism. Similarly, a full pass-through adjustment for food products in the medium-term will help to foster a positive agricultural supply response. On promoting increased supply in the medium-term, countries should avoid any distortionary price controls in view of their adverse effect on incentives for domestic production. In the medium-run, countries should also avoid any export restriction because it hinders expansion of agricultural production and encourages smuggling. In the longer term, countries should raise agricultural productivity through improving rural infrastructure and offering HYV seeds, fertilizer subsidies, etc. In the long-run, countries should also strengthen their social safety nets programme. It is clear that regional and international cooperation to facilitate the elimination of barriers to agricultural trade has become an urgent imperative in the wake of the food crisis. Measures such as the establishment of regional and sub regional commodity exchanges, and clearinghouses need to be considered. The government revenue losses from reduction or exemptions of temporary taxes and customs for petroleum products and some food products need to be monitored carefully. Similarly fiscal costs due to fiscal subsidies also need to be monitored carefully. Some countries eliminated or reduced custom tariffs for fuels and food imports and announced indicative prices for these products to monitor and support through a strengthened dialogue with wholesalers and retailers. It is also clear that international community should work with governments to urgently develop implement able safety net measures and improved targeted tax cuts, subsidies, and pro-poor spending to mitigate the adverse impact of food and petroleum price increases on the poor, design supply side measures to increase agricultural production, and strengthen monetary and exchange rate policies. The analysis here has made several key points. First, the recent surge in world cereal prices has been accompanied by a real depreciation of the US dollar. For many countries (but not all), this depreciation has neutralized a substantial proportion of the increase in world prices. Second, domestic commodity specific policies in several of these Asian countries have further stabilized domestic prices relative to the change in world prices. On average, the increase in domestic food prices was about half of the increase in real US dollar world market food prices. Although this might seem somewhat small, this should not be taken to imply that events on world markets have no consequences for food security: even relatively small price increases of 10 to 20% for staple foods have serious implications for the household food security of the poor. Third, the policy challenge is to ensure that economic efficiency and stability are maintained while at the same time protecting vulnerable population groups. The best option in the medium term is to develop a well-targeted social safety net that can protect vulnerable households in the face of rising prices. However, the design and implementation of such a programme is itself a challenge. 79 6.2 Responses to oil price shock32 Fuel Subsidies Governments often subsidize petroleum products, commonly household fuels such as kerosene and LPG but also in some cases transportation fuels. But they can find this very costly. Thailand, for example, in January 2004 introduced price ceilings for petroleum products, most of which continued until October 2004, and ceilings for diesel until February 2005 \u2013 resulting in a subsidy bill for that period of around US$ 2.2 billion (ESMAP 2006). Indonesia had a similar programme, which in 2005 produced a subsidy bill of about US$ 9.9 billion. That increased to about US$ 9.3 billion in 2007. An IMF study concluded that for a range of countries subsidy expenditures could be higher than health and education expenditures combined (IMF 2006). Governments will want therefore to ensure that subsidy programmes are well- managed and accurately targeted for the poor. Malaysia, for example, in 2006 launched a smart-card scheme targeted at public transport operators and fishermen, giving them access to subsidies through a monthly quota based on vehicle category or boat size. When subsidies were further reduced in 2008, targeted cash transfers were made to private owners of small vehicles. In India, under-recoveries due to subsidization of Kerosene and LPG prices had reached US$ 12.32 billion in 2006-07 (Mahurkar, 2007). In Pacific island countries subsidies are generally only available to specific industries, including state- owned power generators and commercial fishing enterprises, some countries also provide a concessionary duty rate on out-board engine fuel in recognition of the importance of this transport system and the role of inshore fisheries in", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7fca1e61-9066-4668-b2cb-7f91791da00f": {"__data__": {"id_": "7fca1e61-9066-4668-b2cb-7f91791da00f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0c54844a897845bff4ca9c575e0a876f14f7fcbd39f2f524403c4c0a7b9e4705"}}, "hash": "0c54844a897845bff4ca9c575e0a876f14f7fcbd39f2f524403c4c0a7b9e4705", "text": "food security. Tax adjustment Because many retail petroleum products, especially transportation fuels, can be quite heavily taxed, governments can smooth the prices for consumers by adjusting the rates of taxation. This has been the main form of adjustment in Bangladesh and Lao PDR. Following the recent oil price rise, more governments have resorted to tax adjustments rather than subsidies. In India, the taxes on gasoline and diesel were reduced by 3% and 4% respectively in November 2006 as compared to 2005 rates. Compensation schemes Compensating the poor to offset the impact of price rise is another method adopted by the governments. Indonesia, for example, after reducing subsidies on petroleum products in 2005 redirected some of the savings to a cash transfer programme for the poor of about US$ 30 per household every three months, as well as to poverty reduction programmes in education, rural development and health. China too has in some provinces briefly introduced cash transfer schemes to help tide consumers over rising oil prices. Governments also may consider that other safety net programmes offer good opportunities for targeting. Sri Lanka, for example, has a food stamps programme that is substantially better targeted than those for kerosene subsidies (IMF 2006). A number of countries in the region have applied one or more of these pricing-related measures. Stabilization funds: These can be used by both oil exporters and importers. Based on pre- determined rules, exporters will pay into the fund when prices are high and can withdraw from them when prices are lower. Importers do the opposite. Thailand established an oil price stabilization fund in 2004 to finance oil price subsidies. While the initial large demand upon the fund has subsided because of the subsequent removal of diesel and gasoline subsidies, the 32 This sub-section relies heavily on UNDP report \u201cOvercoming Vulnerabili ty to Rising Oil Prices: Options for Asia and the Pacific\u201d, UNDP Regional Centre, Bangkok, 2007 80 fund remains an important source of financing for LPG subsidies of about US$ 12.6 million a month (ADB 2005). India and the Philippines have had such funds, but these have now been suspended. Long-term contracts: Countries also may shield themselves from short-term fluctuations in oil prices by engaging in long-term contracts based on prices that are fixed, or adjustable within agreed ceilings. Most of the trade in natural gas uses such contracts, but they are less common in the oil sector where, even in long-term contracts, the prices are linked to market prices. At present, however, there seems to be a move away from long-term contracts even for natural gas and crude oil, so this does not seem like a useful immediate option. However, there are countries which prefer long-term contracts; for example, Republic of Korea in 2007 had opted for 70% of the oil imports under long-term contract (KITA, 2008). Enhancing oil supply Although the supply of oil is finite, governments in the region can take a number of measures to enhance supplies. These include: Strengthening oil exploration and extraction - Higher prices can spur the search for new sources or encourage the exploitation of those hitherto unattractive. In Viet Nam, for example, exploration activities have been yielding results: In October 2004, a joint venture comprising American Technologies, Petronas, Singapore Petroleum, and PetroVietnam announced a 100-million-barrel oil discovery off the country\u2019s northeast coast. The Philippines too, though having only small reserves, in its Energy Plan 2005 stressed intensive promotion of oil and gas exploration. Exxon Mobil, the world's biggest oil and gas producer, is set to start oil exploration in the country and said it hopes it would produce encouraging results by the middle of 2009 (Chinaview, 2008). And the government of Sri Lanka is increasingly pinning its hopes on oil and gas discovery: In October 2005, it formed a new Ministry for Petroleum Resources Development to invite bids for oil and gas exploration (Bacon & Kojima, 2006). Continuation of its efforts, Sri Lanka has given one of eight blocks to explore for oil in Mannar to India and another to China (Tamil Net, 2007). A number of oil-producing countries also have been simplifying their procedures and dismantling national monopolies in order to encourage greater private investment, including foreign investment. Indonesia, for example, has been limiting the control over oil sector development that was previously the preserve of Pertamina, the state- owned oil company. Pakistan has executed production sharing agreements with exploration companies based in Austria France, and Malaysia. Increasing refining capacity -Another important way of enhancing supplies of petroleum products is to increase the capacity of refineries, as has been happening in China, India, Malaysia and Singapore.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ae7d37e1-6225-4886-b0c1-d37a2b521d2e": {"__data__": {"id_": "ae7d37e1-6225-4886-b0c1-d37a2b521d2e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2d99982bc3bfc217b45d3c54eadf9dcc77094d64d0628c9da25831aa36af8af9"}}, "hash": "2d99982bc3bfc217b45d3c54eadf9dcc77094d64d0628c9da25831aa36af8af9", "text": "But it also is important to ensure that new refineries can process heavy sour crude, which are cheaper and more readily available, while meeting the demand for lighter products such as transportation fuels, and accommodating environmental requirements. China has been upgrading its refineries for processing heavier sour crude. And in India Reliance Petroleum is in the process of establishing a new 29-million-tonne refinery, capable of processing the heaviest and sourest of crude oils from the Middle East into high- quality refined products, primarily for export. Amongst Pacific Island countries these options are however only available to PNG (and Timor Leste) being the only countries with substantial proven oil reserves. Diversifying sources of oil - Some economies in the regions that have sufficient demand can widen their range of supply sources, in two main ways: 81 Invest in foreign oil fields: India and China, mostly through state-owned companies, already have been investing in oil extraction in other countries. The China National Petroleum Corporation, for example, has invested in a number of countries, including Kazakhstan and Myanmar (World Bank 2006). India has invested through ONGC Videsh Ltd. an additional US$ 400 million in an existing facility in Venezuela to increase the capacity from 20,000 barrels/day to 60,000 barrels/day (Conapri, 2008). Diversify import sources: One way of reducing vulnerability to oil supply disruptions is to diversify sources of imports. For crude supplies, most Asian countries will continue to depend largely on the Middle East, which is geographically the closest, but they also could diversify to some extent to Russia, Central Asia and Africa. This would reduce risks and also increase competition (APERC 2003). For example China\u2019s sources of oil imports have gradually extended to regions other than the Middle East, such as Africa, Central Asia, Russia and Latin America. According to customs statistics, in the first half of 2006 China imported 73.33 million tonnes of crude oil, up 15.6% from a year ago, while its imports from Africa grew 22% to reach 23.4 million tonnes (Asia Times, 2007). Maintaining oil price stability also will depend on regional and international cooperation among consuming countries as well as on continuing dialogues between producers and consumers. Some importing countries have, for example, started negotiating price discounts or concessionary financing terms with oil producers. Thus, Bangladesh in March 2006 made an agreement with Kuwait and UAE to buy oil on concessionary terms. India has mooted the idea of limiting price volatility through an agreement between producers and consumers on a price band mechanism. Restraining oil demand Restraining in this context does not mean cutting demand at the cost of economic or social activity, but rather, minimizing wastage and concentrating the use of oil on purposes for which cheaper alternatives are not available. This has the further merit of reducing costs for businesses and households while slowing the depletion of conventional oil resources and reducing the impact on the climate. Asia-Pacific countries have been putting efforts in improving energy efficiency. China has been leading the way: Between 1990 and 2003, energy use per USD PPP GDP declined from 0.49 to 0.22 kilogrammes of oil equivalent (kgoe) (World Bank 2006). India too has achieved a reduction over the same period, from 0.25 to 0.18, and Sri Lanka from 0.14 to 0.11 kgoe. Their changes may be smaller than China\u2019s but are still impressive since these countries started from higher levels of efficiency. Many other countries in the region have begun stressing energy efficiency and energy conservation. Indonesia, for example, has developed a Blueprint for Energy Management, while the Philippines has adopted an Energy Plan to curtail the intensity of fossil fuel consumption and help achieve energy independence. China and India also have enacted laws to conserve energy and have established accompanying implementation mechanisms. Studies in Marshall Islands and other small Pacific states have suggested that substantial savings can be made through energy efficiency measures both in generation and consumption. The evidences from the region show that countries have adopted various measures across different sectors to restrain the demand for oil. The government of Philippines, for example, has halted the purchase of new vehicles, optimized office air conditioning, and reduced official trips. Some of the efficiency improvement measures require major and potentially disruptive technological adaptations. To cushion the immediate impact on economic activity, 82 these could be introduced in a phased manner. China, for example, is implementing fuel efficiency norms for passenger cars in two phases: Phase I was implemented in 2005/ 06, while Phase II will be implemented in 2008/09. Many countries have been diversifying away from industries that are energy-intensive. When it comes to energy-intensive products,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "900e914e-f98b-4975-b9db-970ee2ece9c1": {"__data__": {"id_": "900e914e-f98b-4975-b9db-970ee2ece9c1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4dfa694be1abc3a400022209f7ce8fc63e887f85c7d1dce6b1ca17380d867267"}, "3": {"node_id": "da083247-9bf1-4354-9c94-4d61a24f1e71", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0070417431a3d46e881d14b1574d7e9f165f426631ded05d60d69a287ec6a19e"}}, "hash": "9877ccbba92607d0bfa27c16102e68f3c759881ca736ca9fae94ba9f6a5b6fa8", "text": "they have been aiming to use a higher proportion of recycled materials. They also have been taking measures to improve energy efficiency elsewhere while shifting from oil to other energy sources, particularly those like Lao PDR and Bhutan, which have considerable hydroelectric potential. Some countries also have been trying to change consumption patterns, for example, through education campaigns that aim to reduce peak electricity demand. In Viet Nam in 2005 and 2006, government agencies were asked to reduce fuel purchase expenditures by 10 % (ESMAP 2006). Few are providing tax incentives and publicity campaigns to promote the purchase of energy-efficient appliances or imposing a ban on the import and marketing of inefficient appliances (Bacon & Kojima, 2006). Even within agriculture sector, there are attempts to discontinue the old inefficient practices. In the 1980s, Bangladesh imported from China many cheap but inefficient diesel irrigation pump sets, but following rural electrification has encouraged farmers to switch to electric pump sets. With respect to households, many countries of the region have implemented programmes to improve energy efficiency in the households through efficient lighting systems, solar water heating systems, etc. China and India are at the forefront in building millions of biogas plants with an objective of providing access to modern energy for cooking. Diversifying fuels Given that energy demands will continue to rise, particularly in developing countries, restraining demand for oil will have to be accompanied by efforts to switch from oil to alternative sources, including hydro, coal, natural gas and renewable energy. Natural gas and coal: One of the most readily available options is natural gas. Between 2002 and 2030, the natural gas consumption in developing Asia is expected to more than triple, from about 208 to 672 billion cubic metres (IEA 2004). Asian countries are adopting natural gas combined cycle (NGCC) power generation systems. These have low levels of pollutant emissions and high efficiencies: advanced NGCCs incorporating air or steam-cooled gas turbine blades and compressor inter-cooling are able to provide efficiencies beyond 55%. Another area in which natural gas will find wide application is the combined generation of heat and power, or \u2018cogeneration\u2019 in countries like Malaysia and Thailand. For power generation many countries are also making greater use of coal. Compared with other fossil fuels, however, coal presents significant environmental challenges. Technologies that are being explored include supercritical pulverized fuel technology, atmospheric fluidized bed combustion, pressurised fluidized bed combustion, integrated gasification combined cycle (IGCC) and hybrid combined cycle systems. The Indian government has recently approved captive mining for production of gas through coal gasification and liquefaction. The underground coal gasification programme is aimed at the extraction of energy from coal seams that cannot otherwise be mined through conventional methods. Renewable sources of energy: Renewable energy technologies currently supply 13% of the world\u2019s primary energy supply but up to 32% for Asia. Thanks to the increased use of renewables such as hydropower, wind, solar, biomass and geothermal, the share of 83 renewables in developing Asia should rise if their generation costs become competitive with conventional fossil fuel resources. The rapid pace of technological change also is creating opportunities for a broader range of small-scale and low-cost energy supply options that are affordable for the poorest, both for off-grid and utility-connected applications. The challenge lies, however, in using these resources for productive and income-generating activities, so that the poor can pay for these modern energy services that are essential for improving their quality of life. The recent nuclear pact between US and India is another example of diversification away from crude oil. The following sections highlight the types of fuel diversification activities initiated in the region. Transport: As one of the largest consumers of petroleum products, this sector is unlikely to move away from oil very quickly, but has the most potential to conserve oil usage and there have been a number of developments in this field. Proposal to develop electricity-driven mass transit systems and plans to switch to alternative-fuel automobiles, using LPG or CNG, ethanol or biodiesel blending, hybrid-electric, and hydrogen fuel from wind power. The focus of India\u2019s biofuel programme, for example, is diesel produced from oil-bearing seeds of several non-edible plants, including Jatropha curcas, and blended with high-speed diesel. Several other countries in the region, including Malaysia, Philippines and Thailand, have adopted targets \u2013 some mandatory \u2013 to increase the contribution of biofuels to their transport fuel supplies.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "da083247-9bf1-4354-9c94-4d61a24f1e71": {"__data__": {"id_": "da083247-9bf1-4354-9c94-4d61a24f1e71", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4dfa694be1abc3a400022209f7ce8fc63e887f85c7d1dce6b1ca17380d867267"}, "2": {"node_id": "900e914e-f98b-4975-b9db-970ee2ece9c1", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9877ccbba92607d0bfa27c16102e68f3c759881ca736ca9fae94ba9f6a5b6fa8"}}, "hash": "0070417431a3d46e881d14b1574d7e9f165f426631ded05d60d69a287ec6a19e", "text": "Many Pacific Island Countries also see biofuels as an opportunity to revive and expand copra production for coconut oil as a fuel supplement, giving increased income to copra producers. Vehicles using a coconut-oil/diesel mix are now common in Vanuatu", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "31ee457f-7130-4848-9f0d-361a272e4942": {"__data__": {"id_": "31ee457f-7130-4848-9f0d-361a272e4942", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0f70e45a4437dbb21e1264c0147e182eb16f03a7a370f67455652cecff104c27"}}, "hash": "0f70e45a4437dbb21e1264c0147e182eb16f03a7a370f67455652cecff104c27", "text": "and Micronesia and a pilot project is currently under investigation in Marshal Islands. India has fixed a target of achieving 20% blending of biofuels with petroleum products for transport by 2017. Similarly, China has fixed a target of biofuel share of 15% of transport energy by 2020. Industry: Fuel substitution options in the industrial sector include the replacement of petroleum chemical feedstock by biomaterials and the promotion of alternative fuels. An example of the former is the shift away from oil in the fertilizer sector, as in India, where as feedstock there is a clear move away from naphtha to natural gas. In China, a similar shift is taking place, substituting oil with coal. Other options include promoting the conversion of existing oil-fired plants to other fuels or multi-fuel firing, and exploring alternatives like biomass gasification or biogas power generation for decentralized power supply. For example, following the oil price hikes during 2005-06, several industries in Thailand switched from oil to coal, biomass or agro-industrial residues. The change is, however, likely to be gradual because of the need, for most applications, to invest in new capital equipment. Agriculture: Farmers who use petroleum products in agricultural machinery for irrigation and in threshing can in some cases switch to electricity made available through accelerated rural electrification programmes. Other options for fuel substitution included biomass liquid fuel for tractors and diesel pumps along with the use of hybrid systems such as solar photovoltaic- powered water pumps, with diesel as a backup. Households: With growing rural electrification, it is important to reduce the use of petroleum products in power generation. One option, for both grid and off-grid systems is to switch to renewable sources. China and India, which have large coal reserves, also would benefit from making more use of clean-coal technologies. Several countries are also considering expanding their nuclear power capacity, as witnessed by the recent US-India agreement and signs of ASEAN reconsidering its decades-old stance as a nuclear-free zone. 84 A good solution for some rural areas in less developed countries is the development of renewable energy through community initiatives. Examples include rural electrification projects based on usage of solar energy in China, biomass gasification in Cambodia, and micro-hydropower in India, Nepal, China and now Indonesia. The community-based development of rural energy systems in Nepal has been an effective model, operating within the government\u2019s decentralized structure through village and district development committees ensuring energy access for both consumption and productive uses. Many remote Pacific communities have experimented with PV systems. Attention is now also moving towards micro-hydro schemes, particularly in some parts of Melanesia. The pacific Plan, a blue-print for regional cooperation has renewable energy development as a high priority for all Pacific Island states. Preparing for emergencies Each country also needs to prepare for abrupt disruptions in oil supplies. This should involve measures to build strategic reserves as well as plans to make rapid and drastic cuts in oil consumption through rationing systems. Building strategic reserves Both governments and private companies are keeping stockpiles of crude oil and oil products separate from operational ones, though at high cost. For India, the cost of building storage to stock 15 million tonnes of crude oil was estimated in 2004 at USD 950 million (UNCTAD 2006). Several Asia-Pacific countries have begun to develop strategic oil reserves. Japan has 171 days of consumption reserve, which would correspond to nearly 980 million barrels. India has begun to develop a strategic crude oil reserve expected to be pegged at 40 million barrels. The Republic of Korea has a reported reserve of 43 million barrels. Among ASEAN countries, Thailand recently increased the size of its strategic reserve from 60 to 70 days of consumption. Singapore has an estimated storage capacity of 32 million barrels of crude oil and 65 million barrels of oil products. By 2008, China plans to have an 800- million-barrel strategic reserve stored at four facilities (Sakhuja, 2005). In 2007 China announced an expansion of their crude reserves into a two part system; consisting of a government- controlled strategic reserve of 101.9 million barrels complemented by mandated commercial reserves of 209.44 million barrels. An example of a multi-country strategic reserve within the framework of regional cooperation is the 1986 ASEAN Petroleum Security Agreement (APSA). This established an ASEAN Emergency Petroleum Sharing Scheme. In cases of critical shortage, where total supply falls below 80% of normal domestic consumption the oil-exporting members of ASEAN would provide emergency oil supplies. In times of broader crises affecting more than one ASEAN member state, the agreement calls for the distribution to be allocated initially in proportion to their", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "19306546-b6ab-408c-ac8a-cb7b92ce9d96": {"__data__": {"id_": "19306546-b6ab-408c-ac8a-cb7b92ce9d96", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f9ad1252234422f95450ec842e5271e144c6caafd750a4e4882a756e1f70cc62"}}, "hash": "f9ad1252234422f95450ec842e5271e144c6caafd750a4e4882a756e1f70cc62", "text": "respective normal domestic consumption and to exports for the 12-month period prior to the crisis. APSA has never actually been executed, although it nearly was in the early 1990s during the Gulf War (Giragosian 2004). Rationing to ensure essential supplies Other methods adopted to restrain demand under emergencies are rationing and fixing quotas. Following the oil price shocks in the 1970s and 1980s, a number of countries like Bangladesh, India, Sri Lanka and Viet Nam introduced such measures as fuel rationing, fuel stamps and lifeline tariffs. Indeed, in India some of these measures like kerosene rationing and quotas at subsidized prices are still in place. For example, the Bantuan Langsung Tunai program was Indonesia\u2019s first cash transfer program and it reached about a third of 85 households, giving a flat rate benefit of about 15 % of the poverty line, more than enough to compensate the poor for higher fuel prices. In India, kerosene supply is rationed and distributed through public distribution system. The quota per family and prices vary across states. For example, in the state of Kerala, two litres of kerosene per month for electrified houses and five litres per month for non-electrified houses for lighting purposes are provided. Apart from this, for cooking kerosene is provided at the rate of six litres per month per household. The present consumer price of Kerosene is Rs. 9.50 per litre. 7. Findings, Recommendations and UNDP role Trends in Commodity Prices The recent commodity price crisis has been notable for both its broad nature (covering not just grain and oil, but metals, and most other food products) and its long duration. However although recent commodity price rises are higher in nominal terms than previous price spikes, in real terms they are mostly much smaller than, for example, price rises in the 1970s, and indeed prices remain low in real terms compared with the 1980s and 1990s. In terms of staple food grains, real prices have been on a downward trajectory since the 1970s, reaching a low in 2000. The recent rise in their prices has been dramatic, but in real terms food is still cheap compared with the 1970s. By contrast crude oil prices in 2008 sky rocketed in mid- 2008 \u2013 by 222% in real and 257% in nominal terms from the seventies to a record high of $145 in June 2008. However the recent return of crude oil to around $70 per barrel in late 2008 demonstrates\u2026 Whilst the recent price rise is of concern, particularly for poor consumers in the Asia Pacific region, an even more disturbing trend is the level of volatility in commodity prices, which has dramatically increased since the 1990s. This volatility presents specific additional challenges to the region\u2019s poor, as it makes it difficult for farmers to interpret demand signals through price transmission. Underlying causes of the food and fuel price rises Although rapid urbanization and changes in dietary preferences towards greater meat consumption in major developing economies in Asia (notably China and India) has been cited [ref] as a major cause of food price rises, this is not supported by the evidence. Over Asia as a whole, increase in meat consumption is slowing, as is growth in consumption of maize (the staple crop most diverted into animal feed use). In fact, staple grain use for meat consumption remains low, with most livestock being fed on crop by-products, household waste and open grazing. Asia\u2019s growth in cereal consumption for food is also decelerating. Overall, our analysis finds that China and India\u2019s consumption patterns are not a major driver of the food price increase because (1) their demand for food is increasing at a much slower rate than the rest of the world; and (2) they meet their slowly rising consumption demand primarily through domestic production rather than imports. However our research indicates that biofuels, another widely cited driver for food grain price increases, are indeed responsible for a considerable proportion of price increases. Global wheat and maize stocks would not have declined significantly were it not for a big increase in biofuel production from grains and oilseed in the US and EU. This was seen in the diversion of maize production directly to biofuel use; limited expansion of wheat production due to land use for biofuel related oil seed production; and price transmission from wheat to rice 86 prices due to panic-driven domestic policies and speculation. The impact of biofuels was particularly severe due to rapid expansion of the sector in response to government subsidies. Increased demand driven by biofuel production and speculative activities took place in against a backdrop of stagnating", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "81721e4f-52e6-4423-8a0b-e808e0a29e43": {"__data__": {"id_": "81721e4f-52e6-4423-8a0b-e808e0a29e43", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "af1dca9446b78c45ffe5140819d06d48bf17057f27bbf5221e692242a7f15f00"}}, "hash": "af1dca9446b78c45ffe5140819d06d48bf17057f27bbf5221e692242a7f15f00", "text": "productivity increases at a global level. Asian economies accounted for two-thirds of the developing world\u2019s agricultural growth over the past 25 years. However this growth has decelerated rapidly \u2013 from 2.7% pa during 1981-1995 to 1.3% pa 1996-2008. This is due to the fact that very little new land is available for agricultural land, and that investment in agriculture has declined dramatically, limiting the potential for increased yields. Agricultural spending as a percentage of total government spending in the Asia Pacific region decreased from 14.8% in 1980 to 8.6% in 2002. This was largely driven by the prioritization of social sector spending within poverty reduction strategies; promotion of industrial and service sectors at the expense of agriculture; and persistent low prices for agricultural products at the end of the twentieth century. These deep rooted supply-side issues were exacerbated by weather related production shocks in major exporting countries such as Australia and Canada. Declining acceleration in the rise in demand (before the biofuel boom) and production, combined in some instances with deliberate policies to minimize opportunity loss, led to a gradual reduction in food grain stocks since 2000, which made it harder for countries and regions to adjust to shocks, setting the stage for the rapid price hikes seen in 2007 and 2008. Beyond market fundamentals, the food price rise was also driven, especially in the case of rice, by the spread of panic in major rice exporting and importing countries. This led to short term policy actions in some countries, such as export bans or taxes, which aimed to protect domestic consumers. However these measures made the situation worse, by further tightening an already thin international rice market, which caused further price volatility. Additionally, most commodities, including food grains and crude oil, are priced in US dollars. Therefore, when the dollar falls, as it has over the past six years, it translates into rising world commodity prices. The FAO forecasts that world cereal production in 2008 will reach a record 2180 million tons, 2.8% up from last year, as producers respond to the price rise. This should have a dampening effect on food price inflation. However food prices are likely to remain relatively high compared with the 1980s and 1990s, due to continuing high input costs and demand for biofuels (though the recent decline in the oil price will dampen these effects to some extent) and due to countries scambling to replenish stocks to safer levels. In the case of oil, both structural factors and speculation have played a role in driving up the oil price so dramatically. Rapidly increasing demand, particularly from the US and major Asian economies such as China, is the main structural driver, but there are supply side constraints too. Surplus production and refining capacity are shrinking, and decades of under-investment have meant that oil extraction is becoming increasingly difficult and costly. Moreover geo-political turbulence in the Middle East, Bolivia and Venezuela has also contributed to the price rise. However, oil supply-demand imbalances and uncertainties have been exacerbated by a massive influx of speculative money into the market for crude oil futures. Estimates on the effect of speculative activity on the oil price range from 20% to over 60% (ref). 87 Impact of soaring food and oil prices at the macro level The impact of rising commodity prices clearly depends on whether countries are net exporters of importers of affected commodities, as well as the relative share of net food and oil exports in total imports, total domestic consumption and total domestic production. In Asia and the Pacific, 26 out of 35 countries are net food importers. Of these, 9 (PNG, Sri Lanka, Fiji, Solomon Islands, Mongolia, Indonesia, Malaysia, Tonga and Lao PDR) have an overall trade surplus in agricultural products. The negative effects of soaring food prices could therefore be balanced out by the sales of agricultural raw materials. Prices of these vary by product, but some, e.g. rubber, are particularly buoyant. Other food importers are major non-food commodity exporters (Indonesia, Iran, Lao PDR, Malaysia, Mongolia), or industrial countries (South Korea, Singapore) who will also derive some degree of insulation from food price increases. However 8 of the 26 (Kiribati, North Korea, Micronesia, Cook Islands, Samoa, Bangladesh, PNG, Nauru and Palau) might be considered as being especially vulnerable to food price rises, as net food imports are more than 5% of their total imports. PNG also has net food imports of greater than 5% of total imports, but as mentioned above their huge agricultural surplus renders them less vulnerable. Most of the vulnerable net food importing states in the region are small island", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5a1b5ec1-d5a8-4590-8d2c-0c707cf56090": {"__data__": {"id_": "5a1b5ec1-d5a8-4590-8d2c-0c707cf56090", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "29446d27148649f525500dbf58220a61bd760e0605f026ab99905aacb0c787ca"}}, "hash": "29446d27148649f525500dbf58220a61bd760e0605f026ab99905aacb0c787ca", "text": "states, or countries in conflict (Sri Lanka, Afghanistan, Nepal). Exceptions are Bangladesh, Bhutan, and North Korea, all of whom are likely to suffer from the price rise. Nine countries in the region (Myanmar, Tuvalu, Thailand, Pakistan, Vietnam, India, China, Vanuatu, Philippines) are net food exporters, who might therefore be expected to benefit from rising prices, However only Myanmar, Tuvalu and Thailand have high net food exports in terms of their total import bill. For the others, benefits are likely to be small, and therefore overall the price rise may be damaging (because of the impact on poor consumers). Moreover only Myanmar, Thailand, Vietnam and India have a trade surplus in both food and total agricultural products. Overall, the oil price increase is expected to have an average negative impact of 5-6% on the GNI of Asia Pacific countries (ADB 2008). But the effects again vary by country. Iran, China, India, Indonesia, Malaysia, Vietnam, Brunei Darussalam, Thailand, PNG and Timor Leste all produce oil, but only a few of these are net oil exporters. Timor Leste and PNG in particular are likely to see big benefits from the increase in the oil price: ADB (2008) predicts that price increases for PNG exports will add 45 % to GNI above 2006 levels. Mongolia and PNG will also benefit from rising gold and copper prices. Terms of trade and income distribution Dramatic changes in commodity prices will affect income distribution between countries. At a regional level, according to available data, Eastern, South Eastern and Southern Asian countries will experience a significant deterioration in their terms of trade, owing to their dependence on the import of energy and industrial raw materials, and their specialization in labour-intensive manufactures exports. Within the region, exporters of manufactures suffered losses from changes in their terms of trade equivalent to 1.2% of GDP 2004-6. However exporters of oil and minerals improved their terms of trade by between 5 and 7% of GDP annually. 88 The deterioration in the terms of trade for many Asian countries has already begun to affect exchange rates in India, Pakistan and Nepal. There has also been some impact on the current account balance of net commodity importers. However, despite a slowing US economy, overall Asian and Pacific exports have remained resilient and capital is still flowing into the region, so external positions have not moved into dangerous levels. Pass through of world food and fuel prices to domestic consumer prices Rising global food prices are contributing to high inflation in many Asia Pacific countries. However, the impact varies according to the extent to which global prices have been transmitted to domestic prices. Overall, only about half of the increase in real US dollar prices have been passed through to domestic prices in the region. This is partly because of exchange rate movement of Asian currencies against the US dollar, which has cushioned domestic consumers to some extent. Countries have also varied in their willingness to pass through price increases to consumers, and their ability to control pass through (i.e. reliance on imported food, and budgetary headspace to subsidise food prices). The highest pass-through ratios are observed for Mongolia, Sri Lanka, China, Maldives and Indonesia, with Mongolia having a pass through of 97%. Although 2008 data on Mayanmar, Vietnam, Lao PDR, Cambodia and Afghanistan are not yet available, pass-through rates and food price inflation is also likely to be high in these countries. By contrast, South Korea, Singapore, Malaysia and India have experienced low pass-through rates \u2013 just 15% in South Korea, for example. Pass through rates, and food price inflation, have also been low in most Pacific countries. In terms of oil, pass through rates have been higher for diesel than for gasoline, with rates for the former ranging from 85% in Malaysia, to 30% in India. The effects of domestic fuel price inflation have been particularly marked in Afghanistan (216%), Indonesia (180%) and Malaysia (177%). Pass through rates for oil prices have been increasing in most countries over the past two years as the cost of protecting customers from oil price increases has become unsustainable. Impact on domestic inflation In many countries, food and fuel price inflation is higher than aggregate inflation and is contributing to underlying inflationary pressures. Higher food prices are particularly significant for developing countries as food expenditure accounts for a significant share of their consumer price index. Many Asia Pacific economies now suffer double-digit inflation rates. The rises in food prices have contributed about 2-3% to headline inflation. However, in some countries, domestic demand pressures have pushed up inflation further. At a regional level, the recent oil", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a9026f8f-f856-4101-b188-f77364ce9ef1": {"__data__": {"id_": "a9026f8f-f856-4101-b188-f77364ce9ef1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "bd53055ffbecdea9f741656de09a2063aa6d1cb50f248ddc12c92b51c94bea0c"}}, "hash": "bd53055ffbecdea9f741656de09a2063aa6d1cb50f248ddc12c92b51c94bea0c", "text": "price spike has had less impact on inflation, though oil price increases over the past few years has been a significant driver of increasing inflation. Overall, higher food and oil prices are likely to continue to drive up inflation over 2008, which will mean that inflation will emerge as one of the beiggest risks to the regional outlook. Inflation expectations have also risen markedly, and there is a danger that recent commodity price rises could trigger and inflationary spiral based on second round effects such as wage increases. Rapid liquidity growth in the region over the past few years is also an important underlying driver of inflation. Governments need to act now to combat inflationary pressures, notably by increasing agricultural production. Impact on GDP growth One of the greatest concerns about the commodity price spike is that it may stifle economic growth by raising the cost of production; and by contributing to inflation and hence reducing 89 the incentive to consume and invest. Attempts by countries to contain inflation through tight monetary policies could also stifle economic growth. However, so far the effect on growth has been limited, partly due to the cushioning effect of local currency appreciation against the dollar. Economic growth across the region did slow down in 2008 against 2007 levels. High growth economies such as China, India and Vietnam witnessed stronger moderation. The ADB (2008) forecasts that growth in East Asia will decelerate from 9.6% in 2007 to 7.7% in 2008, from 8.6% in 2007 to 7.1% in South Asia over the same period, and from 6.5% to 5.4% in South East Asia. However growth in the Pacific is forecast to double in 2008, mainly due to growth in its largest economy, PNG (mostly on the back of rising commodity prices). However recent slowdowns in the US economy could mean that growth rates fall further. Impact on domestic exports, imports and current account balance The sharp increases in food and fuel prices have led to higher import bills and strained the balance of payments position of many countries. Asia and the Pacific region as a net importer of fuel and food is likely to face an increase in its imports bill (which could be by as much as 1-2% of GDP). Meanwhile, the growth of other exports (and indeed imports) is slowing, particularly in the light of the global economic slowdown. The increase in the total imports bill could widen the regional current account deficit as a share of GDP by more than 1-2%. Countries have existing high current account deficits will be particularly vulnerable. Cambodia, Lao PDR, Maldives, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Vietnam and the Pacific Islands (except PNG) all have large trade deficits (above 4% of GDP) and those which import significant quantities of food and fuels could experience severe balance of payment problems. Impact on government revenue, expenditure, fiscal balance and monetary indicators With regards to government budgets, all of the domestic measures to cushion the burden of rising prices have a fiscal cost \u2013 either lower revenues from reduced taxes and tariffs, or higher expenditure on subsidies and social safety nets or support measure for small farmers. Countries which have resisted full pass through of international prices to domestic consumers are likely to experience significant fiscal costs which could reduce fiscal space and hence fiscal performance. The total fiscal cost of policy responses to food and fuel prices has been high (more than 2% of GDP) in Indonesia, Maldives, Bangladesh and Timor Leste, and more than 1% of GDP in Malaysia, India and Cambodia. Countries with existing high fiscal deficits \u2013 notably Sri Lanka, Pakistan, India and Bangladesh \u2013 will face particular challenges in allocating scarce resources. Available data from 2008 suggests that fiscal deficit indicators have generally worsened from 2007. Aggregate spending on social and other services has risen because of the cost of the fiscal response to the price increases, and second round inflationary effects such as higher prices are likely to create further fiscal pressure. It is therefore important that any new social safety net measures introduced by governments in the region are effectively targeted, to avoid creating further fiscal pressure. Equity, currency and financial markets As discussed above, the impact of rising world food prices on domestic economies is dependent partially on the exchange rate between local currencies and the dollarReal exchange rate appreciation against the US dollar, to the extent that it occurs, will neutralize some of the impact of increased world prices in dollar terms. . In the first half of 2008, trends in Asian currency markets were mixed. The Indian rupee, Philippino peso, Korean", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "61215ae1-c5c4-44b5-9f04-75b21532c211": {"__data__": {"id_": "61215ae1-c5c4-44b5-9f04-75b21532c211", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e8dd4f18d6ee72e2e51e8e1601f1ac5b63c64a69931ad3bd16816e78d1c49465"}}, "hash": "e8dd4f18d6ee72e2e51e8e1601f1ac5b63c64a69931ad3bd16816e78d1c49465", "text": "won and 90 Thai baht depreciated against the US dollar. But the Chinese reminbi, Indonesian rupiah, Malaysian ringgit and Singapore dollar stabilized or strengthened. Equity markets in many Asian economies are expected to weaken in 2008 partly due to the financial crisis in the US sub-prime markets, and partly due to lower growth expectations. In late 2008, regional stock markets continued to trend downward from their record highs of October 2007, as the global market turmoil worsened and equity markets in industrialized countries fell sharply. Food and fuel security The recent food and fuel price crisis has placed renewed attention on the issue of food and fuel security. Attainment of such security is a priority of the Asia Pacific region, due to the fact that most countries in the region are net importers of food and oil. Some countries, such as Korea, Nepal, Philippines and Sri Lanka, which depend on imported oil for nearly 100% of their consumption, need to be especially concerned about future price fluctuations. However, from a macro perspective, food and fuel security at a regional level does not appear to have been excessively threatened. This is evident from the improved positions of most Asia Pacific countries in terms of the ratio of foreign exchange reserves to imports. When we compare the average ratio of forex reserves for 2004-7, against 2000-3, most countries \u2013 with the exception of Indonesia, Pakistan and Thailand are in a stronger position to face external shocks. Instead, the greater cause for concern is the impact of the price rises at a household level. Increased poverty The World Bank (2008) estimates that food inflation could push at least 100 million people into poverty. In percentage terms, this is in the range of 3-5% of global poverty rates. This could mean \u2018seven lost years\u2019 in the fight against worldwide poverty. In East Asia and the Pacific, poverty was expected to decline from 17.9% in 2005 to 11.7% in 2009 if the growth rate of the last few years is maintained. In South Asia, poverty was expected to reduce from 40.3% to 37.2% over the same period. However, data suggests that growth will decelerate buy about 1-2% in 2008 and 2009. This would suggest that poverty rates will be at least 1% higher across the region than previous projections. Increased malnutrition Malnutrition and hunger is not a new consequence of high good prices \u2013 over 500 million people in the region lived in hunger even before prices began to rise. But, unsurprisingly, the price rise is adding to the number of hungry people. Across Asia, households are reducing their food consumption, or reducing the consumption of other essential items (such as education or health care) to enable them to continue their previous levels of food spending. According to the World Bank (2008) the number of malnourished people globally will increase by 44 million due the crisis FAO estimates are even higher. The largest increases in the number of undernourished people as a result of the food price crisis live in Asia. FAO predict that 41 million people in Asia and 24 million in sub-Saharan Africa will fall below the hunger threshold due to the crisis. Impact of soaring food and oil prices at the household level For households in low income countries, who spend up to 60-70% of their incomes on food, higher prices can have devastating effects. Nevertheless, 75% of the world\u2019s poor live in rural areas, and the vast majority of these are engaged in agriculture. In this regard, one might expect rising food prices to benefit much of Asia\u2019s poor \u2013 specifically, small farmers. 91 In reality, however, the smallholder population is quite diverse. Whether a particular smallholder household will gain or lose from higher food prices depends on its net position on food markets \u2013 as a seller or buyer \u2013 the net effect between rising value of sales and rising input costs (especially of petroleum products and derivatives, such as fertilizer) , changes in rural wages, the cost of purchased consumer goods. Impacts depend on access to land, educational levels, gender, ethnicity, and access to rural non-farm employment opportunities. Even at a country level, detailed mapping of who is gaining or losing is important for designing any social safety nets to protect the most vulnerable. Because the effects of the crisis has not yet been reflected in household poverty and human development statistics, its impact is hard to analyse or quantify, but the effect on the poor will clearly depend primarily on whether they are net buyers or sellers of food. A recent world bank paper (ref) suggests", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a9bb35b8-4b4f-4e69-a7d5-dad8816ca808": {"__data__": {"id_": "a9bb35b8-4b4f-4e69-a7d5-dad8816ca808", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "054cb7880727efa4f2f5c27aff51e465ac5f3f658a688c828af5dd68130a9bd4"}}, "hash": "054cb7880727efa4f2f5c27aff51e465ac5f3f658a688c828af5dd68130a9bd4", "text": "that only 6% of urban households, 32% of rural households, and 23% of all households were net food sellers. But the distribution of net food buyers and sellers clearly differs from country to country. Within Asia Pacific, the highest shares of net sellers are observed in Cambodia and Vietnam, suggesting that farmers in these countries are better placed to benefit from an increase in food prices. Given that only a small share of most countries\u2019 households are net sellers, a related question is whether net seller households are predominantly rich or poor. The general presumption has been that net food sellers tend to be relatively wealthy households with larger farms. In fact, on average, at a national level, about 27% of poor householders and 13% of rich households are net food sellers. Therefore, in most countries, a higher proportion of poor households are net food sellers compared to the proportion of richer households. Higher food prices should therefore result in some income transfer from richer to poorer households, whilst low prices should do the opposite. However, the majority of poor householders are net food sellers and will therefore suffer from the effects of rising prices. Additionally, small scale farmers (over-represented amongst the poor) are less likely to be able to gain full benefits from higher prices than larger and medium sized farmers, particularly in middle income countries. This is partly because of price transmission mechanisms \u2013 since most small holders sell food locally, and many Asian governments have limited the pass through of the price increase to domestic markets \u2013 they may not see significantly higher prices for their produce. Moreover, they may be unable to respond to pricing signals by producing more food, because of lack of access to land or to credit to buy fertilizers and other inputs (often bought at high prices from state monopolies). Even within wealthier economies, structural barriers to rural development may keep these gains from being widely shared among rural communities. Better rural infrastructure is therefore needed to ensure that the rents accruing from higher prices are reinvested in rural areas, to boost agricultural productivity and real incomes. More developed transport, irrigation and financial infrastructure in rural areas would increase yields and farm incomes, help small farmers get their produce to market, and increase the demand for agricultural labour. Urban households have benefited disproportionately from the region\u2019s rapid economic progress. However, soaring food prices are expected to hit urban households (and especially the urban poor) harder than the rural population. Unlike the rural poor, virtually all poor urban householders are net food purchasers. 92 In the case of fuel, the impact of rising oil prices at a household level depends on the extent of kerosene, gas and electricity use. Available data show that households in the region spend only 3-8% of their budget on household fuel use, and 5-8% on transport. Fuel consumption patterns also display a clear rural-urban divide in developing countries. For instance, in India, only 8% of rural households, compared to 66% of urban households, use some form of oil product as their primary cooking fuel, preferring instead biomass. This suggests that (i) oil price rises would not significantly affect consumption expenditure of rural households on cooking fuel; (ii) subsidies on oil products are inherently biased toward urban households; and (iii) the existence of such subsidies for many years has failed to shift rural fuel consumption patterns away from biomass. Nevertheless, rising fuel prices will impact on the rural poor through rising prices for kerosene, which is widely used for lighting. Moreover higher prices will set back attempts to improve the livelihood of the poor through increased consumption of fuels and electricity, which could make issues such as food storage safer and more practicable, and enable working after darkness falls. Finally, the poor are likely to be impacted in terms of increasing public transport costs, and indirectly through general inflation. Scenario analysis Section 5 of the paper investigated the effects of the food and fuel price crisis through a simple scenario analysis which used the variables which determine a household\u2019s vulnerability. First, a baseline scenario was assumed, with given levels of: 1. household income; 2. household expenditure; 3. spend on food as a share of total expenditure 4. spend on cereal as a share of total food expenditure. These four variables allow for the estimation of the ratio of total consumption to income; total food expenditure; ratio of food expenditure to total income; and total expenditure on cereal and non-cereal foods across the different expenditure quintiles. Then, the actual rise in international cereal prices (116%) and the pass-through", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "be67e6a7-4445-404a-b0aa-7f874cc16ef4": {"__data__": {"id_": "be67e6a7-4445-404a-b0aa-7f874cc16ef4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0aefef0a7bb2cf9b37ecaea3df3502c61a922d55a8378a1efcd304deccf39485"}}, "hash": "0aefef0a7bb2cf9b37ecaea3df3502c61a922d55a8378a1efcd304deccf39485", "text": "co-efficients of various countries during the period 2006-8 were fed into the model. The resulting analysis showed that the international food price rise raised Asia Pacific households\u2019 food spend significantly \u2013 by an average of 43% across the region for poor households, and only 18% for rich households. Increases were particularly high for the poor of Mongolia, Philippines and Sri Lanka; and lowest in Singapore, India, Bangladesh and Cambodia. The price rise can therefore be said to have decreased poor households\u2019 purchasing power substantially \u2013 by about 24% in Asia Pacific as a whole, though only 4% for rich households. For the poor of Mongolia, purchasing power reduced by 51%. Policy responses to food and fuel price inflation Policy responses adopted by governments to address fuel and food price increases have been varied. Some of the measures implemented are more cost-effective and less distortionary than others. A number of countries may have moved to implement universal rather than targeted measures because they allow a quicker response. Monetary responses to food and fuel price inflation 93 The monetary policy stance in many countries in Asia and the Pacific has moved towards more tightening given sharply rising inflation, but at the same time it has become more cautious given the worsening global economic outlook and the increased volatility of financial markets. Available information shows that countries generally accommodated the first-round effects of higher food and fuel prices on inflation. However, in recent months, many countries have tightened their monetary policies to prevent the first-round effects of higher food and fuel prices on inflation from spilling over to higher prices of other goods and services, triggering a wage-price spiral. This is particularly important for countries where inflation has already been rising because of overly expansionary macroeconomic policies. Central banks in India, Indonesia, Pakistan, Philippines, Thailand, Taiwan (China), Vietnam have raised policy rates and/or cash reserve requirement ratios. Central Bank of China has raised the bank reserve requirement ratio, but not interest rates. Singapore has tightened policy through a stronger currency, whilst Sri Lanka has issued its own securities to contain excess liquidity. Others in the region have so far maintained their key rates, but may yet adopt monetary tightening if inflation worsens. More than half of the Pacific Island countries are constrained in their use of monetary policy as a tool of macroeconomic management due to their use of third-country currencies as their medium of exchange. In most of those that are able to use monetary instruments, their capital markets are relatively undeveloped and interest rates are not regarded as an effective tool for influencing economic behaviour. Exchange rate policy is likewise constrained. Fiscal responses to the Food and Fuel price Inflation Available information shows that many governments in Asia and the Pacific have used actively tried to minimise pass-through effects of the international price rise. The monetary tightening described above often incurs the undesirable cost of slowing growth, which can worsen the pain to consumers of higher prices, which has further encouraged countries to adopt various fiscal measures with the aim of protecting the vulnerable. These include subsidies, transfers, safety net programmes, etc. However, governments need to assess the overall fiscal cost of such programmes: even the most efficient and effective policy responses in substantial fiscal costs. Some countries are already beginning to phase out unaffordable fuel and food subsidies. The options over the medium term depend on individual countries\u2019 macroeconomic situation and their capacity to create fiscal space. Fiscal space can be created in a variety of ways, including by increasing revenue, reducing non-productive spending, raising borrowing in a non inflationary and sustainable way, and securing higher external grants or concessional loans provided by donors. One notices, in many 2008 or 2009 budgets, a very welcome increased emphasis on trying to prevent future food and fuel crises through expansionary fiscal spending on agriculture. However, other countries will find it difficult to create fiscal space and therefore need to limit the size and duration of the fiscal response and pass-through the increase in international prices to domestic consumers more rapidly. To the extent possible, this should be accompanied by strengthening and expansion of cost-effective social safety nets. Almost all Pacific Islands are heavily dependent on imported food and fuels. Taxes on imports are also a major source of government revenue, thus reductions in tariff rates to ease the burden of price rises on the poor has the impact of increasing the pressure on, often 94 already stretched, government finances. The scope for a fiscal response from Pacific governments to mitigatie rising prices and the impact on the poor is therefore", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "cd02f9dc-f3f7-49e5-a01e-2d020edf4787": {"__data__": {"id_": "cd02f9dc-f3f7-49e5-a01e-2d020edf4787", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "00fb4cf96b05ae9ea856d793db476fbe7f753b03dbe1b26e294f7386b8043c3b"}}, "hash": "00fb4cf96b05ae9ea856d793db476fbe7f753b03dbe1b26e294f7386b8043c3b", "text": "very limited. Only in Fiji has the government attempted to reduce tariffs on \u201cessential\u201d food items, including rice and cereal products, to mitigate the price increases. Trade related responses to the Food and Fuel price Inflation As food prices soared, a key component of many national policy responses has been to ensure than more domestically produced grain is consumed locally through the use of export tariffs and other trade related measures. However global food markets need to be kept open to avoid any distortion to the economy. Restrictive trade policies, have unintended negative consequences at the domestic the global level. They push up world prices even further and hurt net importers in particular. From a global perspective, maintaining free trade in commodities while fostering incentives for production and using efficient policies to protect the urban poor (e.g. targeted cash transfers) is a priority. An ambitious Doha Round conclusion, including on agriculture, can help broaden and stabilize international food trade. While this may not mean lower food prices in the short term, it will foster efficient agricultural production in the medium and long term and boost global growth. As noted earlier, reduced tariffs on imported food can alleviate food prices pressures and improve efficiency. However, many poor countries have narrow tax bases and rely on tariffs and other trade taxes for a large part of government revenue. In such countries, it is important to ensure that the revenue loss from tariff or trade tax reductions can be accommodated without destabilizing countries\u2019 macroeconomic policies. Responses to oil price shock To enhance oil supplies, a number of oil-producing countries in the region have been simplifying their procedures and dismantling national monopolies in order to encourage greater private investment, including foreign direct investment. Indonesia, for example, has been limiting the control over oil sector development that was previously the preserve of Pertamina, the state-owned oil company. Pakistan has executed production sharing agreements with exploration companies based in Austria, France, and Malaysia. Another important way of enhancing supplies of petroleum products is to increase the capacity of refineries, as has been happening in China, India, Malaysia and Singapore. The focus is on new refineries which can process heavy sour crude, which is cheaper and more readily available. There have been efforts in improving energy efficiency. For example, in the case of China between 1990 and 2003, energy use per PPP $ GDP declined from 0.49 to 0.22 kgoe. India too has achieved a reduction over the same period, from 0.25 to 0.18, and Sri Lanka from 0.14 to 0.11 kgoe. Diversifying into other fuels types like natural gas, hydro, renewable energy sources and nuclear energy can also protect economies from rising oil prices. India has fixed a target of achieving 20% blending of bio fuels with petroleum products for transport by 2017. Similarly, China has fixed a target of biofuel share of 15% of transport energy by 2020. However increased dependence on biofuel may cause further upwards pressure on food prices. The nuclear pact between US and India is another example of diversification away from crude oil. 95 Both governments and private companies are keeping stockpiles of crude oil and oil products separate from operational ones, though at high cost. India has begun to develop a strategic crude oil reserve sized at 37.4 million barrels, enough for two weeks of consumption. The Republic of Korea has a reported reserve of 43 million barrels. Thailand recently increased the size of its strategic reserve from 60 to 70 days of consumption. By 2008, In 2007 China announced an expansion of their crude reserves into a two part system; consisting of a government-controlled strategic reserve of 101.9 million barrels complemented by mandated commercial reserves of 209.44 million barrels. Key recommendations Countries need to strike a balance between helping the poor to cope with the significant increases of food and fuel prices, ensuring macroeconomic stability, and encouraging increased agricultural production. National policy interventions can be divided into three broad classes:; (ii) interventions to lower domestic food and oil prices through short-run trade policy measures or administrative action, and (iii) interventions to enhance longer-term food and oil supply. (i) interventions to ensure household food and energy security by strengthening targeted safety nets: A number of countries may have moved to implement universal rather than targeted measures because they allow a quicker response. These countries should assess the efficiency of the measures as soon as possible and replace untargeted programs with more cost-effective measures. Targeted transfer programs, preferably as part of an integrated social safety net, can reach the poor efficiently and effectively, but implementation can be challenging (see", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3a98f0f8-b9cc-4f67-9639-5afcd37b91f2": {"__data__": {"id_": "3a98f0f8-b9cc-4f67-9639-5afcd37b91f2", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "12be79ec15b438f17435b8f62f62a21ef3c257e716e0bd2dc4e2e1d36d296ea0"}}, "hash": "12be79ec15b438f17435b8f62f62a21ef3c257e716e0bd2dc4e2e1d36d296ea0", "text": "Annex ?). A growing number of countries are implementing conditional cash transfer programs\u2014but this can take time and requires planning, targeting, and delivery capacity. Expanding the coverage of other targeted measures, such as targeted food distribution or school lunch programs, can also be effective in reaching vulnerable households. Agricultural subsidy programs can help if they are carefully designed and focus on increasing the productivity of small farmers. (ii) interventions to lower domestic food and oil prices through short-run trade policy measures or administrative action. These can include: \u2022 In the short-run regulate pricing policies such that while the interests of the poor are protected \u2022 Use targeted subsidies on household basic items \u2013food (rice, wheat) and fuels (LPG, kerosene) to shield poor consumers from the full impact of the price rise \u2022 Ration subsidized food and fuels through a monthly quota (e.g. smart card scheme) \u2022 Promote the use of the Food and Oil Stabilization Fund However, most of these measures have significant fiscal implications, which need to be taken into account. (iii) interventions to enhance longer-term food and oil supply. These can include: \u2022 Invest more in rural infrastructure and agricultural R& D to improve agricultural productivity \u2022 Provide targeted agricultural input subsidies (e.g., HYV seeds, fertilizers) \u2022 Changing biofuels policy to prevent excessive diversion of staple grains or productive land to non-food uses. 96 \u2022 Promotion of staple food production rather than production of cash crops. \u2022 Include in the mandate of large oil companies investment in alternates sources of decentralised energy ,besides dedicated targets for oil exploration tied to supply targets and not only global prices \u2026for example, a part of their profits must be expended on exploration activities and provide fiscal incentives like tax rebates to oil companies to strengthen exploration activities in the long term development strategies. \u2022 Encourage the establishment of refining capacity for sour crude by introducing capital subsidies for sour crude refining facilities and duty exemptions for imported technology. \u2022 Diversify import sources as well as invest into foreign oil fields prudently. \u2022 Engage in barter as well as mutually beneficial cross-border trade in energy Measures to reduce demand for oil (e.g. diversification of energy sources, increased energy efficiency) can also help protect economies from fluctuations in the oil price. In addition to national approaches, governments need to consider regional responses to the food and fuel price crisis. In the short term, this should include moves to eliminate agricultural export bans and release public grain stocks, which will help contain prices across the region. In the medium term, SAARC and ASEAN discussions on the setting up of a regional Food Bank should be continued to help countries respond to future crises. As far as oil is concerned, consideration should be given to establishing an Asia-Pacific Compensatory Oil Finance Facility (AP-COIL) Facility to assist regional LDCs and LICs. This Facility could provide to qualifying LDCs assistance primarily in the form of grants and for LICs a blend of grants and highly confessional loans. This would have two purposes. First, it would enhance a country\u2019s liquidity to help it overcome a balance of payments or fiscal deficit. Second, it would help the country finance essential structural changes to reduce its dependence on oil. A similar facility could be created to assist regional food importing LDCs and LICs. Net food importing countries and other countries faced with domestic shortages need to have financing windows to take care of their short term needs and liquidity constraints to finance food imports in the short run. Many countries have argued for a dedicated food financing facility in addition to the IMF\u2019s Compensatory Financing Facility (CFF) and Exogenous Shocks Facility and emergency facilities of the IMF and World Bank at the WTO in 2001. The international community can support governments in the Asia Pacific region, through: \u2022 Donor support to agricultural sectors, and to food safety net programmes \u2022 Rethinking biofuel policy \u2022 Pushing for a completion of the Doha Round, with an outcome designed to enhance food security, including through dismantling trade-distorting subsidies \u2022 Preventing speculation by price controls and monitoring food grains trade \u2022 Supporting research to improve energy efficient and alternative fuel technology; as well as enhanced agricultural production. Role of the UNDP - How can the UNDP assist countries on food and fuel price shocks? On-going UNDP support The UNDP is working actively with national and international partners in responding to the many challenges posed by the food and fuel price shocks. Addressing the food and fuel crisis requires a cooperative approach involving the countries affected, donors, and international 97 organizations. A multilateral", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "86834d2f-98d0-4d95-b7d7-602dac099b95": {"__data__": {"id_": "86834d2f-98d0-4d95-b7d7-602dac099b95", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1f4a55fe9ddaf469ff9aff30491f8d2aab58100dd3b56a1f88787a3f22e46039"}}, "hash": "1f4a55fe9ddaf469ff9aff30491f8d2aab58100dd3b56a1f88787a3f22e46039", "text": "approach to addressing this global problem enhances the effectiveness of the response and helps minimizes negative spillovers. In Asia and the Pacific, at the country level, UNDP\u2019s responses on food and fuel crisis are focused around three programme areas: \u00a7 Coordination \u2013 In its role as Coordinator of UN development activities at the country level, UNDP is working with governments, other UN and international agencies to collectively offer coherent and effective support to governments on food and fuel price volatilities in the region and help develop copying strategies. \u00a7 Policy advisory services - The UNDP is engaged in policy advisory services with many countries to help them address the impacts of global food and fuel price changes on the national development strategies. Examples include Indonesia, Mongolia, Bangladesh, Nepal, China, Thailand to quote a few. The pacific countries receive policy advisory support from UN Coordination team on energy access enhancement linked to their MDG targets. \u00a7 Technical assistance - UNDP provides technical support to governments in undertaking technical analysis of macro, micro or sector specific programmatic responses. Examples include Mongolia and Pakistan, China, Philippines Possible UNDP support in future At a global level, UNDP should continue to support international efforts to alleviate the impact of the food and fuel price volatilities on the poor, and to address its root causes. At the regional level, extensive analytical work is needed on various dimensions of the recent price increases, with a view to adequately diagnosing the underlying causes of the price increases as well as their impact and come up with policy responses that are relevant in the country context as well as identify roles of regional bodies At present, many countries in the Asia Pacific region are interested in understanding the underlying causes and socio-economic implications of rising food and fuel prices as well as policy options to cope with emerging challenges. In other words, the greatest demand for UNDP engagement is to help countries evaluate the socio-economic implications of rising food and fuel prices, as well as the available policy responses. Since many governments are faced with controlling inflation as well as sustaining growth in the face of global slowdown, the UNDP can provide technical and analytical inputs to highlight the trade-offs involved and help countries forge an effective response. For instance UNDP has already helped nine countries in Asia and twelve PICs to undertake in-depth analysis of challenges and way forward faced in establishing linkages between energy access and poverty reduction. UNDP can continue to help development targets building on these identified challenges policy and program design in NDS and feed into emerging strategies for both climate mitigation and adaptation. Given the UNDP past record as neutral and trustworthy partner, the UNDP is well positioned to help countries in this regard particularly identifying and promoting the appropriate short and long-term policies. There is strong demand for the UN and IFI advice on the design and expansion of safety net programs and food market interventions to help protect vulnerable groups. Given the profound humanitarian consequences of rising food and fuel prices, there is a strong case for strengthening social safety net programmes, in particular for LICs. In this regard, improving the quality of and access to safety nets will be a priority for protecting vulnerable households. The policy challenge in many countries is to replace poorly targeted and expensive policy 98 responses with more cost-effective targeted programmes. The same approach needs to be encouraged for increased energy access at the level of poor households with no access to cheap and clean fuel. It is not often understood or even prioritised that meeting the MDG targets need energy as a primary input across most of the sectors. In countries that do not have effective safety nets, new safety net programmes (e.g. school feeding programs, cash transfers to the most vulnerable populations, reduction in education and health fees, and public transport subsidies) should be designed and implemented. In countries that do have some forms of safety net, the UNDP can help make these stronger and more flexible to cope with shocks, with clear targeting and programmatic frameworks that can be quickly scaled up to protect vulnerable households. In addition, expanding programmes to ensure basic nutrition, particularly for infants, and improved access to health and education systems will also help minimize the likelihood that income shocks reduce demand and damage human capital accumulation. There has also been demand for advice on market interventions to smooth supply and lower food prices. With regards to improving food supply, the focus should be to (i) improve producer incentives (including the removal of subsidies which benefit", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ee76df45-c2bb-4e56-b318-059e9bf0c291": {"__data__": {"id_": "ee76df45-c2bb-4e56-b318-059e9bf0c291", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "491de0a1a85e842ea594b1e44e102885fd1fcd9c41e4c8822a50677d82853693"}, "3": {"node_id": "5350fe2f-5476-4569-a824-cd3f770f967c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1f3355d972a2d24585291d1b8830dedf08125bf0f39a5534d28bee1e4ff171e9"}}, "hash": "44b47f3f8036d57c7dbbeb3ea1a76b439082b14ebeb9fb733da9d9fd2ee8fd31", "text": "richer farmers more); (ii) provide quality core public goods \u2013 science, infrastructure and human capital; and (iii) stronger institutions to support an attractive rural investment climate for men and women, including more access to rural financial institutions and risk management instruments, improved property rights, and greater opportunities for collective action by farmers; and (iv) ensure sustainable use of natural resources. In fact, the recent WDR on Agriculture identified these four key elements for a comprehensive approach to agricultural growth. Technical assistance \u2013 UNDP helps and needs to continue it\u2019s support to countries in assessing the micro and macroeconomic impact of recent shocks. Based on country-specific diagnoses, UNDP could offer policy advice on issues related to strengthening social safety net programmes as well as fiscal space, monetary and exchange rates, and trade policies. In introducing policy responses such as social safety net programmes, tax and tariff changes or transfer programmes, issues related to their appropriate design and implementation are often an important consideration. The UNDP should assist countries address these challenges in its areas of expertise. Analytical work to understand better the economic, poverty and social implications of rising food and fuel prices is also critical. This can contribute to the design of flexible, country specific strategies. This implies expanding UNDP diagnostics and support in critical areas such as distributional analysis of food and fuel price increases and safety net programmes and identifying agricultural constraints and promoting inclusive growth. The UNDP should work with countries and donors on global and regional debate on bio-fuels through analysis, monitoring and balancing of competing needs for energy and food security. UNDP could also initiate area-based development programming\u2014including microfinance \u2013 that can help poor rural areas take advantage of the opportunities presented buy higher food prices. The later will directly support the new and emerging area of donor interest of meeting the Climate challenges using integrated territorial approach to both mitigation and adaptation strategies at local levels. Coordination and advocacy - UNDP could also help governments to analyse the causes and implications of rising food and fuel prices for their national development strategy and investment programmes. In doing so, the UNDP needs to work closely with other donors to build a shared dialogue and coordinated response. In this regard, policy dialogue can help countries to align policy and media discourse to gain political support for reforms. For 99 example, a policy dialogue on food stocks (which addresses optimal stock amounts, fiscal trade-offs, and implementation challenges) will be useful for food import countries. Similar policy dialogue on effective, appropriate and optimal levels of the fuel and food subsidy programmes will also be useful. This is because subsidies or price controls can create distortions. Attempts to maintain domestic food prices below world levels through untargeted subsidies, price controls, or export restrictions create incentives for evasion of the controls or smuggling of food. Similarly, a policy forum on biofuel policies would be useful. Less ambitious targets and low biofuels subsidies would lower pressure on food prices by reducing the competition with food for agricultural land and resources. Moreover, the impacts of the recent surge in food prices are creating different challenges including social, economic and environmental challenges. Because it is capable of weaving together these multi-disciplinary perspectives, the UNDP is well-placed to catalyze global and regional action and influence the international agenda. For example, UNDP can work with countries and other donors to minimize the adoption of policies with negative spillover effects for others. Examples include export ban, high levels of tariffs and subsidies, short term adaptation measures to Climate Change without fully working out the long term implications of the measures etc. It is clear that key components of the UNDP\u2019s support area include coordination, technical assistance and policy advice. 100 References ADB (Asian Development Bank). 2005. \u201cThe Challenges of Higher Oil Prices. Asian Development Bank Outlook. 2005 Update\u201d. Manila: ADB. ADB (Asian Development Bank). 2008a. \u201cAsian Development Outlook 2008\u201d, Manila: ADB. ADB (Asian Development Bank). 