data": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "94382f78a52c04d54ad5bd4af628927247057ce899fb0fb92ef28609f93c8e61"}, "2": {"node_id": "fea822c1-0807-4a9a-ac91-1ba288743837", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3360d85681263c7087ad8662b109e44872262b2cf186630cfa18efd7e589c6b8"}}, "hash": "c08bae2455d9aac7a5d81a0b4feb7f8cdd76de7cf295d123f1e88acd8d16a77a", "text": "International trade statistics 2007, World Trade Organization, Geneva, http://www.wto.org/english/res_e/statis_e/its2007_e/its07_merch_trade_product_e.htm. 104 Annex 1: POTENTIAL SHORT TERM SOLUTIONS: FOOD STAMPS/ COUPONS What are food stamps?: Scope, objectives, scale of coverage \u2018Food stamps\u2019 are a form of public subsidy to food consumption whereby the government provides a special currency which can only be used for staple food purchases. The term \u2018food stamps\u2019 is often used to describe a range of food linked income transfer schemes. These include tokens or discount cards which can be exchanged for food, or for the right to buy discounted food. Alternatively electronic transfer cards, which are credited each month with an allowance to be spent on food, may be used. Food linked income transfer schemes vary widely in individual and commodit y coverage, as well as scale. The objective of the scheme is usually nutritional (to increase the quantity or quality of food consumed) or livelihood related (to enable poor farmers to meet their overall basic needs). Stamps may also be targeted at vulnerable groups such as women and children. Another objective may be to provide a bigger market for domestic suppliers. Food stamps involve lower costs than food distribution systems, and have a greater likelihood of resulting in increased food consumption t han straight cash transfers (see below). However, food stamps are difficult to implement without a strong supporting government and private sector architecture (see below) and so have not been widely employed. Historically, they have been more prevalent i n the Americas, whereas Asian governments have tended to prefer distribution schemes. Although food stamps are associated with developing countries, arguably the most well known and successful food stamps programme is in the USA. In general, food stamps have been adopted as a temporary measure to help poor consumers adapt to short term shocks such as the removal of more generalized subsidies, or after currency devaluation. However, many such programmes have lasted much longer than expected, largely becaus e they are popular with recipients and therefore difficult to unpick. Country experiences Sri Lanka Sri Lanka introduced food stamps in 1979 as an attempt to wean the population off unaffordable general food subsidies (which then accounted for 15% of government spending).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5383cfff-c78b-41f3-b9c2-d656631c3a7c": {"__data__": {"id_": "5383cfff-c78b-41f3-b9c2-d656631c3a7c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0f0eb4bbbaceab3a1a9bd8a1a41475a8f91eed821b7dd022be3eef5770188d2f"}}, "hash": "0f0eb4bbbaceab3a1a9bd8a1a41475a8f91eed821b7dd022be3eef5770188d2f", "text": "The stamps were intended to focus benefits on the most needy sections of society. However, by 1989, around 50% of the population were receiving food stamps, before the scheme was phased out in the 1990s. The stamps could be used to purchase rice (which accounted for 75% of food stamp purchases), flour, bread, sugar and milk products. The main problem affecting the success of Sri Lanka\u2019s food stamp programme was inflation. Failure to adjust the scheme in line with inflation meant tha t the real value of the stamps declined by around 50% over its first two years. The Government was reluctant to adjust the value of the stamps in line with inflation for fear of increasing the cost of the scheme. Moreover, the stamps did not reach the intended recipients: around 30% of the poorest quintile did not participate, whilst large numbers of richer families did. This was due to miscalculations of income, and the fact that income calculations were not recalculated over time. In addition, because coupons were not targeted at vulnerable groups such as pregnant women and children, most extra food was consumed by men. Edirisinghe (1987) estimated that amongst the poorest calorific intake actually declined after the introduction of stamp scheme. The scheme was much cheaper than general food subsidies, however, accounting for only 3% of government spending. Since abandoning the scheme, Sri Lanka has looked to other means of subsidizing consumption, such as \u2018fair price\u2019 co -operative shops for the poor. Source: Casta\u00f1eda 2000, Edirisinghe 1986 Philippines In 1983, a one-year pilot food subsidy project was introduced in the Philippines by its National Nutrition Council and Ministry of Agriculture. Eligibility for the scheme was based on geography \u2013 i.e. villages with high levels of malnutrition were selected, rather than through any assessment of need 105 at the household level. Selected families were issued with a discount card, which allowed them to purchase cooking oil and for some families, rice in accr edited local stores. These products were selected because they are staple foods of the target population, are income elastic for the poor, and in the case of oil, high in calorific vale. Local markets in rice and oil were considered effective i.e. able to respond to increased demand. The cards gave a 32% discount on rice and 50% for oil. Participants could purchase 5kg of rice a month, about half of an average family\u2019s monthly consumption. However they could use the cards to purchase and up to 2.5 cups of oil (an extra marginal amount, with the intention of increasing consumption of this product). Storekeepers were given a 3% incentive reward when they redeemed the subsidized cost of accepting the cards. Transactions were recorded on the cards which were replaced monthly and transactions studied to check for fraud. Robust monitoring and support mechanisms were established. When analysed, the scheme was found to have increased the poorest participants\u2019 average income by a rather modest 9.1%, and account ed for approximately 8% of beneficiaries\u2019 daily calorie intake. The cost of implementing the scheme was low - around US$0.79 per beneficiary per month. 83.4% of this was food costs, 7.2% retailer incentives, and only 9.4% administration. The scheme experienced some leakages: geographic needs testing meant that some richer households were included in the scheme (although some of these were observed to have shared their entitlements with poorer families); eligible households invited extended family members from non-eligible villages to move in, increasing their entitlements which were based on family size; and there was significant resale or use for business purposes of the cooking oil by poor families (but not the rice). Other problems identified with the s cheme were that it caused delays and queues in participating retailers, problems with accessing stores for geographically dispersed families, and difficulties in use of the cards for illiterates. Source: Garcia 1988 India India has historically relied more heavily on food distribution (through its public distribution system or PDS) than food stamps as a means of achieving food security. In 1993 Purcell and Gulati argued for the replacement of the PDS with a food stamp system, on the grounds that this would be more targeted on the poorest, that it would remove the need for the Government to operate extensive food distributions systems, and would help free Indian\u2019s markets in staple foods, by allowing producers to benefit from market prices and thereby stimulating the agricultural system. However Swaminathan (2000, 2004) has argued that by targeting only the poorest, food stamps will exclude many who are going hungry. Moreover, the replacement of the PDS with vouchers or stamps would be unpopular,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "979cd5c1-49e6-477c-b7ee-8cab3abf464c": {"__data__": {"id_": "979cd5c1-49e6-477c-b7ee-8cab3abf464c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "22cebdb3c27900572825fc06f547e3310711da1f27522632191ef263a0fb4259"}}, "hash": "22cebdb3c27900572825fc06f547e3310711da1f27522632191ef263a0fb4259", "text": "and, at a time of rising hunger and prices, could even spark unrest. India has experimented with small scale and hybrid voucher systems. For example, in Andhra Pradesh in 1988 -9, beneficiaries were given vouchers for rice and kerosene, which must however be used in existing ration shops. The coupons were denominated in small quantities and could be redeemed only with the production of a photo card. The State Government believed that this system reduced corruption by saving about 20,000 tonnes of rice and 7,100 kilo litres of kerosene every month over the previous pure rationing system (sources: Jenkin and Goetz, 2002, India\u2019s tenth 5 year plan). Pakistan A World Food Programme activity in Pakistan, Creating Assets for Rural Women (CARW) originally involved the distribution of imported wheat to recipients. However, in the Sindh province, the WFP has experimented with substituting food stamps for the wheat, through a state owned philanthropic organization. This pilot has saved significant resources previously used in distributing, transporting and storing grain, and the WFP is considering its extension to further regions. The programme is aimed, because of limited resources, at the very poorest communities, and the most nutritionally vulnerable members of these (women and children). The stamps, currently valued at half a daily wage, will be adjusted for inflation over time. Source: World Food Programme 2003 Pros and Cons Food stamps are more popular with the general public than cash transfers, as most people believ e food stamps are also more efficient than cash transfers in addressing hunger, as they can only be spent on food items. Although economic theory (see e.g. Southwell 1945) would suggest that inframarginal 106 levels of food stamps can result in equivalent levels of subsidy diversion to other purchases (i.e. because although the stamps are spent on food, this frees up some income to be spent on non-food items), evidence from the States and elsewhere suggests that in practice food stamps use results in a greater increase in food consumption than cash transfer (see e.g. Fraker 1990). In a multi -country study, Casta\u00f1eda (2000) found that food stamp programmes generally improved families\u2019 disposable income by 20-25%, but that food consumption improved even more greatly than would be expected for a transfer of this scale. Rogers and Coates (2002) argue that this is because food stamps are more likely to be controlled by women, whereas cash is more likely to be controlled by men, and that this may result in more of the extra resource being devoted to food for the family\u2019s children. Another factor which may in practice limit diversion is the use of small denominations of food vouchers, where the transaction cost of \u2018converting\u2019 these into cash by resale or other means is high The biggest advantage that food stamps offer over food distribution programmes is one of affordability. Food stamps are much cheaper to administer because they absolve the government of responsibility for purchasing, transporting and distributing grain. Because they rely on strict a priori identification of recipients, they also allow greater targeting than distributions systems. In a tight budgetary situation (as many governments are experiencing, due to broader effects of the crisis), the targeting of benefits to the most deserving ensures that the majority of government funding is channelled where it is needed most. Enhanced targeting brings its own challenges. As mentioned above, Swaminathan (2000, 2004) has argued that targeting is undesirable in a country such as India which has large populations of which many are hungry and poor. What is needed, he argues, are broad programmes which bring food to the deserving many. It is worth noting, however, that there is no inherent reason why a food stamp scheme of broad scope could not be introduced. Another challenge in targeting the poorest groups through food stamps is that the most impoverished individuals may be illiterate and/ or lack a permanent address, both of which will hinder their attempts to register in a food stamp scheme. By removing direct government intervention in the food markets, food stamps also enable the freer operation of market price mechanisms. This can be an advantage or a disadvantage for the poor. Where supply if of eligible food is able to respond to increased demand, and in particular where such food is locally produced, food stamps can create a virtuous cycle where production increases to meet demand, increasing farmers\u2019 incomes and rural livelihoods. However, where there are supply constraints, increased demand arising from food stamp use is likely to result in inflation (Rogers and Coates). Not only does this increase prices for non-recipients of the stamps, it will also make", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3ca0ad82-f76a-4b7e-bd4c-a8b7092d5249": {"__data__": {"id_": "3ca0ad82-f76a-4b7e-bd4c-a8b7092d5249", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "36f84246d9a6dba34df5b03b5a05d1c9d4fb81543c255a18585328bf6c125424"}}, "hash": "36f84246d9a6dba34df5b03b5a05d1c9d4fb81543c255a18585328bf6c125424", "text": "the stamps less valuable for recipients, unless they are adjusted for inflation. Even where food stamps do not in themselves contribute to inflation, they remain vulnerable to its effects, unless mechanisms are in place to ensure that the value of the stamps tracks inflation. Otherwise, the benefits from the scheme will decline over time whilst administrative costs remain constant (see Sri Lanka\u2019s experience above). For this reason, governments should be cautious about introducing widespread food stamp schemes at a time of strong infl ation (especially food price inflation). If properly implemented, food stamps may be less vulnerable to corruption and other leakage than either cash or food distribution. However, this relies on the coupons having inbuilt security features, and the existence of a robust monitoring and evaluation system to prevent misuse. Depending on coverage, food stamps also offer more choice to consumer than food distribution systems, which may result in purchase of higher-quality/ calorie foods such as meat or milk (Gentilini 2007) Food stamps may not, however, be attractive to retailers or traders (Gentilini 2007), both because they impose on retailers (as well as customers) the burden of handling and redeeming vouchers, and because retailers may not believe that the coupons are fully liquid Eligibility for becoming a food stamp retailer may also determine who has access to government subsidized grain. Geography is also an issue: it may be impractical to distribute or monitor the use of stamps in a population whic h is 107 widely dispersed. Equally, such a population may find it difficult to access an eligible store. Another risk associated with the use of food stamps is that vouchers will be resold on the black market. Finally, there is a question over how long a food stamp programme should last: although food stamps can become part of a permanent government strategy to address hunger, poverty and/ or malnutrition, it could act as a disincentive for individuals to seek work, especially if eligibility is determined by income. In summary, food stamps are most likely be a sound policy response where some or all of the following characteristics are present: \u00a7 The government has the required infrastructure and administrative structures to implement and monitor the intervention effectively; \u00a7 A well developed commercial retail and banking sector exists; \u00a7 The government\u2019s credibility in economic matters is good \u2013 i.e. that there is faith that the government will honour the food stamps; \u00a7 Existing inflationary pressures are low, OR the scheme will be too limited in scope to affect overall pricing levels; \u00a7 The main limitation on hungry households is related to purchasing power as opposed to food availability; \u00a7 The scheme is intended as a temporary solution to a short term problem (as it does nothing to improve underlying structural causes of hunger); \u00a7 There is a clear difference in needs between those inside and outside the food stamp scheme which justifies targeting of resources; \u00a7 Social factors such as poverty-linked alcohol abuse argues against cash transfer, and in favour of more control of household resources by women \u00a7 Even where some of these factors are absent, where food distribution schemes are unaffordable. How to design and implement a successful food stamp programme Many of the elements relevant to designing and implementing a successful food stamp or food coupon programme are common to food distribution systems. For example, it is critical to have clarity about what the scheme is intended to achieve, and who the targeted benefi ciaries are. Rogers and Coates (2002) claim that food stamps may encourage a degree of self -deselection as non-poor individuals may not wished to be stigmatized by receiving the stamps. However the experience of Sri Lanka suggests that governments in developing countries would be wise not to rely on this. Targeting by geographical area, as in the Philippines example, is cheap and easy to administer, but may result in abuse and/ or leakage. By comparison, means-testing households may be more accurate but is expensive, can exclude the illiterate or homeless, and, as the Sri Lankan example shows, can be counter-productive unless assessments are accurate. It is also critical to ensure that needs are reassessed on a regular basis, as households move in and out of poverty. Since food stamps tend to be more targeted than food distribution mechanisms, a premium must be placed on identifying the most deserving recipients. There needs to be robust monitoring and evaluation mechanisms in place to ensure benefits are being realized and leakages minimized. This is not an appropriate area for economizing, as the potential for wastage is high. In the case of short-term schemes intended", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a32dd53f-7b00-4662-b373-37ba37923f51": {"__data__": {"id_": "a32dd53f-7b00-4662-b373-37ba37923f51", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "34c7cbc11b9ba6a182407debbf6631029c7a383312c21c26ed6932fb1ca68c0d"}, "3": {"node_id": "56d0bc72-ed4b-4b61-9965-acc62cd0f0ca", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "164086d3619106f42caec90b2e478085e77e1559d987ad20c86e5e02ba9490b4"}}, "hash": "150b2fd74bf90d6c1bad9f14747b0256d2a12bcb92aebf07511e3a4396294e74", "text": "to protect the vulnerable at times of crisis, there needs to be a credible exit strategy. In terms of issues specific to the use of food stamps, care needs to be taken in determining the design of the stamps or coupons, to minimize the potential for fraud, though the benefits of sophisticated security measures may need to be balanced against their costs. Recirculation of vouchers as unofficial currency and the creation of a black market can be countered by producing vouchers in small denominations and with expiry dates. 108 Retailers need to be paid promptly (and consideration given to i ncentive payments for accepting vouchers). They should be accessible, and willing to serve beneficiaries and have a clear understanding of their roles and responsibilities. The coverage of commodities is important. Free choice may be desired by beneficiaries. But a focus on locally produced staples may help local farmers\u2019 livelihoods. Limitation to \u2018low status\u2019 but nutritious foods can help self-deselection by richer families. Families can also be steered towards new dietary patterns, including the consumption of higher calorie or nutrient food. However, as the Philippines example shows, dietary preference changes slowly and in the meantime leakage (through the resale of food) may result. Another key issue is the need for systems to be in place to a djust the value of the stamps in line with inflation, otherwise the benefits from the system will decline over time, while the administrative overhead will remain constant. Alternatively, stamps or vouchers can be denominated by quantity of foodstuff, rather than price. This may create problems in verifying retailers\u2019 claims for compensation, however, particularly in the case of rapidly fluctuating food prices. In terms of scale and cost, most food stamp programmes have tended to aim at covering 20 -25% of beneficiaries\u2019 food costs. (Casta\u00f1eda, 2000). Although larger transfers have been tried (such as for certain US states) this is unlikely to prove affordable for most developing countries. Below the 20% mark, the administrative overhead required for operation of the scheme is unlikely to be justified by any health benefits. Again, it is vital that governments ensure that the stamps are inflation-linked, otherwise the intended benefits will not be realized. Casta\u00f1eda (2000) has noted that the benefits from food stamp schemes can be maximized if they can be linked to other social safety net programmes (e.g. by making them dependent on mothers\u2019 attendance at pre- or post-natal clinics, or children\u2019s immunization programmes). This does assume, however, capacity to deliver supplementary programmes. Another approach, which has been tried in Jamaica and Honduras, is to provide food stamps only to specific individuals e.g. pregnant and lactating women. Additionally, as in the Philippines example above, a food stamp programme can be enhanced by educational programmes which teach communities about nutritional and food safety issues. 109 References Casta\u00f1eda, Tarsicio \u2018The Design, Implementation and Impact of Food Stamp Programs in Developing Countries\u2019 April 2000, Human Development Network, The World Bank Edirisinghe, N. 1986. \u2018The food stamp scheme in Sri Lanka: costs, benefits, and options for modifications.\u2019 Research Rep. no 58, IFPRI, Wash., D.C. Fraker, T. 1990 \u2018The effects of Food Stams on Food Consumption: A review of the literature\u2019 Mathematica Policy Research, Prepared for United States Department of Agriculture Washington DC Garcia, Marito, \u2018Food Subsidies in the Philippines: Preliminary Results http://www.ifpri.org/pubs/books/ppa88/ppa88ch14.pdf 1988 last accessed 27 August 2008 Gentilini,U, 2007, \u2018Cash and food transfers: a primer\u2019 Occasional Papers No 18, World Food Programme Southworth, Herman M. The Economics of Public Measures to Subsidize Food Consumption Journal of Farm Economics, Vol. 27, No. 1 (Feb., 1945), pp.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "56d0bc72-ed4b-4b61-9965-acc62cd0f0ca": {"__data__": {"id_": "56d0bc72-ed4b-4b61-9965-acc62cd0f0ca", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "34c7cbc11b9ba6a182407debbf6631029c7a383312c21c26ed6932fb1ca68c0d"}, "2": {"node_id": "a32dd53f-7b00-4662-b373-37ba37923f51", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "150b2fd74bf90d6c1bad9f14747b0256d2a12bcb92aebf07511e3a4396294e74"}}, "hash": "164086d3619106f42caec90b2e478085e77e1559d987ad20c86e5e02ba9490b4", "text": "27, No. 1 (Feb., 1945), pp. 38-66 Published by: Blackwell Publishing on behalf of the American Agricultural Economics Association Stable URL: http://www.jstor.org/stable/1232262 Last accessed 26 August 2008 Jenkins, Roy and Anne Marie Goetz \u2018Civil Society Engage ment and India\u2019s Public Distribution System: Lessons from the Rationing Kruti Samiti in Mumbai\u2019 University of Sussex October 2002 Planning Commission, Government of India, \u2018Tenth Five year Plan 2002 -7\u2019 http://planningcommission.nic.in/plans/planrel/fiveyr/welcome.html Last accessed 27 August 2008 Pursell, Garry and Ashok Gulati (1993), \u2018Liberalizing Indian Agriculture: An Agenda for Reform\u2019, Working Paper 1172, World Bank, September Swaminathan, Madhura 2000, \u2018Weakening Welfare: The Public Distribution of Food in India\u2019, Leftword. Swaminathan, Madhura 2004, \u2018Targeted Food Stamps\u2019, The Hindu, 3 August. Rogers, Beatrice Lorge and Coates, Jennifer, Social Safety Net Primer Series: Food-Based Safety Nets and Related Programs\u2019 June 2002 World Bank Institute World Food Programme, 2003 draft Country Programme, Pakistan http://www.wfp.org/eb/docs/2003/wfp015849~2.pdf last accessed 26/08/08 110 Annex 2 FOOD FOR WORK What is \u2018Food for Work\u2019?: Scope, objectives, scale of coverage \u2018Food for work\u2019 schemes are a form of safety net, whereby a segment of unemployed", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "92a11e9e-776a-4b70-a8dd-216a70850138": {"__data__": {"id_": "92a11e9e-776a-4b70-a8dd-216a70850138", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "67b69c33398bbf22156fe9328d24593bd1da322397feb16eabfe682f85dded43"}}, "hash": "67b69c33398bbf22156fe9328d24593bd1da322397feb16eabfe682f85dded43", "text": "or underemployed society is invited to participate as workers in a public works programme, in exchange for a \u2018payment\u2019 of food rather than (or in addition to) cash. The objective of the scheme is usually livelihood related (to provide participants with work); nutritional aims (i.e. providing food rather than cash to ensure that the wage for this work is consumed as food) may be complementary or secondary. Some schemes have been specifically aimed at women workers, to help address issues of gender inequality, both in terms of right-to-work, and nutritional disparities (women, particularly in South Asia, tend to suffer higher rates of malnutrition and hunger than men). Often food-for-work has been established in post-conflict or disaster situations, where the state is weak, and there is a need for a self-targeting programme. Like food distribution systems, there is a high administrative overhead associated with work for food, as the government has to adopt a major role in buying, storing, transporting and distributing grain. However, they offer additional benefits compared with distribution systems where there is a high instance of unemployment or underemployment, in providing work for those affected, and for providing benefits to communities in terms of the output of participants. Food for work schemes have proved popular in South Asia as well as other parts of the developing world (notably sub-Saharan Africa), in part because of the willingness of international NGOs to provide food for such programmes. However there have been few formal eva luations of the effectiveness of Asian programmes, especially from a food security point of view. Country experiences India The National Food for Work Programme (NFFWP) was established by the Government of India in 2004. The NFFWP targeted the 150 most economically disadvantaged areas of the country (mostly tribal areas). The programme was intended as a pilot. Food for the programme was provided by the GoI, but State Governments were responsible for the handling and transportation of the food, and for food tax. The scheme was intended to be self-limiting, i.e. anyone wanting to participate could do so. The work offered was manual and semi-skilled in nature, and focused on water management, drought proofing and land management. Participants were paid at least 25% of their wages in cash, but with the remainder being of staple grains (normally up to 5kg per man day). Total wages were not to be less than the mandated minimum wage, and were to be paid weekly. The Programme has now been subsumed into the National Rural Employment Guarantee Act, which guarantees 100 days work for any rural worker willing to undertake unskilled work for minimum wage, and is one of the most ambitious social safety net programmes in the developing world. This incorporation sugges ts that the NFFWP\u2019s aims and outcomes were viewed primarily in terms of rural livelihoods rather than nutrition per se. Source: Government of India Bangladesh Bangladesh has operated a food for work programme since the aftermath of its 1974 famine. The main objectives of the programme are to provide rural employment, particularly during the dry season, and to provide labour to develop and maintain rural infrastructure. Programmes are regionally targeted on the poorest communities, and seem to have largely reached their target audience \u2013 the poorest quintile of the population being five times more likely to participate than the richest quintile. Moreover the programme has been particularly successful in times of particular food shortage \u2013 and is credited with avoiding a famine in 1988. However, Ravallion found there was a significant forgone 111 earning effect during the late 80s, which meant that the net income gain to participants was only 57% of their gross earnings. Sources: Hossain et al 2008 and Ravallion 1991 Afghanistan The World Food Programme has supported a major food for work programme in post -conflict Afghanistan, covering 2.9 million people in the first half of 2007. The main aim of the programme is to rebuild community assets such as schools, reservoirs and roads, as well as environmental projects, whilst helping meet Afghanistan\u2019s food security needs. Participants work for approximately 21 days per months in exchange for about 85% of their families\u2019 nutritional needs. The scheme operates in areas with no or limited market access or cash for work schemes, and where communities prefer food for work or a mixture of cash and food for work. Schemes operate in lean pre -harvest periods. Provision is made for resources for tools and other requirements as well as food. The food for work programme faces severe challenges from the poor security environment in Afghanistan, and is part of WFP\u2019s overall food security strategy for Afghanistan,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "efd519d5-5378-43e5-8c1a-83e10914fd5c": {"__data__": {"id_": "efd519d5-5378-43e5-8c1a-83e10914fd5c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a49526d368aa1465584c9619aac4c27d2a7f84fdc39d4024132f9e2e6510d54b"}}, "hash": "a49526d368aa1465584c9619aac4c27d2a7f84fdc39d4024132f9e2e6510d54b", "text": "which includes emergency food assistance and food for education. This ensures that those who are hungry/ malnourished but unable to participate in the scheme (e.g. the non-able bodied) will be supported though supplementary schemes. Source: World Food Programme 2005b and 2008 Food for work in Post-tsunami Asia The World Food Programme planned food for work interventions as part of its post-tsunami response in Sri Lanka and Indonesia (and to a lesser extent, Myanmar), along with food distribution and cash for work. The latter two programmes intended to be phased in aft er initial disaster relief with the aim of helping the reconstruction of damaged infrastructure as well as providing a food related social safety net. Challenges occurred because of lack of local experience with food for work programmes, and the continuation of government-run food distribution systems for longer than expected along side food for work (which disincentivised working, particularly for non-cash wages). Nor was it easy to find locally hired staff capable of adequately supervising food for work schemes. Moreover in Aceh it was found that, as local food markets were working effectively, cash for work was preferable to food for work, allowing more choice (including for non-food items) and reducing overheads. Nevertheless, food for work projects formed a significant component of the WFP\u2019s longer term tsunami recovery work in Sri Lanka, and in that country food transfers (through distribution or food for work) were found to be more effective in addressing malnutrition than cash transfers. Source: WFP 2005a Pros and Cons Food for work programme provides the ultra-poor with the dual benefits of work and food. Where food markets are working effectively, i.e. there is sufficient local capacity to respond to increased demand, and the problem is simply one of employment/ income, a cash-based public employment scheme may be equally effective as a food for work programme. This would also free the government of the expense of handling large quantities of food. However, cash is more likely to be spent on no n- food items (which may be desirable if it is spent on essentials such as health, education or shelter; but much less so if spent on e.g. alcohol). Moreover food for food for work schemes have often been provided by donors, making it attractive for governments (Lorge Rogers and Coates, 2002). Food for work programmes are more likely to be self-targeting for the very poor than pure distribution systems as cash wages are generally more desirable for those who can attain them (see e.g. Ravallion 1991). This means that the government can target needy households with relatively little administrative overhead. Moreover some of the problems associated with other safety net programmes which require enrollment (hence a permanent address and, sometimes, literacy) a re reduced or eliminated. Many of the other problems associated with distribution systems will apply for food for work, including leakage through corruption and wastage from poor storage. These can be limited to some extent through robust monitoring and other controls. But food for work programmes can be even more 112 expensive than distribution systems. Coady (2004) estimates that non-transferred costs, foregone non-scheme earnings by participants, and leakage to non-poor participants mean that it can cost as much as 146 rupees in a typical programme to transfer 60 rupees to a target beneficiary. Food for work programmes may be less likely to lead to a culture of dependency, as food is directly linked to employment. Participants may acquire new skills which may enhance their future employability. This might be particularly significant in post-conflict situations where food for work programmes might incentivise combatants to adopt new, peaceful, roles. However, in rural communities, participants who previously produced some food for their families may no longer be able to spare time to harvest and grow crops for personal consumption. Another risk, if the programmes are small in scale, is that other households may migrate to participating areas in search of work. This may necessitate restrictions on eligibility. Barrett (2006) has criticized work for food programmes for often having too many disparate aims (providing a safety net, building assets, ensuring food security) which means that their benefits are likely to become dispersed. It is notable that in the examples described above, nutritional objectives were often secondary to livelihood objectives or the desire to improve infrastructure. Participation in a work for food scheme entails having a house hold member who is fit enough to work (often in physically demanding tasks). Therefore such schemes may neglect the needs of some of the most vulnerable e.g. the infirm, elderly, disabled, pregnant or young. In summary, food for work programmes are", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c8a600d7-2efc-45be-9ac7-ecaead0bf05f": {"__data__": {"id_": "c8a600d7-2efc-45be-9ac7-ecaead0bf05f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5d366a86d8b2ab9f4a2b7f3a45814a240c7c9d23d7c96628a4139922b4f92a67"}}, "hash": "5d366a86d8b2ab9f4a2b7f3a45814a240c7c9d23d7c96628a4139922b4f92a67", "text": "most likely be a sound policy response where some or all of the following characteristics are present: \u00a7 There is a failure in both employment and food markets; \u00a7 There is little knowledge of, and little capacity to ascertain, levels of poverty and hunger at household or individual levels (this may include high illiteracy and low land and home ownership rates); \u00a7 Infrastructure is damaged or underdevelopment, and its improvement is as much a priority as feeding a population (or can help combat hunger and poverty throughout a community e.g. improving irrigation systems); \u00a7 The government can afford to act as a major purchaser and distributor of foodstuffs, and/ or donors are willing to provide the food for the programme; \u00a7 The scheme is intended primarily as a temporary solution to a short term problem (as its contribution to solving underlying structural causes of hunger is limited); \u00a7 There may have been a conflict or other crisis. How to design and implement a successful food stamp programme Unlike most food safety net programmes, the self-deselecting nature of food-for-work means that detailed targeting of recipients is not necessary (though some identification of poor neighbourhoods can help, especially in small scale projects). Some schemes have specifically targeted women, both because women tend to suffer higher rates of malnutrition and because the literature (e.g. Lorge Rogers and Coates 2002) suggests that food is more likely to reach vulnerable members of the family if it controlled by women. However both for women-only and for schemes targeted at both men and women, aspects such as physical strength and the need to provide child care may affect women\u2019s ability to participate or earn equal wages. Providing cr\u00e8ches and selecting appropriate work and wage structures can help offset these problems. A particular challenge for Food for Work programmes lies in setting the amount of food payable, both in respect of the nutritional needs of participants (especially if the work involves heavy physical labour) and equivalence with cash-paid labour, particularly if a minimum wage applies in that country (Rogers and Coates 2002). The balance here is between ethical and legal considerations which might 113 argue for a higher provision which might allow participants to progress out of poverty; and a more affordable scheme which will benefit a greater number of recipients. Lower wages will also enhance self-deselection of non-target populations. Wages can either be set by day (which will help ensure equal wages for weaker and more vulnerable participants) or by piece or progress (which will reward the more efficient worker and incentivise progress). The overall objectives of the individual project and the relative priority given to nutritional aims will be the deciding factor. Commodity selection is also important. High value non-perishable items (e.g. canned goods, oils) may be preferred by participants, but may also be resold (especially if food wage levels are set too high, i.e. more than participants would normally consume). Staple grains, perhaps fortified to add other nutrients, are the usual basis for food for work, but are expensive to store and transport. Small regular payments are less subject to resale leakage, but are more expensive to administer. Selecting \u2018low status\u2019 (but high-nutrition) foods can help self-deselection. In order to reduce leakages, control mechanisms such as that for public distribution systems are critical to prevent pilferage and other fraud as well as wastage through post -harvest loss. However, measures should also be taken to minimize leakage through for -gone earnings. For this reason, seasonal programmes such as that envisaged in Afghanistan may be appropriate. These would allow poor farmers to participate, but also to harvest and sell th eir own crops. Rogers and Coates (2002) suggest that a key factor in designing food for work programmes is that the public work element should be as meaningful as possible to local society. This can provide benefits for the wider community in terms of building community assets \u2013 as in the drought proofing work in the India example above. This can in turn form part of a longer-term strategy against hunger. Consideration should also be given to the location of projects, which should ideally be commutable for participants. Where nutritional aims are prioritized, it is important that those who cannot participate in the scheme because of health or other physical limitations should not be forgotten, and there is a strong argument for supplementing food-for-work with another safety net for these individuals (as in the Afghan example above). Finally, as with all social safety net programmes, it is essential that the programme is evaluated and monitored to ensure that it is meetings its intended objectives. References", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "39b7a49b-0699-43b9-82cb-ee3a3d9580e3": {"__data__": {"id_": "39b7a49b-0699-43b9-82cb-ee3a3d9580e3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6bed41e8f98617cae38a4cb29f568ab7827924b6b0d9d2e71fe210f15b475bbc"}, "3": {"node_id": "0cf100b8-8723-4bf2-91b7-1ca4241548e7", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fabac5450d4d3a971e18166a41191927b32912eb80fdf05fbe6def65e00a136c"}}, "hash": "7341bb08d8c06ab95af43be39e955e941ca263541ef7d93c8f88f62fd445bcfc", "text": "Barrett Christopher B. \u2018Food Aid as Part of a Coherent Strategy to Advance Food Security Objectives ESA Working Paper No. 06-09\u2019September 2006 www.fao.org/es/esa last accessed 1 September 2008 Coady, David P, 2004, \u2018Designing and Evaluating Social Safety Nets\u2019 FCND Discussion Paper No 172 IFPRI Washington Government of India National Food for Work Programme Guidelines http://india.gov.in/outerwin.htm?id=http://rural.nic.in/nffwpguidelines.htm [last accessed 1 September 2008] Hossain, Mahabub, Firdousi Naher and Quazi Shahabuddin, \u2018Food Security and Nutrition in Bangladesh: Progress and Determinants\u2019 e JADE electronic Journal of Agricultural and Development Economics Vol. 2, No. 2, 2005, pp. 103-132 Agricultural and Development Economics Division (ESA) FAO ftp://ftp.fao.org/docrep/fao/008/af136e/af136e00.pdf last accessed 1 September 2008 114 Ravallion, Martin \u2018Reaching the Rural Poor through Public Employment: Arguments, Evidence, and Lessons from South Asia\u2019 The World Bank Research Observer, Vol. 6, No. 2 (Jul., 1991), pp. 153- 175 Published by: Oxford University Press Stable URL: http://www.jstor.org/stable/3986315 Rogers, Beatrice and Coates, Jennifer, Social Safety Net Primer Series: Food-Based Safety Nets and Related Programs\u2019 June 2002 World Bank Institute World Food Programme 2005 \u2018Full Report of the Real Time Evaluation of WFP\u2019s response to the Indian Ocean Tsunami\u2019 Rome September 2005 Ref. OEDE/2005/3 (2005a) World Food Programme 2005 Post-Conflict Relief and Rehabilitation in the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan November 2005 http://www.wfp.org/operations/current_operations/project_docs/104270.pdf [last accessed 1 September 2008] (2005b) World Food Programme 2008 http://www.wfp.org/country_brief/indexcountry.asp?country=004 [last accessed 1 September 2008 115 Annex 3: FOOD DISTRIBUTION SYSTEMS What are food distribution systems?: Scope, objectives, scale of coverage \u2018Food distribution systems\u2019, also known as food rationing systems, are a form of food safety net whereby the government provides staple foods to poor and/ or hungry members of the population. They should however be distinguished from emergency food distribution or relief aid (short term food assistance targeted at crisis-hit populations) and supplementary feeding programmes (such as school feeding programmes, which are aimed at meeting nutritional shortfalls in targeted vulnerable sections of society). Food distribution systems are directly aimed at combating hunger and malnutrition amongst the poor, whether this is caused by poor access or availability of food. The primary aim is therefore usually nutritional. However secondary objectives may be livelihood related (as families can improve their standard of living since they no longer have to spend such a large portion of their income on food, yet are still free to find paid employment). Other objectives may be supporting producers and keeping food prices stable. Given the scale of the food distribution systems in India and China, this type of intervention has been one of the most widely applied food safety net in the Asia Pacific region, and moreover has been well studied. Country experiences India The Public Distribution System (PDS) was introduced in the 1960s, born out of a previous food rationing scheme which was set up in the 1940s. It aimed to provide staple food grains to the poor at affordable prices. It also aimed to support farmers by purchasing their produce at a fair price, and to maintain national food security by holding stockpiles for times of crisis. The scale of the PDS is huge \u2013 160 million families are reached each year. The PDS was originally untargeted (or self -targeted), but since 1997 has been refocused to meet the needs of the below poverty line (BPL) population, on the reasoning that rapid economic growth had improved the incomes of many. Since 1997, the above poverty line (APL) population pays approximately 90% cost for food purchased in participating retailers. BPL families can buy around 10kg (more in years where stocks are high) at half cost or even less.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "0cf100b8-8723-4bf2-91b7-1ca4241548e7": {"__data__": {"id_": "0cf100b8-8723-4bf2-91b7-1ca4241548e7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6bed41e8f98617cae38a4cb29f568ab7827924b6b0d9d2e71fe210f15b475bbc"}, "2": {"node_id": "39b7a49b-0699-43b9-82cb-ee3a3d9580e3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7341bb08d8c06ab95af43be39e955e941ca263541ef7d93c8f88f62fd445bcfc"}}, "hash": "fabac5450d4d3a971e18166a41191927b32912eb80fdf05fbe6def65e00a136c", "text": "The scheme focuses on food grains, but also covers sugar and cooking oil, which are sold through 489,000 fair price shops, 75% of them in rural areas. The value of commodities distributed annually is more than Rs 300 billion, with the Government of India (GoI) controlling about 10% of India\u2019s grain production. GoI meets the full costs of the scheme (except local distribution). The main disadvantages associated with the PDS are cost and leakage. There is a high cost associated with large scale purchase, storage and distribution of foodstuffs. The cost of the PDS has increased from 2.5% of total Government expenditure in the early 1990s to 6% in 2008. As well as the cost of running the system, farmers\u2019 interest groups have been successful in pushing up the minimum support price, which increases procurement costs to the Government. Similar vested interests have also led to the accumulation of excessive buffer stocks, which carry an associated opportunity cost. Moreover, the costs of the programme are greatly increased by leakages from corruption, pilferage and resale. Estimates of the rate", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "cd044e10-dbcf-4093-858f-0a34f4fc9424": {"__data__": {"id_": "cd044e10-dbcf-4093-858f-0a34f4fc9424", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "067068f0934b19428f5d7bbc0999f15df5ee4189e76471fa4cf6045f8e47f940"}, "3": {"node_id": "021a0ce9-85d3-4487-9f8c-87c633ce67a4", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e783758a9cd3dbb78b676a1b5be8a737b5a6e14457e3841445afa7cf8f03c21a"}}, "hash": "203d0ba87aa4ea7bc884ee6dcf1bef9487e9f53c016f4bb70945839f8c00c1f3", "text": "of leakage ranges from 31% for grain and 36% for sugar (Vittal 2002); to a staggering 87% of wheat and 94% of rice (Parivartan survey33). Leakage occurs at every 33 A local civil-society organization based in Delhi carried out a recent survey that revealed that out of a sample of 182 families, 142 families did not receive a single grain of wheat during the month of June, 2007. 167 families did not receive a single grain of rice. Out of a total of 4650 KG of wheat supposed to have been distributed to the people, only 595 Kgs had actually been received. The rest 87% found it s way to the black 116 stage of the system, from warehouse through retailer to end user (who often stockpiles food for resale). Participants are supposed to produce a ration card to reduce fraud, but this in itself creates the opportunity for bribe-seeking from those distributing the cards. Moreover the Programme Evaluation Organisation\u2019s 2005 Study established that there were large scale exclusion and inclusion rates in most States, due to errors in establishing people\u2019s poverty levels, and the fact that many above the official poverty line are still living in hunger and need. Leakages mean that average PDS purchases were less than 1 kilo per month (against average need of 11 kg) in some states, although in others (such as Jammu and Kashmir and Kerala) the scheme met nearly 50% of monthly needs for the average participant. Nevertheless, the PDS is a landmark scheme which has brought food to millions of needy families. Swaminathan (2000) amongst others has called for the maintenance of a broad based sch eme for targeting the many, rather than the few, in order to address hunger as a rights issue. The scheme is also very popular nationally, with recipients and suppliers. The PDS is supplemented by a number of other national food interventions which target especially vulnerable groups such as the elderly, and school children. India\u2019s eleventh five year plan suggests a number of design features to improve the PDS, namely computerization of PDS operations and improving security features of ration cares; an a dvocacy programme to publicise the benefits of the PDS; and a village grain bank scheme for food -insecure areas. Sources: as cited and Zhou and Wang (2006) and GoI 11 th Five year plan. China In the 1950s, the Government of China introduced the \u2018unified gr ain procurement and sale system\u2019 which meant that the Government became the only buyer of domestic grain. Buyers of grain (basically urban workers, rural non-agricultural workers, and restaurants and bakeries) were given coupons with which to buy food through government shops. Unlike the Indian system, the Chinese distribution system was targeted heavily at urban workers (who paid lower prices than rural recipients), irrespective of income and need. The system was viewed by the government as essential to providing social stability through ensuring adequate food security. However, the cost to the government began to rise rapidly, as procurement prices rose whilst selling prices remained static. In addition, Zhou and Wang (2006) argue that operational inefficiency also drove up the cost of the scheme. The scale of the programme was immense \u2013 at its peak the system handled 100 million tons of grain in one year (compared with around 20 million tons in the case of India\u2019s PDS). By 1990, the cost of the programme had risen to 27 billion yuan (1.44% of GDP), leading to calls for it to be abandoned, and for the market to determine grain prices. In 1993, as incomes rose and the scheme became less valued by urban consumers, the grain market was opened to market f orces. But, after just a couple of years of price volatility, responsibility for subsidizing grain or providing rations was delegated to regions. By the late 1990s, given increased production and low prices, rationing was discontinued in favour of cash transfers, although the government continues to subsidise grain prices and maintain stores in case of local shocks. Source: Zhou and Wang (2006) Pros and Cons The main advantage of distribution systems is that they can provide the immediate needs of a larg e hungry population. As they can be designed to be self-deselecting (see below), they often do not require sophisticated pre-targeting measures which may marginalize the deserving illiterate or homeless.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "021a0ce9-85d3-4487-9f8c-87c633ce67a4": {"__data__": {"id_": "021a0ce9-85d3-4487-9f8c-87c633ce67a4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "067068f0934b19428f5d7bbc0999f15df5ee4189e76471fa4cf6045f8e47f940"}, "2": {"node_id": "cd044e10-dbcf-4093-858f-0a34f4fc9424", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "203d0ba87aa4ea7bc884ee6dcf1bef9487e9f53c016f4bb70945839f8c00c1f3"}}, "hash": "e783758a9cd3dbb78b676a1b5be8a737b5a6e14457e3841445afa7cf8f03c21a", "text": "Although they are less self-deselecting than food for work schemes, they do leave participants free to participate in other economic activities to supplement their income. Other than infrastructure (such as roads and warehouses), and of course resources, they impose fewer state competency requirements than many cash", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "aef7d5e3-6a15-43c0-9f16-6685f98e5c78": {"__data__": {"id_": "aef7d5e3-6a15-43c0-9f16-6685f98e5c78", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c7a50b1ef523b507f8c467266f606b36eaffc7793a1b4836f7dc13e6971fc06c"}}, "hash": "c7a50b1ef523b507f8c467266f606b36eaffc7793a1b4836f7dc13e6971fc06c", "text": "or voucher schemes (e.g. reliable banking systems). market. Out of a total of 1820 KG of rice supposed to have been distributed as per daily sales registers, only 110 KG was received by the people. 94% was siphoned off. 117 Additionally, Rogers and Coates (2002) argue that food transfers are more likely to be controlled by women and that this may result in more of the extra resource being devoted to food for th e family\u2019s children. However food distribution systems are very expensive \u2013 usually at least twice as expensive as cash transfers (Oxfam, as cited by Gentilini 2007). This is because of the enormous costs involved in procuring, storing, transporting and distributing bulk grain; combined with the massive potential for leakage which occurs because food is harder to account for than cash. Governments in a weak fiscal position should be very cautious about starting a public distribution system, particular ly as costs have tended to sky-rocket, and they have proved difficult to dismantle. Large scale public distribution systems are likely to result in the government controlling prices in staple foods, which can help producers and non-targeted consumers by providing stability, and in the case of suppliers, a guaranteed market. However this may also mean that demand signals are not relayed to producers. Distribution systems are less likely to provoke inflation than cash -based systems (because they focus on increasing supply of rather than demand for food). However, they may trigger an unsustainable fiscal deficit because of spiralling costs. In summary, food distribution systems are most likely be a sound policy response where some or all of the following characteristics are present: \u00a7 There is a large number of deserving target recipients; \u00a7 The government can afford to finance a resource-intensive scheme; \u00a7 There are problems in identifying individual or household levels of poverty (due to weak bureaucracies or high illiteracy rates); \u00a7 The government has access to large quantities of affordable grain, either nationally produced or internationally donated; \u00a7 The government (or implementing agency) has the capacity to transport, store and distribute large quantities of food; \u00a7 At a regional/ local level there are problems around food availability as well as access; \u00a7 Market control of prices and/ or creation of purchase price certainty and fairness for domestic suppliers is considered desirable; \u00a7 Localised flooding or drought makes the acquisition of banked food stores desirable; \u00a7 The scheme is intended as a temporary solution to a short term problem (as it does nothing to improve underlying structural causes of hunger); \u00a7 Social factors such as poverty-linked alcohol abuse argues against cash transfer, and in favour of more control of household resources by women How to design and implement a successful food distribution system Asia\u2019s major food distribution systems have mostly emerged organically, evolving out of post -war rationing schemes which were focused on provision of scarce food. However, in an ideal world a public distribution system should only be introduced with a very clear idea of aims, objectives and target population. This is especially important because distribution systems have proved expensive, with escalating costs, and difficult to unpick except (as in China) where underlying problems of poverty and hunger are addressed. As discussed above, large scale distribution systems are most valuable where problems of hunger and poverty are widespread, and where there is limited need for targeting by income or vulnerability. However leakage to non-poor families should be minimized by careful commodity selection, to enhance self-deselection. For example, \u2018inferior\u2019 or lower status food (albeit with good nutritional value) is unlikely to be attractive to better off consumers. By contrast, higher status food, particularly if non-perishable and resaleable, will attract non target consumers (for instance, the inclusion of sugar and kerosene in India\u2019s PDS is thought to have attracted better -off families). Where more precise targeting is considered desirable, it is important that the homeless and illiterate are not excluded, and the balance between low cost, low accura cy methods (such as geographical 118 targeting) and high cost, high accuracy methods (household survey data) needs to be considered. Overall, targeting is more likely to be justified where resources are limited, and/ or where there is a high differentiation in terms of need between target and non-target populations. However if this is the case, alternative interventions such as food stamps may be more appropriate. Secondly, careful attention needs to be paid to storage and distribution networks for the food. If a distribution system is to meet its objectives, it needs to provide a regular supply or acceptable quality food. The infrastructure and logistics required to achieve this should", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a028ed09-dca4-44c5-a43b-2c09eb33cbae": {"__data__": {"id_": "a028ed09-dca4-44c5-a43b-2c09eb33cbae", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "802f22608780f220d7adf192ddc5a4bd9e2e6333974cf8f1e89e46bd2a914c54"}, "3": {"node_id": "f72adfcf-d337-4100-8388-cb8aa1e3c728", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0d8e73e32bd8ae77540a5e8f4e6f703b4268945ce4c717e2dca789b02286c6dc"}}, "hash": "6c07d2a2d42f97a88b1cf26e612c88fe90008789f8d5e95bf276a11c40dcf01d", "text": "not be underestimated, particularly for the large countries which have favoured distribution systems in the past. Moreover mechanisms must be in place at every stage of the distribution process to prevent leakage, both from spoilage, and, especially, corruption. Corruption is a major problem in many distribution schemes because of the challenges inherent in auditing bulk produce, as opposed to cash or vouchers. Moreover those handling food supplies at every point in the value chain are likely to be relatively poor and may be tempted therefore to take food. Attempts have been made to tackle fraud by participants through the use of ration cards. However, this causes problems of its own in that participants may need to pay a bribe to get a card; the illiterate or homeless may be unable to acquire one; and, crucially, much of the corruption-based loss occurs earlier in the supply chain. This argues for a greater investment in the policing of warehouses and supply networks, and for greater salaries for and oversight of those responsible for handling grains. Consideration needs to be given to how surplus stocks should be managed. The accumulation of stocks can be advantageous, particularly in countries which suffer from regionalized food production shocks such as drought or flooding. Moreover, recent price rises have emphasize d the importance of buffer stocks, both nationally and regionally. That said, accumulation of excessive buffer stocks represents an opportunity cost (food could be used to feed the hungry) and may result in participants being given old and poorer-quality food (ref). In both India and China, distribution systems have played an important role in supporting farmers by providing a reliable market for grain at a stable price. However, the relationship between the government and farmers must be handled carefully. First, it is important that the government, whilst taking into account genuine livelihood concerns from farmers, must protect the interests of the scheme\u2019s recipients as a primary concern. This means setting a purchase price which will be fair for consumers as well as producers, and which is fiscally sustainable. It is also important that market signals on increasing or decreasing demand are transmitted to farmers, again through government -set prices. Efforts by governments to control domestic prices are likely to reap limited rewards unless like China the government assumes a monopoly position in purchasing \u2013 this is likely to be unaffordable for most. However even limited market intervention may help stabilize prices. Finally, as the China example shows, the best way to end an expensive food distribution system is to work through parallel strategies such as job creation to improve incomes sufficiently that demand for the programme is drastically reduced. References Gentilini,U, 2007, \u2018Cash and food transfers: a primer\u2019 Occasional Papers No 18, World Food Programme Jenkins, Roy and Anne Marie Goetz \u2018Civil Society Engagement and India\u2019s Public Distribution System: Lessons from the Rationing Kruti Samiti in Mumbai\u2019 University of Sussex October 2002 Planning Commission, Government of India, \u2018Tenth Five year Plan 2002 -7\u2019 http://planningcommission.nic.in/plans/planrel/fiveyr/welcome.html Last accessed 27 August 2008 119 Rogers, Beatrice and Coates, Jennifer, Social Safety Net Primer Series: Food -Based Safety Nets and Related Programs\u2019 June 2002 World Bank Institute Swaminathan, Madhura 2000, \u2018Weakening Welfare: The Public Distribution of Food in India\u2019, Leftword. N. Vittal, Central Vigilance Commissioner, Government of India, \u2018Corruption in Public Life: Steps to Improve India\u2019s Image\u2019, public address, Mumbai, 14 Feb 2002 Zhou, Zhang-Yue and Wan Guanghua, 2006, \u2018The Public Distribution Systems of Foodgrains and Implications for Food Security: A Comparison of the Experiences of India and China\u2019 Research Paper No 2006/98 United Nations University UNU World Institute for Development Economics Research September 2006 120 Annex 4: SUPPLEMENTARY FEEDING ROGRAMMES. What are supplementary feeding programmes?: Scope, objectives, scale of coverage \u2018Supplementary feeding programme\u2019 is a term usually used to describe targeted food interventions aimed at combating malnutrition amongst vulnerable groups. Usually they take the form of school feeding programmes, or programmes targeted at pregnant and nursing mothers; babies and pre -school children; or the elderly, sick and infirm. Supplementary feeding programmes are therefore intended to combat hunger and malnutrition amongst the most vulnerable members of society. The primary aim is therefore usually nutritional. However supplementary feeding programmes often produce a number of very valuable secondary benefits.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f72adfcf-d337-4100-8388-cb8aa1e3c728": {"__data__": {"id_": "f72adfcf-d337-4100-8388-cb8aa1e3c728", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "802f22608780f220d7adf192ddc5a4bd9e2e6333974cf8f1e89e46bd2a914c54"}, "2": {"node_id": "a028ed09-dca4-44c5-a43b-2c09eb33cbae", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6c07d2a2d42f97a88b1cf26e612c88fe90008789f8d5e95bf276a11c40dcf01d"}}, "hash": "0d8e73e32bd8ae77540a5e8f4e6f703b4268945ce4c717e2dca789b02286c6dc", "text": "However supplementary feeding programmes often produce a number of very valuable secondary benefits. For example, school feeding programmes, if properly implemented, can increase school attendance (especially for girls), reduce drop-out rates and even improve performance and behaviour. Programmes focused on pregnant and lactating mothers can reduce the instance of low -birth weight babies and maternal mortality, and, along with feeding programmes for pre-school age children, can help children to develop normally both mentally and physically. Country", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3404d810-a16c-4b2b-a02b-36fba86a24d5": {"__data__": {"id_": "3404d810-a16c-4b2b-a02b-36fba86a24d5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0d5fe3757f570fe94f2e2151f84e6fec9cc8c7293d7add65fffa6e262b456753"}}, "hash": "0d5fe3757f570fe94f2e2151f84e6fec9cc8c7293d7add65fffa6e262b456753", "text": "experiences Tamil Nadu, India Tamil Nadu has had a long history of providing food for vulnerable populations, having had a mother and child programme since the 1950s. In 1982, the programme was extended to include pre -school children, and the school mid-day meal programmes is now deeply entrenched in the state\u2019s educational system, and regarded as an entitlement by its population. Meals given are cooked, nutritious, varied and tasty. Other elements have been incorporated into the programme, such as growth monitoring, worming, and the provision of supplements. 8% of the state\u2019s population is no w covered by the scheme. The scheme has had a dramatic impact on nutrition outcomes. Since 1983, severe malnutrition amongst 0-36 month age children has declined from 12% to negligible levels. The percentage of normal children has increased over the same period from 20% to 60%. The daily cost of operating the scheme has been estimated at USD 0.083 per recipient. Although the scheme faces some difficulties in the form of leakages, as well as second generation issues such as remote location access, continued staff motivation and limited community participation in scheme design, it has had a significant impact. The scheme is now being scaled up to national level, and the right to a mid-day meal for certain vulnerable population is now established under law (Supreme Court Orders of Nov 28, 2001). Initial results from other states have been mixed to date, emphasising the importance of good programme design (see below). For example, in Chhattisgarh poor management and infrastructure meant that cooking took place in soot-covered class-rooms, disrupting teaching, whilst in Rajasthan under-funding meant that the same meal was served each day and rejected by some castes. Nevertheless, the Tamil Nadu example does demonstrate that a sustainable school feeding programme is a possibility. Source: Rajivan, 2008 Bangladesh Since 2002, the World Food Programme has been running a school feeding programme in partnership with the Government of Bangladesh. The programme aimed to provide approximately 15% of participating children\u2019s calorific needs in the form of a biscuit which also contained essential vitamins and minerals. 128 schools were included from poor rural areas and rural slums. As well as nutritional aims, the programme was intended to increase enrolment, decrease drop-out and repetition rates, improve behaviour and performance; and to encourage the construction of safe wells and girls\u2019 toilet facilities. When reviewed in 2004 against non-nutritional aims only, Rogers et al found that the scheme was well implemented and reaching target children. Enrolment improved, though drop-out and repetition rates did not. Behaviour improved significantly according to teachers, and there was a 121 small but non-significant improvement in test scores. There was no impact on well and sanitary facilities. Although no assessment was made of the impact on nutritional outcomes, children and teachers interviewed claimed there was surprisingly little diversion in the form of leakage of the biscuits to non-target family members, nor in terms of substitution for food which would have been provided from home. Source: Rogers et al 2004 Pros and Cons The main advantage of (well run) supplementary feeding programmes is that they channel food to the most vulnerable groups, not just within a society but within a household. This is particularly important in countries where women have low status, and commensurate access to food resources. Malnutrition in women is not only of concern in itself, but is also important in terms of the nutritiona l profile of whole communities: underweight and malnourished women give birth to low birth weight babies, who fail to develop to their physical or mental potential. This in turn can affect their ability to earn a living, and hence buy food for themselves and their families. Women in this generation are also likely to be malnourished and to have low-birth weight babies, thus perpetuating the cycle. Therefore, unlike many food safety net schemes, supplementary feeding programmes can help break cycles of malnutrition and hunger, and therefore can be viewed as appropriate strategies for tackling some of the root socio/cultural/economic causes of hunger (rather than, for example, simply helping poor families through crises and price shocks). In terms of disadvantages, supplementary feeding programmes are expensive to administer. In itself, this may not be a problem, particularly as such programmes are likely, if well designed, to deliver significant positive externalities, such as greater school attendance (es pecially for girls), better birth outcomes and better health, which may actually save the state money (though there has yet to be a full economic analysis of the costs and benefits of such a scheme). Mothers of school age children may also be freed from some food", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "72f734fe-e2b9-491a-804d-f720604191b4": {"__data__": {"id_": "72f734fe-e2b9-491a-804d-f720604191b4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "99bde7870b2d15ccc2ce3e91b9f3da69d19dec16f4a324c383d2890087e1ddd1"}}, "hash": "99bde7870b2d15ccc2ce3e91b9f3da69d19dec16f4a324c383d2890087e1ddd1", "text": "preparation responsibilities and hence be more able to contribute to the household through paid or unpaid labour. The key however lies in effective programme design and delivery (see below). A poorly thought - through and executed programme may not meet even basic nutritional objectives, and may (as in the Chhatisgarh example above) distract resource from other services such as education provision. Without appropriate checks and balances, moreover, supplementary feeding programmes may be associated with excessive leakages \u2013 through corruption (those administering the programmes are likely to be poorly paid themselves), diversion (in the case of dry rations, children may bring the food back home to share with others) or substitution (parents may pro vide less food in the knowledge that the children are fed at school). Some donors may be more willing to contribute to supplementary feeding programmes \u2013 particularly school feeding programmes \u2013 than to other food safety nets as they may be more focused on secondary aims such as education. However in these cases it is important that other deserving groups (e.g. pre-school children) are not excluded. In summary, food distribution systems are most likely be a sound policy response where some or all of the following characteristics are present: \u00a7 Societal, economic or cultural factors (such as lack of gender equality) make some groups especially vulnerable to malnutrition; \u00a7 Where there is a cycle of malnutrition, passing from malnourished mother, to low-birth weight baby, through stunted child; \u00a7 Where infrastructure exists to provide a successful scheme; \u00a7 Where there exist other important objectives (such as low female participation in education) which could be met through e.g. a school feeding programme; \u00a7 Where resources are so limited as to justify tight targeting on the most needy; OR to supplement a general distribution system where certain groups are especially vulnerable; 122 \u00a7 Additionally, supplementary feeding programmes are an important part of any response to a crisis which threatens hunger and/ or starvation. How to design and implement a successful supplementary feeding system A key first step in designing any successful supplementary feeding system is to identify who the target recipients should be. The Lancet (2008) has recently argued that such efforts should be focused only on maternal and infant feeding schemes, because these have the greatest direct impact on nutritional outcomes. However, Radhakrisnan (2004) noted that nutritional outcomes need to be judged over longer time periods \u2013 for example, she and fellow researchers found that women in Guatemala who had received supplementary feeding programmes as children had higher birth weight babies \u2013 even when they did not receive extra food when pregnant. School feeding may also achieve significant non-nutritional outcomes in terms of educational attainment and, especially, girls\u2019 participation in schooling. These may have longer term impacts on hunger (higher earning potential for all; and educated girls are less likely to marry young and have large families). But there have been few studies to quantify these benefits. Either way, feeding some combination of mothers, children and babies is likely to provide the greatest benefits because it breaks the cycle of hunger. Nevertheless, it may be beneficial to include the elderly, sick and infirm on simple humanitarian grounds, particularly as they are unable to participate in some alternative schemes such as food for work. This may also free up women carers to participate in other activities. Once the target group has been decided on, there is the challenge of identifying target recipients. For school feeding programmes this is relatively straightforward. It is more difficult to identify and reach pregnant and nursing mothers, babies and pre-schoolers, especially in areas where literacy and access to maternal health services are low. Pre-schoolers are notoriously hard to reach \u2013 and some donors will not support programmes which target this (very vulnerable) group (Rajivan 2008). Moreover, targeting supplementary programmes only at the malnourished can in itself be damaging (Rogers and Coates 2002) as it means that malnutrition is treated, rather than prevented, and families can even be incentivised to under-feed children if this results in the provision of free food (ibid). Instead, a programme like Tamil Nadu\u2019s is available to all children, which helps break down cast and class barriers (though does little to keep the costs of the programme down) (Raji van, 2008). In designing the programme, there is a balance to be struck between the costs and benefits of providing cooked versus dry rations. Dry rations are much more likely to be stolen, or to be brought home for consumption by other family members (or even livestock). For this reason cooked food is usually preferred. However, as the Chhatisgarh experience shows,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5b66bf81-ca88-4977-8421-9eb61733b74f": {"__data__": {"id_": "5b66bf81-ca88-4977-8421-9eb61733b74f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Rising Food and Fuel Prices in Asia and the Pacific: Causes, Impacts and Policy Responses", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1b934c6417f30f0c206e3f7dfa3070cb1e9a837aef191688a7c2afa6b274db9c"}, "3": {"node_id": "578e9e31-3189-40b9-bd4b-973c7fdbb8b1", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/rising-food-and-fuel-prices-asia-and-pacific-causes-impacts-and-policy-responses", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b0b67be10b0e6ac5c8c53407442c979c2972e66df14d1a791f5e3c45e9272c3d"}}, "hash": "cfe0974652fe5398190f9f2c1099f750ebfffb8c3f701cdcc7abd83892d9b000", "text": "without adequate staffing and facilities, the pressure of cooking school meals may be excessive, and may in fact make education less rather than more effective. Moreover Bangladesh\u2019s experience shows that even dry rations can provide some positive benefits. Where possible, however, the ideal is a well staffed and resourced cooked meal, with enough variety to be enticing to children. Rajiva n (2008) has documented that in Rajasthan higher caste children declined to eat the gruel provided through the mid-day meal scheme, with the result that caste and economic inequities were highlighted. Rajivan (ibid) also notes that, whilst school feeding may be effective in meeting educational objectives, it cannot substitute for the quality of teaching. It is therefore important that the primary objective of the programme is recognized to be nutritional; if educational objectives are to be met as well, the school feeding must form part of a coherent educational strategy. Benefits from supplementary feeding programmes can be maximized if they can be combined (through fortification or complementary provision) with the provision of supplements and medicine s, and if they are accompanied with a campaign to educate people about good nutrition. This latter can help prevent parents from giving the children less food (because they know they will be fed at school). 123 Finally, it is important that participants in the scheme are regularly monitored in order to ascertain whether expected benefits are being realized. Supplementary feeding programmes are expensive, and often designed to be longer-lived than other food safety net schemes. It is important therefore that they are effectively evaluated. References The Lancet 2008 What works? Interventions for maternal and child undernutrition and survival Maternal and Child Undernutrition 3, January 2008 Ramakrishnan, Usha, 2004, \u2018Nutrition and low birth weight: from res earch to practice\u2019 American Journal of Clinical Nutrition, Vol. 79, No. 1, 17-21, January 2004 Radjivan, Anu, 2008 (forthcoming) Targeted Interventions against Hunger: A Case for Preschool and School Feeding UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo Rogers, Beatrice Lorge and Coates, J., Social Safety Net Primer Series: Food-Based Safety Nets and Related Programs\u2019 June 2002 World Bank Institute Rogers, Beatrice Lorge, Coates, J. and Osei, A. K. WFP Bangladesh School Feeding Programme Mid Term Evaluation Final Report World Food Programme December 30 2004 124 Annex Tables Table : Scenario Analysis - Impact of Higher Cereals Prices on the Poor and Rich households in China Bottom 20% Q2 Q3 Q4 Top 20 % I. Base scenario Total household income (LCU) 3,646 6,024 8,167 11,051 20,174 Total consumption expenditure (LCU) 3,399 5,096 6,498 8,346 13,796 Consumption expenditure as % of income 93.2 84.6 79.6 75.5 68.4 Food costs as %